a Ilbo]] | language= ko | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200308133034/https://newslibrary.naver.com/viewer/index.nhn?articleId=1980020100209201020&edtNo=2&printCount=1&publishDate=1980-02-01&officeId=00020&pageNo=1&printNo=17945&publishType=00020 | archive-date= 2020-03-08 | access-date= 2020-03-06 | ref= DongA_Ilbo | df= dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Segye_Ilbo\">{{cite news | date= 2012-12-11 | title= [\ud55c\uad6d\uc758 \ubb34\uae30 \uc774\uc57c\uae30] \u97d3 \uccab \uc870\ub9bd\uc804\ucc28, 105\u339c \ud3ec\ud0c4\uc5d0\u2026\uad00\ud1b5\ub825 '\uc73c\ub738' | trans-title= [Korea's Weapons Story] \u97d3 First Tank, 105mm Shell\u2026 Penetration 'Best' | url= https://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LSD&mid=sec&sid1=100&oid=022&aid=0002470199 | url-status= live | work= [[Segye Ilbo]] | language= ko | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200308133735/https://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LSD&mid=sec&sid1=100&oid=022&aid=0002470199 | archive-date= 2020-03-08 | access-date= 2020-03-06 | ref= Segye_Ilbo | df= dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"2011_Janes\">{{cite magazine |url= http://articles.janes.com/articles/Janes-Military-Vehicles-and-Logistics/Rheinmetall-Landsysteme-Keiler-armoured-mineclearing-vehicle-Germany.html |title= Rheinmetall Landsysteme Keiler armoured mineclearing vehicle (Germany), Mine warfare equipment |date= 2009-11-26 |work = Jane's Military Vehicles and Logistics |publisher= [[Jane's Information Group]] |language= en |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120820152126/http://articles.janes.com/articles/Janes-Military-Vehicles-and-Logistics/Rheinmetall-Landsysteme-Keiler-armoured-mineclearing-vehicle-Germany.html |archive-date= 2012-08-20 |url-status= dead |access-date= 2020-03-08 |ref= 2011_Janes |df= dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"TankNut\">{{cite web |url= https://tanknutdave.com/the-german-m48a2ga2-tank-a-super-m48-tank-upgrades/ |title= The German M48A2GA2 Tank & Super M48 Tank upgrades |date= 2012-02-17 |website= tanknutdave.com |language= en |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180909053703/https://tanknutdave.com/the-german-m48a2ga2-tank-a-super-m48-tank-upgrades/ |archive-date= 2018-09-09 |url-status= live |access-date= 2020-03-08 |ref= TankNut |df= dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Pike_Pakistan\">{{cite web |url= https://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/pakistan/army-equipment.htm |title= Pakistan Army Equipment |last= Pike |first= John |website= globalsecurity.org |publisher= [[GlobalSecurity.org]] |language= en |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180612235504/https://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/pakistan/army-equipment.htm |archive-date= 2018-06-12 |url-status= live |access-date= 2020-03-08 |ref= Pike_Pakistan |df= dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"1998_Zaloga\">{{cite book |last1= Zaloga |first1= Steven J. |author-link= Steven Zaloga |date= 1998 |title= Tank Battles of the Mid East Wars: (2) The Wars of 1973 to the Present |url= https://archive.org/details/tankbattlesmidea00zalo_215 |url-status= live |series= Armor at War |language= en |edition= First |publisher= Concord Publications |isbn= 978-9623616133 |oclc= 464148452 |ol= OL27090763M |access-date= 2020-03-08 |via= [[Internet Archive]] |url-access= limited |ref= 1998_Zaloga |df= dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"2006_Kassis\">{{cite book |last1= Kassis |first1= Samer |date= 2006 |title= 30 ans de v\u00e9hicules militaires au Liban, 1975-2005 |trans-title= 30 years of military vehicles in Lebanon, 1975-2005 |language= fr |publisher= Elite groupe |isbn= 978-9953007052 |oclc= 496027616 |ref= 2006_Kassis |df= dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book |last1= Higgins |first1= David R. |date= 2016-01-19 |title= M48 Patton vs Centurion: Indo-Pakistani War 1965 |series= Duel |language= en |volume= Book 71 |others= Illustrated by Johnny Shumate and Alan Gilliland |edition= First |publisher= [[Osprey Publishing]] |isbn= 978-1472810922 |oclc= 947095346 |ref= 2016_Higgins |df= dmy-all}}\n*{{cite book | last1 = Rabinovich | first1 = Abraham | author-link = Abraham Rabinovich | date = 1972 | title = The Battle for Jerusalem: June 5-7, 1967 | language = en | edition = 1st | publisher = [[Jewish Publication Society|Jewish Publication Society of America]] | asin = B0006C6MHM | isbn = 978-9657287071 | oclc = 947062697 | ref = 1972_Rabinovich | df = dmy-all}}\n* {{cite book | last1 = Zaloga | first1 = Steven J. | author-link = Steven Zaloga | date = 2000-11-25 | title = M26/M46 Pershing Tank 1943\u201353 (New Vanguard) | url = https://archive.org/details/mmpershingtank00zalo | url-status = live | series = New Vanguard (Book 35) | language = en | others = Illustrated by Tony Bryan and Jim Laurier | edition = 1st | publisher = [[Osprey Publishing]] | isbn = 978-1841762029 | ol = OL8922180M | access-date = 2020-03-02 | url-access = limited | ref = 2000_M24_M46 | df = dmy-all}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|M48 tanks}}\n*[http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/systems/ground/m48.htm GlobalSecurity.org: M48 Patton]\n*[http://www.memorialmuseum.org/displays/tanks/item/m48-patton M48 Patton] at U.S. Veterans Memorial Museum\n*{{Internet Archive short film | gov.archives.arc.2569562 | Birth of a Tank - 1950's United States Army Educational Documentary }}\n\n{{US tanks|style=wide}}\n{{Cold War tanks|style=wide}}\n\n[[Category:Cold War tanks of the United States]]\n[[Category:Post\u2013Cold War main battle tanks]]\n[[Category:Medium tanks of the Cold War]]\n[[Category:Medium tanks of the United States]]\n[[Category:Military vehicles introduced in the 1950s]]\n", "name_user": "CIB2008 OEF", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M48_Patton"}
{"title_page": "Feng Menglong", "text_new": "{{Chinese|t={{linktext|\u99ae|\u5922|\u9f8d}}|s={{linktext|\u51af|\u68a6|\u9f99}}|p=F\u00e9ng M\u00e8ngl\u00f3ng|w=F\u00eang<sup>2</sup> M\u00eang<sup>4</sup>-lung<sup>2</sup>}}\n{{Chinese name|[[Feng (surname)|Feng]]}}\n'''Feng Menglong''' (1574&ndash;1646), courtesy names '''Youlong''' (\u7336\u9f8d), '''Gongyu''' (\u516c\u9b5a), '''Ziyou''' (\u5b50\u7336), or '''Eryou''' (\u8033\u7336),<ref>Feng Menglong was also known by a variety of pseudonyms or art names (\u865f, ''hao''), including \u9f8d\u5b50\u7336, \u58a8\u61a8\u9f4b\u4e3b\u4eba, \u5433\u4e0b\u8a5e\u5974, \u59d1\u8607\u8a5e\u5974, \u524d\u5468\u67f1\u53f2, \u9867\u66f2\u6563\u4eba, and \u7da0\u5929\u9928\u4e3b\u4eba.</ref> was a Chinese historian, novelist, and poet of the late [[Ming Dynasty]]. He was born in Changzhou County (\u9577\u6d32\u7e23, not [[Changzhou]]), now part of [[Suzhou]], in [[Jiangsu]] Province.<ref>Yenna Wu. ''Vernacular Stories.''  in [[V. Mair]], (ed.),  ''[[The Columbia History of Chinese Literature]]''  (NY: [[Columbia University Press]],  2001). pp. 597-605.</ref>\n\nFeng was born into a scholar-bureaucrat gentry household, where he and his brothers Feng Menggui (\u99ae\u5922\u6842) and Feng Mengxiong (\u99ae\u5922\u718a) were educated in the classics and the traditional arts of the gentleman. He and his brothers, all well-known as accomplished writers, artists, and poets, became known collectively as the \"Three Fengs of the Wu Area\" (\u5433\u4e0b\u4e09\u99ae).  In spite of his literary talent and his zeal for scholarship from a young age, Feng sat the imperial civil service examinations many times without success, eventually giving up and making a living as a tutor and teacher.   \n\nIn 1626, he narrowly avoided punishment after being implicated as an associate of Zhou Shunchang (\u5468\u9806\u660c), who was framed and purged by the corrupt eunuch [[Wei Zhongxian]].  Appalled by the injustice, he resolved to complete his trilogy of vernacular Chinese short story collections: ''Stories to Instruct the World'', ''Stories to Caution the World'', and ''Stories to Awaken the World''  (\u55bb\u4e16\u660e\u8a00, \u8b66\u4e16\u901a\u8a00, and \u9192\u4e16\u6046\u8a00). \n\nIn recognition of his reputation as a writer, Feng was finally awarded the ''[[Imperial examination|gongsheng]]'' degree in 1630 at the age of fifty-seven.  In the subsequent year, he received his first government post as instructor of Dantu County (\u4e39\u5f92\u7e23, today [[Zhenjiang]], Jiangsu).  In 1634, he was appointed magistrate of [[Shouning County|Shouning]] County (\u58fd\u5be7) in Fujian.  During his tenure, he became regarded as a morally upright and diligent administrator.  He retired in 1638.\n\nIn 1644, the Ming state was thrown into turmoil by the sacking of Beijing by [[Li Zicheng]]'s rebel army and invasion by the Manchu Qing forces.  At the age of seventy-one, he published the ''Grand Proposals for National Rejuvenation'' (\u4e2d\u8208\u5049\u7565) to inspire his countrymen to repel the invaders.  He died in despair in 1646 as the Ming dynasty continued to collapse.  Some works indicate or imply that he was killed by Qing soldiers.\n\nFeng's literary output consisted of the compilation of histories and local gazettes, the retelling of folktales and stories from antiquity in the form of short stories and plays, and the authorship of vernacular Chinese novels. Two of his noteworthy works are the ''Qing Shi'' (''History of Love'', \u60c5\u53f2), an anthology of classical love stories, and the [[shenmo]] novel ''[[Pingyao Zhuan]]''. In 1620 he published the ''[[Illustrious Words to Instruct the World]]'' (\u55bb\u4e16\u660e\u8a00 Yushi Mingyan), or ''Stories Old and New'', the first part of his well-known trilogy.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=tnGASn7jJsIC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Feng+Menglong&hl=en&ei=Hg9DTsLtC8eHsAKo8_3HCQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&sqi=2&ved=0CDAQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Stories old and new: a Ming dynasty collection''.]  [[University of Washington Press]]</ref>\n\nFeng was a proponent of the school of [[Li Zhi (Ming Dynasty)|Li Zhi]], which supported the importance of human feelings and behavior in literature. He is frequently associated with [[Ling Mengchu]], author of [[Slapping the Table in Amazement]],<ref>http://www.washington.edu/uwpress/search/books/LINSLA.html</ref> a two-part collection of entertaining vernacular tales.\n\n==Writing style==\nFeng Menglong was in love with a famous prostitute when he was young. Unfortunately, Feng Menglong was not able to afford to redeem his lover out. At the end, his lover was redeemed by a merchant, and they had to leave each other. Feng Menglong suffered from pain and desperation due to the separation, and he expressed his sorrow through poems. This experience influenced the way he portrayed female characters in his stories. In fact, Feng Menglong was one of the few authors who portrayed female as being strong and intelligent; and this is different from other authors, where they tended to ignore the importance of female\u2019s position. The female characters in Feng Menglong\u2019s stories were portrayed as brave and bright when dealing with different situations. For instance, in his story Wan Xiuniang Takes Revenge Through Toy Pavilions from Jing Shi Tong Yan, Wan Xiuniang showed her braveness during her tough times, and she was able to escape using her intelligence. Other female characters, such as Du Shi-niang and Qu Xiuxiu, are example to show Feng Menglong\u2019s respectful and sympathetic portrayal of female characters.\n\nFeng Menglong also expressed his attitudes towards society through his works, which were heavily influenced by his interactions with officialdom and the Chinese literati. Feng Menglong became the magistrate of Shouning near the end of his life, in his sixties. During his appointment, he sought to correct injustices and hoped to build up a reputation as an humble and upright official. Unfortunately, his efforts were frustrated by the widespread corruption of the late Ming dynasty (a theme also treated extensively in other contemporaneous works, such as Zhang Yingyu's ''[[The Book of Swindles]]'' (ca. 1617)<ref>Zhang Yingyu, ''The Book of Swindles: Selections from a Late Ming Collection'' (New York: Columbia University Press, 2017).</ref>); bribery and extortion were common bureaucratic behaviors, and themes of official malfeasance figure in many of Feng's stories. Realizing that atmosphere of corruption could not be easily changed, Feng Menglong conveyed his discontent and patriotism through words. Each character of his stories has strong and direct characteristics: there is a clear morality line drawn between \u201cgood\u201d and \u201cbad\u201d. Moreover, the meaning behind the stories explores the social issues during Ming Dynasty. For instance, the stories of \"The White Maiden Locked for Eternity in [[Leifeng Pagoda]]\" and \"The Young Lady Gives the Young Man a Gift of Money\" from ''Stories to Caution the World'' express the idea of how women pursued their freedom and happiness under a patriarchal society.\n\nDuring his tenure as magistrate of Shouning, Feng learned of the local practice of [[Female infanticide in China|drowning female infants]] in the river.  He authored the ''Public Notice on the Prohibition of the Drowning of Daughters'' (\u7981\u6eba\u5973\u544a\u793a) to appeal to parents not to carry out what he viewed as an abhorrent custom and provide for punishments for infanticidal parents and rewards for those taking in abandoned children.<ref>An excerpt:\n \n\u201c\u00b7\u00b7\u00b7\u00b7\u00b7\u00b7\u4e00\u822c\u5341\u6708\u61f7\u80ce\uff0c\u5403\u76e1\u8f9b\u82e6\uff0c\u4e0d\u8ad6\u7537\u5973\uff0c\u7e3d\u662f\u9aa8\u8840\uff0c\u4f55\u5fcd\u6df9\u68c4\u3002 \u70ba\u7236\u8005\u4f60\u81ea\u60f3\uff0c\u82e5\u4e0d\u6536\u5973\uff0c\u4f60\u59bb\u5f9e\u4f55\u800c\u4f86\uff1f\u70ba\u6bcd\u8005\u4f60\u81ea\u60f3\uff0c\u82e5\u4e0d\u6536\u5973\uff0c\u4f60\u8eab\u5f9e\u4f55\u800c\u6d3b\uff1f\u6cc1\u4e14\u751f\u7537\u672a\u5fc5\u5b5d\u9806\uff0c\u751f\u5973\u672a\u5fc5\u5fe4\u9006\u3002\u00b7\u00b7\u00b7\u00b7\u00b7\u00b7\u201d\n\n... Ordinarily, you carry a fetus for ten [lunar] months and endure an ordeal; regardless of gender, it is still your flesh and blood, how can you bear to drown and discard it?  If girls were not kept, fathers should ask yourselves, where would your wife have come from?  Likewise, mothers should ask yourselves, how could your own life have continued?  Moreover, boys are not necessarily filial, and girls are not necessarily disobedient....</ref>\n\n==Works==\n*''[[Stories to Awaken the World]]''<ref>http://www.washington.edu/uwpress/search/books/FENST3.html</ref>\n*''[[Stories to Caution the World]]''<ref>http://www.washington.edu/uwpress/search/books/FENSTO.html</ref>\n*''[[Illustrious Words to Instruct the World|Stories to Instruct the World]]'', also known as ''Gujin Xiaoshuo'' (\"Stories Old and New\") (ca. 1620), also known as ''Yushi Mingyan'' (\u55bb\u4e16\u660e\u8a00) (\"Illustrious Words to Instruct the World\") selections translated by Cyril Birch, ''Stories from a Ming Collection: Translations of Chinese Short Stories Published in the Seventeenth Century'' (Bloomington: Indiana University Press,  1959; rpr New York: Grove).\n*''[[Pingyao Zhuan]]''\n*''Qing Shi''\n* Yang Shuihu, Yang Yunqin, tr., ''Stories Old and New: A Ming Dynasty Collection'' (Seattle: University of Washington Press, 2000).(A complete translation of ''Gujin Xiaoshuo'').<ref>http://www.washington.edu/uwpress/search/books/FENSTC.html</ref>\n* ''The Oil Vendor and the Courtesan Tales from the Ming Dynasty.'' (New York: Welcome Rain,  2007). Translated by T. Wang and C. Chen.   ISBN\n* ''[[Chronicles of the Eastern Zhou Kingdoms]]''\n*''Public Notice on the Prohibition of the Drowning of Daughters''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://zh.wikisource.org/zh/%E7%A6%81%E6%BA%BA%E5%A5%B3%E5%91%8A%E7%A4%BA|title=\u7981\u6eba\u5973\u544a\u793a|last=Feng|first=Menglong|date=1634|website=Wikisource}}</ref>\n*''Shan'ge'', a collection of songs. An English translation by {{ill|\u014cki Yasushi|ja|\u5927\u6728\u5eb7}} is included in ''[[Shan'ge, the \"Mountain Songs\"]]''. \u014cki also translated the songs into Japanese, and Cornelia T\u00f6pelmann did work towards a German translation.<ref>{{cite journal |last=McLaren |first=Anne E. |date=July 2012 |title= Shan'ge, the mountain songs: love songs in Ming China|work=[[International Journal of Asian Studies]] |publisher= |publication-place= |volume=9|issue=2|page=231-240 |url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/international-journal-of-asian-studies/article/emotion-and-the-language-of-intimacy-in-ming-china-the-shange-of-feng-menglong/71AB36051A1077DDF9464A6AF8196A27 |accessdate= |isbn= |issn= |oclc= |doi=10.1017/S1479591412000046}} - CITED: p. 232.</ref>\n**{{cite book|author=\u014cki, Yasushi|authorlink=\u014cki Yasushi|title=Fu Boryu \u2018sanka\u2019 no kenkyu: Chugoku Mindai no tsuzoku kayo|script-title=ja:\u99ae\u5922\u9f8d\u300e\u5c71\u6b4c\u300f\u306e\u7814\u7a76: \u4e2d\u56fd\u660e\u4ee3\u306e\u901a\u4fd7\u6b4c\u8b21|place=Tokyo|publisher=[[Keiso Shobo]]|year=2003}}\n**{{cite book|title=Shan ko. Von Feng Meng Lung. Eine Volksliedersammlung aus der Ming zeit|place=[[Wiesbaden]]|publisher=[[Franz Steiner Verlag]]|year=1973}}\n\n==In popular culture==\nSinger [[Yan Weiwen]] stars as Feng Menglong in the 2017 biographical film ''Feng Menglong's Legend'' (\u99ae\u5922\u9f8d\u50b3\u5947).\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Owen, Stephen, \"Vernacular Stories: Feng Meng-long and Lang-xian,\" in Stephen Owen, ed. ''An Anthology of Chinese Literature: Beginnings to 1911''. New York: [[W. W. Norton]], 1997. [http://courses.washington.edu/chin463/OwenDuTenth.pdf p. 834-855] ([https://www.webcitation.org/6PoCPwoqz Archive]), [http://courses.washington.edu/chin463/OwenCensorXue.pdf p. 856-879] ([https://www.webcitation.org/6PoUSvBU2 Archive]).<!--Revealed on two pages: http://courses.washington.edu/chin463/Schedule.html https://www.webcitation.org/6PmyPFX5I, and http://courses.washington.edu/chin463/ https://www.webcitation.org/6PmyNNugV-->\n\n==External links==\n* {{Gutenberg author |id=Feng,+Menglong | name=Menglong Feng}}\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Menglong Feng}}\n* [http://www.angelfire.com/ns/pingyaozhuan/index.html PING YAO ZHUAN: The Sorcerers' Revolt, online English translation]\n\n{{3Y2P}}\n{{Ming Dynasty historians}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Feng, Menglong}}\n\n\n[[Category:1574 births]]\n[[Category:1645 deaths]]\n[[Category:17th-century Chinese historians]]\n[[Category:17th-century Chinese writers]]\n[[Category:Chinese male novelists]]\n[[Category:Chinese male short story writers]]\n[[Category:Historians from Jiangsu]]\n[[Category:Ming dynasty historians]]\n[[Category:Ming dynasty novelists]]\n[[Category:Ming dynasty poets]]\n[[Category:Ming dynasty short story writers]]\n[[Category:Poets from Jiangsu]]\n[[Category:Short story writers from Jiangsu]]\n[[Category:The Three Sui Quash the Demons' Revolt]]\n[[Category:Writers from Suzhou]]\n", "text_old": "{{Chinese|t={{linktext|\u99ae|\u5922|\u9f8d}}|s={{linktext|\u51af|\u68a6|\u9f99}}|p=F\u00e9ng M\u00e8ngl\u00f3ng|w=F\u00eang<sup>2</sup> M\u00eang<sup>4</sup>-lung<sup>2</sup>}}\n{{Chinese name|[[Feng (surname)|Feng]]}}\n'''Feng Menglong''' (1574&ndash;1646), courtesy names '''Youlong''' (\u7336\u9f8d), '''Gongyu''' (\u516c\u9b5a), '''Ziyou''' (\u5b50\u7336), or '''Eryou''' (\u8033\u7336),<ref>Feng Menglong was also known by a variety of pseudonyms or art names (\u865f, ''hao''), including \u9f8d\u5b50\u7336, \u58a8\u61a8\u9f4b\u4e3b\u4eba, \u5433\u4e0b\u8a5e\u5974, \u59d1\u8607\u8a5e\u5974, \u524d\u5468\u67f1\u53f2, \u9867\u66f2\u6563\u4eba, and \u7da0\u5929\u9928\u4e3b\u4eba.</ref> was a Chinese historian, novelist, and poet of the late [[Ming Dynasty]]. He was born in Changzhou County (\u9577\u6d32\u7e23, not [[Changzhou]]), now part of [[Suzhou]], in [[Jiangsu]] Province.<ref>Yenna Wu. ''Vernacular Stories.''  in [[V. Mair]], (ed.),  ''[[The Columbia History of Chinese Literature]]''  (NY: [[Columbia University Press]],  2001). pp. 597-605.</ref>\n\nFeng was born into a scholar-bureaucrat gentry household, where he and his brothers Feng Menggui (\u99ae\u5922\u6842) and Feng Mengxiong (\u99ae\u5922\u718a) were educated in the classics and the traditional arts of the gentleman. He and his brothers, all well-known as accomplished writers, artists, and poets, became known collectively as the \"Three Fengs of the Wu Area\" (\u5433\u4e0b\u4e09\u99ae).  In spite of his literary talent and his zeal for scholarship from a young age, Feng sat the imperial civil service examinations many times without success, eventually giving up and making a living as a tutor and teacher.   \n\nIn 1626, he narrowly avoided punishment after being implicated as an associate of Zhou Shunchang (\u5468\u9806\u660c), who was framed and purged by the corrupt eunuch [[Wei Zhongxian]].  Appalled by the injustice, he resolved to complete his trilogy of vernacular Chinese short story collections: ''Stories to Instruct the World'', ''Stories to Caution the World'', and ''Stories to Awaken the World''  (\u55bb\u4e16\u660e\u8a00, \u8b66\u4e16\u901a\u8a00, and \u9192\u4e16\u6046\u8a00). \n\nIn recognition of his reputation as a writer, Feng was finally awarded the ''[[Imperial examination|gongsheng]]'' degree in 1630 at the age of fifty-seven.  In the subsequent year, he received his first government post as instructor of Dantu County (\u4e39\u5f92\u7e23, today [[Zhenjiang]], Jiangsu).  In 1634, he was appointed magistrate of [[Shouning County|Shouning]] County (\u58fd\u5be7) in Fujian.  During his tenure, he became regarded as a morally upright and diligent administrator.  He retired in 1638.\n\nIn 1644, the Ming state was thrown into turmoil by the sacking of Beijing by [[Li Zicheng]]'s rebel army and invasion by the Manchu Qing forces.  At the age of seventy-one, he published the ''Grand Proposals for National Rejuvenation'' (\u4e2d\u8208\u5049\u7565) to inspire his countrymen to repel the invaders.  He died in despair in 1646 as the Ming dynasty continued to collapse.  Some works indicate or imply that he was killed by Qing soldiers.\n\nFeng's literary output consisted of the compilation of histories and local gazettes, the retelling of folktales and stories from antiquity in the form of short stories and plays, and the authorship of vernacular Chinese novels. Two of his noteworthy works are the ''Qing Shi'' (''History of Love'', \u60c5\u53f2), an anthology of classical love stories, and the [[shenmo]] novel ''[[Pingyao Zhuan]]''. In 1620 he published the ''[[Illustrious Words to Instruct the World]]'' (\u55bb\u4e16\u660e\u8a00 Yushi Mingyan), or ''Stories Old and New'', the first part of his well-known trilogy.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=tnGASn7jJsIC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Feng+Menglong&hl=en&ei=Hg9DTsLtC8eHsAKo8_3HCQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&sqi=2&ved=0CDAQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Stories old and new: a Ming dynasty collection''.]  [[University of Washington Press]]</ref>\n\nFeng was a proponent of the school of [[Li Zhi (Ming Dynasty)|Li Zhi]], which supported the importance of human feelings and behavior in literature. He is frequently associated with [[Ling Mengchu]], author of [[Slapping the Table in Amazement]],<ref>http://www.washington.edu/uwpress/search/books/LINSLA.html</ref> a two-part collection of entertaining vernacular tales.\n\n==Writing style==\nFeng Menglong was in love with a famous prostitute when he was young. Unfortunately, Feng Menglong was not able to afford to redeem his lover out. At the end, his lover was redeemed by a merchant, and they had to leave each other. Feng Menglong suffered from pain and desperation due to the separation, and he expressed his sorrow through poems. This experience influenced the way he portrayed female characters in his stories. In fact, Feng Menglong was one of the few authors who portrayed female as being strong and intelligent; and this is different from other authors, where they tended to ignore the importance of female\u2019s position. The female characters in Feng Menglong\u2019s stories were portrayed as brave and bright when dealing with different situations. For instance, in his story Wan Xiuniang Takes Revenge Through Toy Pavilions from Jing Shi Tong Yan, Wan Xiuniang showed her braveness during her tough times, and she was able to escape using her intelligence. Other female characters, such as Du Shi-niang and Qu Xiuxiu, are example to show Feng Menglong\u2019s respectful and sympathetic portrayal of female characters.\n\nFeng Menglong also expressed his attitudes towards society through his works, which were heavily influenced by his interactions with officialdom and the Chinese literati. Feng Menglong became the magistrate of Shouning near the end of his life, in his sixties. During his appointment, he sought to correct injustices and hoped to build up a reputation as an humble and upright official. Unfortunately, his efforts were frustrated by the widespread corruption of the late Ming dynasty (a theme also treated extensively in other contemporaneous works, such as Zhang Yingyu's ''[[The Book of Swindles]]'' (ca. 1617)<ref>Zhang Yingyu, ''The Book of Swindles: Selections from a Late Ming Collection'' (New York: Columbia University Press, 2017).</ref>); bribery and extortion were common bureaucratic behaviors, and themes of official malfeasance figure in many of Feng's stories. Realizing that atmosphere of corruption could not be easily changed, Feng Menglong conveyed his discontent and patriotism through words. Each character of his stories has strong and direct characteristics: there is a clear morality line drawn between \u201cgood\u201d and \u201cbad\u201d. Moreover, the meaning behind the stories explores the social issues during Ming Dynasty. For instance, the stories of \"The White Maiden Locked for Eternity in [[Leifeng Pagoda]]\" and \"The Young Lady Gives the Young Man a Gift of Money\" from ''Stories to Caution the World'' express the idea of how women pursued their freedom and happiness under a patriarchal society.\n\nDuring his tenure as magistrate of Shouning, Feng learned of the local practice of [[Female infanticide in China|drowning female infants]] in the river.  He authored the ''Public Notice on the Prohibition of the Drowning of Daughters'' (\u7981\u6eba\u5973\u544a\u793a) to appeal to parents not to carry out what he viewed as an abhorrent custom and provide for punishments for infanticidal parents and rewards for those taking in abandoned children.<ref>An excerpt:\n \n\u201c\u00b7\u00b7\u00b7\u00b7\u00b7\u00b7\u4e00\u822c\u5341\u6708\u61f7\u80ce\uff0c\u5403\u76e1\u8f9b\u82e6\uff0c\u4e0d\u8ad6\u7537\u5973\uff0c\u7e3d\u662f\u9aa8\u8840\uff0c\u4f55\u5fcd\u6df9\u68c4\u3002 \u70ba\u7236\u8005\u4f60\u81ea\u60f3\uff0c\u82e5\u4e0d\u6536\u5973\uff0c\u4f60\u59bb\u5f9e\u4f55\u800c\u4f86\uff1f\u70ba\u6bcd\u8005\u4f60\u81ea\u60f3\uff0c\u82e5\u4e0d\u6536\u5973\uff0c\u4f60\u8eab\u5f9e\u4f55\u800c\u6d3b\uff1f\u6cc1\u4e14\u751f\u7537\u672a\u5fc5\u5b5d\u9806\uff0c\u751f\u5973\u672a\u5fc5\u5fe4\u9006\u3002\u00b7\u00b7\u00b7\u00b7\u00b7\u00b7\u201d\n\n... Ordinarily, you carry a fetus for ten [lunar] months and endure an ordeal; regardless of gender, it is still your flesh and blood, how can you bear to drown and discard it?  If girls were not kept, fathers should ask yourselves, where would your wife have come from?  Likewise, mothers should ask yourselves, how could your own life have continued?  Moreover, boys are not necessarily filial, and girls are not necessarily disobedient....</ref>\n\n==Works==\n*''[[Stories to Awaken the World]]''<ref>http://www.washington.edu/uwpress/search/books/FENST3.html</ref>\n*''[[Stories to Caution the World]]''<ref>http://www.washington.edu/uwpress/search/books/FENSTO.html</ref>\n*''[[Illustrious Words to Instruct the World|Stories to Instruct the World]]'', also known as ''Gujin Xiaoshuo'' (\"Stories Old and New\") (ca. 1620), also known as ''Yushi Mingyan'' (\u55bb\u4e16\u660e\u8a00) (\"Illustrious Words to Instruct the World\") selections translated by Cyril Birch, ''Stories from a Ming Collection: Translations of Chinese Short Stories Published in the Seventeenth Century'' (Bloomington: Indiana University Press,  1959; rpr New York: Grove).\n*''[[Pingyao Zhuan]]''\n*''Qing Shi''\n* Yang Shuihu, Yang Yunqin, tr., ''Stories Old and New: A Ming Dynasty Collection'' (Seattle: University of Washington Press, 2000).(A complete translation of ''Gujin Xiaoshuo'').<ref>http://www.washington.edu/uwpress/search/books/FENSTC.html</ref>\n* ''The Oil Vendor and the Courtesan Tales from the Ming Dynasty.'' (New York: Welcome Rain,  2007). Translated by T. Wang and C. Chen.   ISBN\n* ''[[Chronicles of the Eastern Zhou Kingdoms]]''\n*''Public Notice on the Prohibition of the Drowning of Daughters''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://zh.wikisource.org/zh/%E7%A6%81%E6%BA%BA%E5%A5%B3%E5%91%8A%E7%A4%BA|title=\u7981\u6eba\u5973\u544a\u793a|last=Feng|first=Menglong|date=1634|website=Wikisource}}</ref>\n*''Shan'ge'', a collection of songs. An English translation by {{ill|\u014cki Yasushi|ja|\u5927\u6728\u5eb7}} is included in ''[[Shan'ge, the \"Mountain Songs\"]]''. \u014cki also translated the songs into Japanese, and Cornelia T\u00f6pelmann wrote a German translation.<ref>{{cite journal |last=McLaren |first=Anne E. |date=July 2012 |title= Shan'ge, the mountain songs: love songs in Ming China|work=[[International Journal of Asian Studies]] |publisher= |publication-place= |volume=9|issue=2|page=231-240 |url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/international-journal-of-asian-studies/article/emotion-and-the-language-of-intimacy-in-ming-china-the-shange-of-feng-menglong/71AB36051A1077DDF9464A6AF8196A27 |accessdate= |isbn= |issn= |oclc= |doi=10.1017/S1479591412000046}} - CITED: p. 232.</ref>\n**{{cite book|author=\u014cki, Yasushi|authorlink=\u014cki Yasushi|title=Fu Boryu \u2018sanka\u2019 no kenkyu: Chugoku Mindai no tsuzoku kayo|script-title=ja:\u99ae\u5922\u9f8d\u300e\u5c71\u6b4c\u300f\u306e\u7814\u7a76: \u4e2d\u56fd\u660e\u4ee3\u306e\u901a\u4fd7\u6b4c\u8b21|place=Tokyo|publisher=[[Keiso Shobo]]|year=2003}}\n**{{cite book|title=Shan ko. Von Feng Meng Lung. Eine Volksliedersammlung aus der Ming zeit|place=[[Wiesbaden]]|publisher=[[Franz Steiner Verlag]]|year=1973}}\n\n==In popular culture==\nSinger [[Yan Weiwen]] stars as Feng Menglong in the 2017 biographical film ''Feng Menglong's Legend'' (\u99ae\u5922\u9f8d\u50b3\u5947).\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Owen, Stephen, \"Vernacular Stories: Feng Meng-long and Lang-xian,\" in Stephen Owen, ed. ''An Anthology of Chinese Literature: Beginnings to 1911''. New York: [[W. W. Norton]], 1997. [http://courses.washington.edu/chin463/OwenDuTenth.pdf p. 834-855] ([https://www.webcitation.org/6PoCPwoqz Archive]), [http://courses.washington.edu/chin463/OwenCensorXue.pdf p. 856-879] ([https://www.webcitation.org/6PoUSvBU2 Archive]).<!--Revealed on two pages: http://courses.washington.edu/chin463/Schedule.html https://www.webcitation.org/6PmyPFX5I, and http://courses.washington.edu/chin463/ https://www.webcitation.org/6PmyNNugV-->\n\n==External links==\n* {{Gutenberg author |id=Feng,+Menglong | name=Menglong Feng}}\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Menglong Feng}}\n* [http://www.angelfire.com/ns/pingyaozhuan/index.html PING YAO ZHUAN: The Sorcerers' Revolt, online English translation]\n\n{{3Y2P}}\n{{Ming Dynasty historians}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Feng, Menglong}}\n\n\n[[Category:1574 births]]\n[[Category:1645 deaths]]\n[[Category:17th-century Chinese historians]]\n[[Category:17th-century Chinese writers]]\n[[Category:Chinese male novelists]]\n[[Category:Chinese male short story writers]]\n[[Category:Historians from Jiangsu]]\n[[Category:Ming dynasty historians]]\n[[Category:Ming dynasty novelists]]\n[[Category:Ming dynasty poets]]\n[[Category:Ming dynasty short story writers]]\n[[Category:Poets from Jiangsu]]\n[[Category:Short story writers from Jiangsu]]\n[[Category:The Three Sui Quash the Demons' Revolt]]\n[[Category:Writers from Suzhou]]\n", "name_user": "WhisperToMe", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eWorks", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Feng_Menglong"}
{"title_page": "Cristiana Oprea", "text_new": "{{short description|Romanian rally driver|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox racing driver\n| name              = Cristiana Oprea\n| image             =\n| image_size        = \n| caption           = \n| nationality       = {{flagicon|ROU}}Romania\n| birth_name        = <!-- Only if different from name -->\n| birth_date        = {{Birth date and age|1992|03|11|df=y}}\n| birth_place       = \n| related to        = <!-- list of notable relatives with line breaks -->\n| current series    = European Rally Championship FIA ERC <br> DACIA Cup in the Romanian National Rally Championship\n| first year        = 2015\n| current team      = \n| car number        = \n| engine            = \n| crew chief        = \n| spotter           = <!-- Note: \"spotter\" and \"codriver\" share a field     -->\n| codriver          = Diana Ha\u021began\n| former teams      = \n| starts            = 23\n| wins              = \n| podiums           = 2\n| poles             = \n| fastest laps      = <!-- if known -->\n| best finish       = <!-- if a final championship placing has been recorded -->\n| year              = <!-- use piped link if season article exists -->\n| last finish       = \n| prev series       = <!-- previous series with line breaks -->\n| prev series years = \n| titles            = <!-- championship titles -->\n| title years       = \n| awards            = \n| award years       = \n| medaltemplates    = \n| updated           = \n}}\n'''Cristiana Oprea''' (born 11 March 1992) is a Romanian [[Rallying|rally]] driver. She is part of the very few ladies rally crews in Romania. Her career in rallying started in 2015, first as a codriver next to George Grigorescu, then as a driver in DACIA Cup, driving a Dacia Sandero 0.9 TCe.\n\nShe competes in the Romanian National Rally Championship and in the [[European Rally Championship]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fiaerc.com/oprea-all-set-for-dream-step-up-to-erc-in-rome/|title=OPREA ALL SET FOR DREAM STEP UP TO ERC IN ROME|last=FIA ERC|website=www.fiaerc.com|language=en|access-date=2019-09-23}}</ref> In July 2018 she and codriver Diana Ha\u021began became the first Romanian female rally crew in the last 50 years to compete in a foreign rally<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.agerpres.ro/sport/2018/07/17/auto-primul-echipaj-feminin-romanesc-din-ultimii-50-de-ani-la-un-raliu-in-afara-tarii--146346|title=Auto: Primul echipaj feminin rom\u00e2nesc din ultimii 50 de ani, la un raliu \u00een afara \u0163\u0103rii|last=AGERPRES|website=www.agerpres.ro|language=ro|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> (Rally Sliven, Bulgaria, a FIA [[European Rally Trophy]] event).\n\nIn July 2019 she and codriver Diana Ha\u021began became the first ladies crew to ever represent Romania in the FIA ERC European Rally Championship, at Rally di Roma Capitale, where they gained maximum points in the ERC Ladies Trophy standings driving a Peugeot 208 R2.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fiaerc.com/my-erc-debut-by-cristiana-oprea/|title=MY ERC DEBUT. BY CRISTIANA OPREA|last=FIA ERC|website=www.fiaerc.com|language=en|access-date=2019-09-23}}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\n\n=== Studies, career and motorsport debut ===\nOprea is a double graduate of the \"Ion Mincu\" University of Architecture and Urbanism in Bucharest. She studied Urban Planning (2010-2014) and Architecture (2011-2017), but she never worked in the field, wanting to follow her passion for cars.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.femeia.ro/bani-cariera/cristiana-oprea-imi-doresc-sa-reprezint-romania-la-campionatul-european-de-raliuri|title=Cristiana Oprea: \u00cemi doresc s\u0103 reprezint Rom\u00e2nia la Campionatul European de Raliuri|last=-|date=2018-12-13|website=Femeia.ro|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> In 2015 she was for a short while the PR of the Romanian Motorsport Federation, when she first took contact with the motorsport world. Her career in rallying started in 2015, first as a codriver next to George Grigorescu, Master of Sport and founder of the DACIA Cup series, then as a driver in DACIA Cup, driving a Dacia Sandero 0.9 TCe.\n\n==== Motorsport Excellence Centre Bucharest ====\nIn 2017, Oprea created the concept for a Motorsport Excellence Centre in Bucharest as an architecture graduation project.\n\n=== Racing career ===\nCristiana Oprea competed 2 full seasons, 2017 and 2018, in DACIA Cup,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cupadacia.ro/|title=Cupa DACIA|website=Cupa Dacia|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> part of the Romanian National Rally Championship. Her rookie season was 2017, when she completed 7 events driving a Dacia Sandero 0.9 TCe with Ioana Stan as a codriver. They finished on 6th place out of 9 rookie crew and on 12th place out of 18 crews enlisted overall in DACIA Cup. In 2018 she finished on the 5th place overall in DACIA Cup, marking the best result of a woman driver since 2007, when Alina Bunica competed.\n\nOprea first stepped on a podium at the beginning of 2019 season at Arge\u0219 Rally, when together with codriver Diana Ha\u021began took second place overall<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cupadacia.ro/2019/05/07/cristi-sugar-vlad-colceriu-castiga-prima-etapa-cristiana-oprea-diana-hategan-scriu-istorie-in-cupa-dacia-la-raliul-argesului/|title=Cristi Sugar/Vlad Colceriu c\u00e2\u0219tig\u0103 prima etap\u0103, Cristiana Oprea/Diana Ha\u021began scriu istorie \u00een Cupa DACIA la Raliul Arge\u0219ului|date=2019-05-07|website=Cupa Dacia|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> in DACIA Cup.\n\nIn July 2019 she and codriver Diana Ha\u021began became the first ladies crew to ever represent Romania in the FIA ERC European Rally Championship, at Rally di Roma Capitale, where they finished P8 in the highly competitive ERC3 class and gained maximum points in the ERC Ladies Trophy standings.\n\n=== Romanian Women in Motorsport platform ===\nOprea is the founder and administrator of \"Femei \u00een Motorsport\", a platform dedicated to promoting all women involved in Romanian motorsport, following the Women in Motorsport concept as defined by FIA.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://autostiri.ro/femei-motorsport-o-pagina-dedicata-promovarii-femeilor-implicate-automobilismul-si-motociclismul-din-romania/|title=Femei in motorsport, o pagina dedicata promov\u0103rii femeilor implicate \u00een automobilismul \u0219i motociclismul din Rom\u00e2nia|last=Strauti|first=Dan|date=2019-03-01|website=Autostiri.ro|language=ro-RO|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> \n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:Romanian rally drivers]]\n[[Category:Female rally drivers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Romanian rally driver|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox racing driver\n| name              = Cristiana Oprea\n| image             =\n| image_size        = \n| caption           = \n| nationality       = {{flagicon|ROU}}Romania\n| birth_name        = <!-- Only if different from name -->\n| birth_date        = {{Birth date and age|1992|03|11|df=y}}\n| birth_place       = \n| related to        = <!-- list of notable relatives with line breaks -->\n| current series    = European Rally Championship FIA ERC <br> DACIA Cup in the Romanian National Rally Championship\n| first year        = 2015\n| current team      = \n| car number        = \n| engine            = \n| crew chief        = \n| spotter           = <!-- Note: \"spotter\" and \"codriver\" share a field     -->\n| codriver          = Diana Ha\u021began\n| former teams      = \n| starts            = 23\n| wins              = \n| podiums           = 2\n| poles             = \n| fastest laps      = <!-- if known -->\n| best finish       = <!-- if a final championship placing has been recorded -->\n| year              = <!-- use piped link if season article exists -->\n| last finish       = \n| prev series       = <!-- previous series with line breaks -->\n| prev series years = \n| titles            = <!-- championship titles -->\n| title years       = \n| awards            = \n| award years       = \n| medaltemplates    = \n| updated           = \n}}\n'''Cristiana Oprea''' (born 11 March 1992) is a Romanian [[Rallying|rally]] driver. She is part of the very few ladies rally crews in Romania. Her career in rallying started in 2015, first as a codriver next to George Grigorescu, then as a driver in DACIA Cup, driving a Dacia Sandero 0.9 TCe.\n\nShe competes in the Romanian National Rally Championship and in the [[European Rally Championship]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fiaerc.com/oprea-all-set-for-dream-step-up-to-erc-in-rome/|title=OPREA ALL SET FOR DREAM STEP UP TO ERC IN ROME|last=FIA ERC|website=www.fiaerc.com|language=en|access-date=2019-09-23}}</ref> In July 2018 she and codriver Diana Ha\u021began became the first Romanian female rally crew in the last 50 years to compete in a foreign rally<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.agerpres.ro/sport/2018/07/17/auto-primul-echipaj-feminin-romanesc-din-ultimii-50-de-ani-la-un-raliu-in-afara-tarii--146346|title=Auto: Primul echipaj feminin rom\u00e2nesc din ultimii 50 de ani, la un raliu \u00een afara \u0163\u0103rii|last=AGERPRES|website=www.agerpres.ro|language=ro|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> (Rally Sliven, Bulgaria, a FIA [[European Rally Trophy]] event).\n\nIn July 2019 she and codriver Diana Ha\u021began became the first ladies crew to ever represent Romania in the FIA ERC European Rally Championship, at Rally di Roma Capitale, where they gained maximum points in the ERC Ladies Trophy standings driving a Peugeot 208 R2.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fiaerc.com/my-erc-debut-by-cristiana-oprea/|title=MY ERC DEBUT. BY CRISTIANA OPREA|last=FIA ERC|website=www.fiaerc.com|language=en|access-date=2019-09-23}}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\n\n=== Studies, career and motorsport debut ===\nOprea is a double graduate of the \"Ion Mincu\" University of Architecture and Urbanism in Bucharest. She studied Urban Planning (2010-2014) and Architecture (2011-2017), but she never worked in the field, wanting to follow her passion for cars.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.femeia.ro/bani-cariera/cristiana-oprea-imi-doresc-sa-reprezint-romania-la-campionatul-european-de-raliuri|title=Cristiana Oprea: \u00cemi doresc s\u0103 reprezint Rom\u00e2nia la Campionatul European de Raliuri|last=-|date=2018-12-13|website=Femeia.ro|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> In 2015 she was for a short while the PR of the Romanian Motorsport Federation, when she first took contact with the motorsport world. Her career in rallying started in 2015, first as a codriver next to George Grigorescu, Master of Sport and founder of the DACIA Cup series, then as a driver in DACIA Cup, driving a Dacia Sandero 0.9 TCe.\n\n==== Motorsport Excellence Centre Bucharest ====\nIn 2017, Oprea created the concept for a Motorsport Excellence Centre in Bucharest as an architecture graduation project.\n\n=== Racing career ===\nCristiana Oprea competed 2 full seasons, 2017 and 2018, in DACIA Cup,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cupadacia.ro/|title=Cupa DACIA|website=Cupa Dacia|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> part of the Romanian National Rally Championship. Her rookie season was 2017, when she completed 7 events driving a Dacia Sandero 0.9 TCe with Ioana Stan as a codriver. They finished on 6th place out of 9 rookie crew and on 12th place out of 18 crews enlisted overall in DACIA Cup. In 2018 she finished on the 5th place overall in DACIA Cup, marking the best result of a woman driver since 2007, when Alina Bunica competed.\n\nOprea first stepped on a podium at the beginning of 2019 season at Arge\u0219 Rally, when together with codriver Diana Ha\u021began took second place overall<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cupadacia.ro/2019/05/07/cristi-sugar-vlad-colceriu-castiga-prima-etapa-cristiana-oprea-diana-hategan-scriu-istorie-in-cupa-dacia-la-raliul-argesului/|title=Cristi Sugar/Vlad Colceriu c\u00e2\u0219tig\u0103 prima etap\u0103, Cristiana Oprea/Diana Ha\u021began scriu istorie \u00een Cupa DACIA la Raliul Arge\u0219ului|date=2019-05-07|website=Cupa Dacia|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref> in DACIA Cup.\n\nIn July 2019 she and codriver Diana Ha\u021began became the first ladies crew to ever represent Romania in the FIA ERC European Rally Championship, at Rally di Roma Capitale, where they finished P8 in the highly competitive ERC3 class and gained maximum points in the ERC Ladies Trophy standings.\n\n=== Romanian Women in Motorsport platform ===\nOprea is the founder and administrator of \"Femei \u00een Motorsport\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://autostiri.ro/femei-motorsport-o-pagina-dedicata-promovarii-femeilor-implicate-automobilismul-si-motociclismul-din-romania/|title=Femei in motorsport, o pagina dedicata promov\u0103rii femeilor implicate \u00een automobilismul \u0219i motociclismul din Rom\u00e2nia|last=Strauti|first=Dan|date=2019-03-01|website=Autostiri.ro|language=ro-RO|access-date=2019-06-10}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:Romanian rally drivers]]\n[[Category:Female rally drivers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "AutomobilismRO", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cristiana_Oprea"}
{"title_page": "Kalbach-Riedberg", "text_new": "{{Infobox German location\n|name         = Ching chong \n|type         = [[Stadtteil]]\n|Town         = [[Frankfurt am Main]]\n|image_coa    = Wappen_Kalbach.png\n|coordinates  = {{coord|50|11|05|N|08|38|22|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|image_plan   = Frankfurt Stadtteil Kalbach-Riedberg.svg\n|plantext     = Location of Kalbach-Riedberg within Frankfurt am Main\n|state        = Hesse\n|region       = Darmstadt \n|district     = urban\n|elevation    = \n|area         = 6.10\n|population   = 21, 795\n|population_as_of = 2019-12-31\n|postal_code  = 420\n|area_code    = 69\n|licence      = F\n  F\n|website      = [http://www.kalbach-riedberg.de www.kalbach-riedberg.de]\n}}\n'''Kalbach-Riedberg''' is a city district and an ''[[Ortsbezirk (Frankfurt am Main)|Ortsbezirk]]'' of [[Frankfurt am Main]], [[Germany]]. It is subdivided into the ''Stadtbezirke'' Kalbach and Riedberg. Kalbach has a long history and has been mentioned in documented sources as early as year 772. 1200 years later, in 1972, Kalbach was incorporated into [[Frankfurt am Main]]. The Riedberg area of Kalbach-Riedberg has a more recent history. As a way to combat housing shortage in Frankfurt am Main, a project to create housing space for about 20, 000 was initiated here in 2001<ref>{{cite web |title=Am Riedberg |url=https://www.stadtplanungsamt-frankfurt.de/riedberg_5309.html?psid=ukscco2pdkr2ug5jfck39ptt26 |website=Stadtplanungsamt Frankfurt am Main |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>.<ref>{{cite web |title=Kalbach-Riedberg |url=https://frankfurt.de/frankfurt-entdecken-und-erleben/stadtportrait/stadtteile/kalbach-riedberg |website=Stadt Frankfurt am Main |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>. As of 2019, Kalbach-Riedberg has a population of 21, 795<ref>{{cite web |title=Zahlen, Daten, Fakten |url=https://frankfurt.de/service-und-rathaus/zahlen-daten-fakten |website=Stadt Frankfurt am Main |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{Suburbs of Frankfurt am Main}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Districts of Frankfurt]]\n\n\n{{Hesse-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox German location\n|name         = Ching chong \n|type         = [[Stadtteil]]\n|Town         = [[Frankfurt am Main]]\n|image_coa    = Wappen_Kalbach.png\n|coordinates  = {{coord|50|11|05|N|08|38|22|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n|image_plan   = Frankfurt Stadtteil Kalbach-Riedberg.svg\n|plantext     = Location of Kalbach-Riedberg within Frankfurt am Main\n|state        = Hesse\n|region       = Darmstadt \n|district     = urban\n|elevation    = \n|area         = 6.10\n|population   = 21, 795\n|population_as_of = 2007-12-31\n|postal_code  = 420\n|area_code    = 69\n|licence      = F\n  F\n|website      = [http://www.kalbach-riedberg.de www.kalbach-riedberg.de]\n}}\n'''Kalbach-Riedberg''' is a city district and an ''[[Ortsbezirk (Frankfurt am Main)|Ortsbezirk]]'' of [[Frankfurt am Main]], [[Germany]]. It is subdivided into the ''Stadtbezirke'' Kalbach and Riedberg. Kalbach has a long history and has been mentioned in documented sources as early as year 772. 1200 years later, in 1972, Kalbach was incorporated into [[Frankfurt am Main]]. The Riedberg area of Kalbach-Riedberg has a more recent history. As a way to combat housing shortage in Frankfurt am Main, a project to create housing space for about 20, 000 was initiated here in 2001<ref>{{cite web |title=Am Riedberg |url=https://www.stadtplanungsamt-frankfurt.de/riedberg_5309.html?psid=ukscco2pdkr2ug5jfck39ptt26 |website=Stadtplanungsamt Frankfurt am Main |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>.<ref>{{cite web |title=Kalbach-Riedberg |url=https://frankfurt.de/frankfurt-entdecken-und-erleben/stadtportrait/stadtteile/kalbach-riedberg |website=Stadt Frankfurt am Main |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>. As of 2019, Kalbach-Riedberg has a population of 21, 795<ref>{{cite web |title=Zahlen, Daten, Fakten |url=https://frankfurt.de/service-und-rathaus/zahlen-daten-fakten |website=Stadt Frankfurt am Main |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{Suburbs of Frankfurt am Main}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Districts of Frankfurt]]\n\n\n{{Hesse-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Olkaolka9696", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kalbach-Riedberg"}
{"title_page": "Durham University", "text_new": "{{short description|collegiate public research university in Durham, United Kingdom}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox university\n|name            = Durham University\n|latin_name      = Universitas Dunelmens\u012bs\n|image_name      = Durham shield.png\n|image_size      = 150px\n|caption         = [[Coat of arms]] of the University of Durham\n|motto           = {{lang-la|Fundamenta eius super montibus sanctis}}\n|mottoeng        = Her foundations are upon the holy hills ([[Psalm 87]]:1)\n|established     = 1832 (university status)\n|type            = [[public university|Public]]\n|academic_staff = 1,720 (2018/19)<ref name=HESAstaff>{{cite web|url=https://www.hesa.ac.uk/data-and-analysis/staff/working-in-he#provider|publisher=[[Higher Education Statistics Agency]] |title=Who's working in HE |accessdate=1 March 2020|at=Staff numbers by HE provider }}</ref>\n|administrative_staff = 2,640 (2018/19)<ref name=HESAstaff/>\n|chancellor      = [[Thomas Allen (baritone)|Sir Thomas Allen]]\n|vice_chancellor = [[Stuart Corbridge]]\n|city            = [[Durham, England|Durham]] and [[Stockton-on-Tees]]\n|state           =\n|country         = England\n|campus          =\n| students       = {{HESA student population|INSTID=0116}} ({{HESA year}})<ref name=\"HESA citation\">{{HESA citation}}</ref>\n| undergrad      = {{HESA undergraduate population|INSTID=0116}} ({{HESA year}})<ref name=\"HESA citation\"/>\n| postgrad       = {{HESA postgraduate population|INSTID=0116}} ({{HESA year}})<ref name=\"HESA citation\"/>\n|free_label      = Student newspaper\n|free            = ''[[Palatinate (newspaper)|Palatinate]]''\n|colours         = {{color box|#72246C}} [[Palatinate (colour)|Palatinate]]\n|endowment       = \u00a381.9&nbsp;million {{small|(as of 31 July 2019; exclusive of colleges)}}<ref name=\"Durham Financial Statement 18/19\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/treasurer/financial_statements/AnnualReportandFinancialStatements2018-2019.pdf|title=Annual Report and Financial Statements for the year ended 31 July 2019|publisher=Durham University|date=n.d.|accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref>\n|budget = \u00a3452.1&nbsp;million {{small|(2018\u201319)}}<ref group=\"note\">Includes a provision of \u00a379.1&nbsp;million for the [[Universities Superannuation Scheme]]</ref><ref name=\"Durham Financial Statement 18/19\"/>\n|affiliations    =[[Association of Commonwealth Universities|ACU]] <br />[[Coimbra Group]] <br />[[European University Association|EUA]] <br />[[N8 Group]] <br />[[Matariki Network of Universities]] <br /> [[Russell Group]] <br />[[University of the Arctic]]<br />[[Universities UK]] <br />[[Virgo Consortium]] <br />[[Wallace Group (universities)|Wallace Group]] \n|athletics       = [[Team Durham]]\n|website         = {{official URL}}\n|logo            = [[File:Durham University logo.svg|200px]]\n|embedded = {{designation list | embed=yes\n   | designation1 = WHS\n   | designation1_offname = [[Durham Castle and Cathedral]]\n   | designation1_type = Cultural\n   | designation1_criteria = ii, iv, vi\n   | designation1_date = 1986 <small>(10th [[World Heritage Committee|session]])</small>\n   | designation1_number = [https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/370 370]\n   | designation1_free1name = Extension\n   | designation1_free1value = 2008\n   | designation1_free2name = State party\n   | designation1_free2value = United Kingdom\n   | designation1_free3name = Region\n   | designation1_free3value = [[List of World Heritage Sites in Western Europe|Western Europe]]\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Durham University''' (legally the '''University of Durham''')<ref name=\"branding\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/about/trading_name/ |title=The University: Trading Name&nbsp;|publisher=Durham University |date=8 April 2011 |accessdate=1 November 2011}}</ref> is a [[collegiate university|collegiate]] [[public university|public]] [[research university]] in [[Durham, England|Durham]], England, founded by an [[Act of Parliament]] in 1832 and incorporated by [[royal charter]] in 1837. It was the first recognised university to open in England for more than 600 years, after [[University of Oxford|Oxford]] and [[University of Cambridge|Cambridge]], and is thus one of the institutions to be described as the [[third-oldest university in England debate|third-oldest university in England]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/education/sunday_times_university_guide/article4767634.ece|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716104807/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/education/sunday_times_university_guide/article4767634.ece|archive-date=16 July 2011|title=Profile: Durham University|work=The Sunday Times |location=London  | date=13 September 2009 | accessdate=15 September 2010 |first1=Anushka |last1=Asthana |author-link1=Anushka Asthana|first2=Jill |last2=Sherman}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/student/into-university/az-uni-colleges/ucl-university-college-london-459098.html |title=Reference to UCL as third oldest university in England |work=The Independent |date=31 May 2013 |accessdate=16 August 2013 |location=London}}</ref> As a collegiate university its main functions are divided between the academic departments of the university and its 16 colleges. In general, the departments perform research and provide teaching to students, while the colleges are responsible for their domestic arrangements and welfare.\n\nThe university is a member of the [[Russell Group]] of British research universities<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.qmul.ac.uk/media/news/items/65620.html |title=Queen Mary, University of London to join Russell Group of universities |publisher=Queen Mary, University of London |date=12 March 2012 |accessdate=14 March 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171011225547/http://www.qmul.ac.uk/media/news/items/65620.html |archive-date=11 October 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> after previously being a member of the [[1994 Group]].  Durham is also affiliated with the regional [[N8 Research Partnership]] and international university groups including the [[Matariki Network of Universities]] and the [[Coimbra Group]].  The university estate includes 63 [[listed buildings]], ranging from the 11th-century [[Durham Castle]] to a 1930s [[Art Deco]] chapel. The university also owns and manages the Durham [[World Heritage Site]] in partnership with [[Durham Cathedral]]. The university's ownership of the World Heritage Site includes [[Durham Castle]], [[Palace Green]], and the surrounding buildings including the historic [[Durham University Library#Cosin's Library|Cosin's Library]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.durhamworldheritagesite.com/heritage/site-boundaries|publisher=Durham World Heritage Site|title=Site Boundaries: An Evolving Definition of Heritage|accessdate=4 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nAmong British universities, it had the eighth highest average [[UCAS Tariff]] for new entrants in 2016<ref name=\"CUG UCAS\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk/league-tables/rankings?o=Entry+Standards|website=Complete University Guide|title=University League Table 2019|accessdate=12 July 2018}}</ref> and the third lowest proportion of state-school educated students starting courses in 2016, at 62.9 per cent (fifth lowest compared to its benchmark).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/oxford-universities-both-struggling-state-school-recruitment|title=Oxford universities both struggling on state school recruitment|author= Simon Baker|date=1 February 2018|work=Times Higher Education|accessdate=7 February 2018}}</ref> The university is currently ranked 5th to 7th by recent national [[Rankings of universities in the United Kingdom|league tables of the British universities]], 78th to 133rd in three of the four major global tables and in the 201\u2013300 range in the fourth (see [[#Rankings and reputation|below]]). It was [[Sunday Times University of the Year|''Sunday Times'' University of the Year]] for 2005,<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/news/allnews/?itemno=971 |work=The Times | location=Durham | title=The Sunday Times university of the year | date=12 September 2004 | accessdate=10 September 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.milkround.com/article/durham-university/|title=Durham University|accessdate=15 February 2016|publisher=Milkround Online Ltd|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160223094630/http://www.milkround.com/article/durham-university/|archive-date=23 February 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> and the ''Times'' and ''Sunday Times'' Sports University of the Year for 2015,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/news/newsitem/?itemno=22113|date=19 September 2014|title=Durham University named as Times and Sunday Times Sports University of the Year 2015|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=4 October 2015}}</ref> and was awarded a [[Queen's Anniversary Prize]] in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/news/newsitem/?itemno=33775|title=Royal Honour for baby and parent sleep research|date=22 February 2018|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=11 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Chancellor (education)|chancellor]] of the university is [[Thomas Allen (baritone)|Sir Thomas Allen]], who succeeded [[Bill Bryson]] in 2012.<ref name=\"chancellor\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/news/newsitem/?itemno=12950 |title=World-famous opera star Sir Thomas Allen appointed Chancellor of Durham University |publisher=Durham University \u2013 Dur.ac.uk |date=13 October 2011 |accessdate=1 November 2011}}</ref> Current and emeritus academics include 14 Fellows of the [[Royal Society]], 17 Fellows of the [[British Academy]], 14 Fellows of the [[Academy of Social Sciences]], 5 Fellows of the [[Royal Society of Edinburgh]], 2 Fellows of the [[Royal Society of Arts]] and 2 Fellows of the [[Academy of Medical Sciences]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Members of learned societies|publisher=University of Durham|accessdate=4 October 2015|date=3 September 2015|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/research/news/learned_societies/}}</ref> Durham graduates have long used the Latin [[post-nominal letters]] ''Dunelm'' after their degree, from ''Dunelmensis'' (of, belonging to, or from Durham).<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/durham.first/autumn09/whatsinaname/|title=What's in a Name?|volume=27|date=Autumn 2009|accessdate=4 October 2015|journal=Durham First|publisher=Durham University}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{main|History of Durham University}}\n\n===Origins===\n[[File:William_Van_Mildert_by_Thomas_Lawrence.jpg|thumb|upright|[[William van Mildert]], Bishop of Durham and one of the founders of the university]]\n\nThe strong tradition of theological teaching in Durham gave rise to various attempts to form a university there, notably under King [[Henry VIII of England|Henry VIII]] and [[Oliver Cromwell]], who issued [[letters patent]] and nominated a proctor and fellows for the establishment of a [[Durham College (17th-century)|college]] in 1657.<ref name=\"Penny Cyclop\u00e6dia\">{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_7KsrAAAAYAAJ|page=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_7KsrAAAAYAAJ/page/n386 381]|quote=durham university Calendar.|title=The Penny Cyclop\u00e6dia of the Society for the Diffusion of Useful Knowledge|publisher=C. Knight, 1838|accessdate=31 May 2009|year=1838}}</ref> However, there was deep concern expressed by Oxford and Cambridge that the awarding of degree powers could hinder their position.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|title=Historical note|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/university.calendar/volumei/current/historical_note.pdf|archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20070808151224/http://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/university.calendar/volumei/current/historical_note.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=8 August 2007|publisher=Durham University}}</ref> Consequently, it was not until 1832 when [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]], at the instigation of Archdeacon [[Charles Thorp]] and with the support of the Bishop of Durham, [[William van Mildert]], passed \"an Act to enable the Dean and Chapter of Durham Cathedral to appropriate part of the property of their church to the establishment of a University in connection therewith\" that the university came into being. The act received Royal Assent from King [[William IV of the United Kingdom|William IV]] on 4 July 1832.\n\n===The church university, 1832\u20131909===\n[[File:ExamInCosin.jpg|thumb|An examination taking place in [[Durham University Library#Cosin's Library|Cosin's Library]], 1842]]\n[[File:Durham Castle Gatehouse (geograph 2907552).jpg|thumb|[[Durham Castle]] (gatehouse pictured) houses [[University College, Durham|University College]], making it one of the oldest buildings currently being used to house a university in the world<ref>{{cite news|url=http://castle-jcr.dur.ac.uk/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=94&Itemid=78 |title=Castle JCR |author=Castle JCR |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061010134853/http://castle-jcr.dur.ac.uk/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=94&Itemid=78 |archivedate=10 October 2006 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/education/sunday_times_university_guide/article570365.ece |work=The Times |location=London  | title=Widening access without diluting quality | date=2 October 2005 | accessdate=1 May 2010 | first1=Anushka | last1=Asthana | author-link1=Anushka Asthana|first2=Jill | last2=Sherman}}</ref>]]\n\nThe university opened on 28 October 1833. In 1834 all but two of the bishops of the Church of England confirmed that they would accept holders of Durham degrees for ordination. In 1835 a fundamental statute was passed by the Dean and Chapter, as governors of the University, setting up [[Convocation]] and laying down that Durham degrees would only be open to members of the Church of England. Regulations for degrees were finalised in 1836 and the university was incorporated by [[Royal Charter]] granted by William IV on 1 June 1837 as the \"Warden, Masters and Scholars of the University of Durham\", with the first students graduating a week later.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /> Accommodation was provided in the Archdeacon's Inn (now Cosin's Hall) from 1833 to 1837. On the accession of [[Queen Victoria]] an order of the [[Queen-in-Council]] was issued granting the use of [[Durham Castle]] (previously a palace of the Bishop of Durham) to the university.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" />\n\nIn 1846, [[Thomas Hatfield|Bishop Hatfield]]'s Hall (later to become [[Hatfield College]]) was founded, providing the opportunity for students to obtain affordable lodgings with fully catered communal eating, a revolutionary idea at the time, endorsed by a Royal Commission in 1862 and later spread to other universities. Those attending [[University College, Durham|University College]] were expected to bring a servant with them to deal with cooking, cleaning and so on. The level of applications to Bishop Hatfield's Hall led to a second hall along similar lines, [[Bishop Cosin's Hall]], being founded in 1851, although this only survived until 1864. Elsewhere, the university expanded from Durham into [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]] in 1852 when the medical school there (established in 1834) became a college of the university.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /> This was joined in 1871 by the College of Physical Sciences (renamed the College of Science in 1884 and again renamed Armstrong College in 1904). [[St Cuthbert's Society]] was founded in 1888 for non-collegiate, mostly mature, male students as a non-residential society run by the students themselves. Two teacher-training colleges \u2013 St Hild's for women, established in 1858, and The College of the Venerable Bede for men, established in 1839,<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /> also existed in the city and these merged to form the mixed [[College of St Hild and St Bede]] in 1975. From 1896 these were associated with the university and graduates of St Hild's were the first female graduates from Durham in 1898.\n\nDuring its expansion phase the University also became the first English university to establish relationships with overseas institutions;<ref>{{cite web|title=Our history and values|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/about/shaped/|publisher=Durham University|date=1 February 2015}}</ref> firstly in 1875 with [[Codrington College]], Barbados, and secondly in early 1876 with [[Fourah Bay College]], Sierra Leone.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|title=Imperial Echos|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/features/imperial-echoes/419239.article|work=Times Higher Education|date=8 March 2012}}</ref> Under the arrangements the two colleges became affiliated colleges of the university with their students sitting examinations for and receiving Durham degrees.<ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Uncommon problems|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2004/may/11/internationaleducationnews.highereducation|publisher=JOURNAL OF SIERRA LEONE STUDIES|date=1 January 2013}}</ref> The landmark event was not met with universal applause, with the [[London Times]] stating \"it would not be much longer before the University of Durham was affiliated to the Zoo\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Rebuilding the Athens of West Africa: Education in the 21st Century in Sierra Leone|url=http://www.thejournalofsierraleonestudies.com/downloads/Version2.pdf|publisher=The Guardin|date=11 May 2004}}</ref> After nearly a century of affiliation and with the prevailing winds of decolonisation Fourah Bay became independent of the university in 1968 to form part of the [[University of Sierra Leone]], while Codrington College retained its affiliation with the university until the 2000s.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|title=Historical Dictionary of Sierra Leone (Historical Dictionaries of Africa)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=q31SWae8fhIC&pg=RA1-PA54&lpg=RA1-PA54&dq=Fourah+Bay+College+1876+durham&source=bl&ots=s1rWTrYYEj&sig=xx7FbifMOMCJj_fGe3UD6b41_y4&hl=en&sa=X&ei=ZUjOVKrCHMzxaJbxgKAC&ved=0CDYQ6AEwBTgK#v=onepage&q=Fourah%20Bay%20College%201876%20durham&f=false|publisher=Scarecrow Press |date=1 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe first debating society in Durham was founded in 1835, but may have closed by 1839. The Durham University Union was established in 1842, and revived and moved to [[Palace Green]] in 1872-3 as the [[Durham Union Society]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://reed.dur.ac.uk/xtf/view?docId=ead/uni/undg.xml#UNDall-3507|title=Durham University Records: Associations and Societies \u2013 Durham Union Society|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=3 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://dus.org.uk/our-history/|title=Our History|publisher=Durham Union Society|accessdate=3 October 2015}}</ref> Notable past presidents of the Durham Union have included [[Richard Dannatt]], [[Sir Edward Leigh]], and [[Crispin Blunt]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Dannatt|first1=Gen. Sir (Francis) Richard|title=Who's Who|journal=A & C Black|year=2011|issue=online edn|url=http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.001.0001/ww-9780199540884-e-12817|accessdate=12 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=EDWARD LEIGH MEMBER OF PARLIAMENT FOR GAINSBOROUGH|url=https://www.conservatives.com/OurTeam/Members_of_Parliament/Leigh_Edward|website=Conservatives|publisher=The Conservative and Unionist Party|accessdate=12 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Blunt|first1=Crispin|url=https://hansard.parliament.uk/commons/2016-10-21/debates/DD6089AE-523C-4707-9773-4262BB9415BD/SexualOffences(PardonsEtc)Bill|title=Sexual Offences (Pardons Etc) Bill|work=Hansard|accessdate=12 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Durham Colleges Students Representative Council (SRC) was founded around 1900 after the model of the College of Medicine SRC (in Newcastle). The Durham University SRC was formed in 1907 with representatives from the Durham Colleges, the College of Medicine, and Armstrong College (also in Newcastle). In 1963, after the creation of Newcastle University, the Durham Colleges SRC became the Durham University SRC, and was renamed as the [[Durham Students' Union]] in 1970.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://reed.dur.ac.uk/xtf/view?docId=ead/uni/undg.xml#UNDall-1409|title=Durham University Records: Associations and Societies \u2013 Student Representative Bodies|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=3 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nUntil the mid 19th century, University of Durham degrees were subject to a religion test and could only be taken by members of the established church. Medical degrees in Newcastle were exempt from this requirement from the start of the affiliation of the medical school, but in Durham it lasted until the revision of the statutes in 1865.<ref>{{cite news |title=University of Durham|work=Morning Post |date=18 September 1865 |accessdate=5 December 2015 |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000174/18650918/038/0006| via = [[British Newspaper Archive]]|url-access=subscription }}</ref> Despite the opening of degrees, staff and members of Convocation were still required to be members of the Church of England until the [[Universities Tests Act 1871]]. However, \"dissenters\" were able to attend Durham and then sit the examinations for degrees of the [[University of London]], which were not subject to any religious test.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.senatehouselibrary.ac.uk/our-collections/historic-collections/archives-manuscripts/university-of-london-student-records-1836-1931/ |title=University of London student records 1836\u20131931 |publisher=senatehouselibrary.ac.uk |date=12 March 2013 |accessdate=12 March 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100914105055/http://www.shl.lon.ac.uk/specialcollections/archives/studentrecords.shtml |archivedate=14 September 2010  }}</ref> Following the grant of a supplemental charter in 1895 allowing women to receive degrees of the university, the Women's Hostel ([[St Mary's College, Durham|St Mary's College]] from 1919) was founded in 1899.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Durham Difference|author=Nigel Watson|date=2007|publisher=James & James (Publishers) Ltd, London|page=29\n}}</ref>\n\n===The federal university, 1909\u20131963===\n[[File:Durham Heritage Centre.jpg|right|thumb|[[St Chad's College]], one of the two independent colleges]]\nThe Newcastle division of the university, which comprised both Armstrong College (named after Lord Armstrong) and Durham University College of Medicine, quickly grew to outnumber the Durham colleges, despite the addition of two independent [[Anglicanism|Anglican]] foundations: [[St Chad's College]] (1904) and [[St John's College, Durham|St John's College]] (1909). A parliamentary bill proposed in 1907 would have fixed the seat of the university in Durham for only ten years, allowing the Senate to choose to move to Newcastle after this. This was blocked by a local [[Member of parliament|MP]]{{who|date=October 2018}}, with the support of graduates of the Durham colleges, until the bill was modified to establish a federal university with its seat fixed in Durham. This reform also removed the university from the authority of the Dean and Chapter of [[Durham Cathedral]], who had been the governors of the university since its foundation.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Durham Difference|author=Nigel Watson|date=2007|publisher=James & James (Publishers) Ltd, London|pages=30\u201331}}</ref> Thirty years after this, the [[Royal Commission]] of 1937 recommended changes in the constitution of the federal university, resulting in the merger of the two Newcastle colleges in the Newcastle Division to form King's College. The Vice-Chancellorship alternated between the Warden of the Durham Division and the Rector of the Newcastle Division.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Durham Difference|author=Nigel Watson|date=2007|publisher=James & James (Publishers) Ltd, London|page=45}}</ref> (The legacy of this lives on, in that the de facto head of the university is still called \"The Vice-Chancellor and Warden\".)<ref group=note>The title \"warden\" was not used between 1909 and 1937, as the 1909 statutes assigned the title to the Council of the Durham Colleges collectively. Its readoption in 1937 had to do with distinguishing between the two Divisions, the Durham Colleges headed by a warden and King's College (Newcastle) by a rector. It signified that the postholders were \"the chief academic and administrative officers of the Divisions respectively\" (art 45).</ref>\n\nAfter World War II, the Durham division expanded rapidly. St Aidan's Society ([[St Aidan's College, Durham|St Aidan's College]] from 1961) was founded in 1947 to cater for non-resident women and the decision was made to expand further on Elvet Hill (where the science site had been established in the 1920s), relocating St Mary's College, building new men's colleges, vastly expanding the existing pure science provision in Durham, and adding applied science (1960) and engineering (1965).<ref>{{cite web|title=Durham University Records|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=3 October 2015|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/library/asc/collection_information/cldload/?collno=150|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151005154338/https://www.dur.ac.uk/library/asc/collection_information/cldload/?collno=150|archive-date=5 October 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 1947, the foundation stones for the new [[St Mary's College, Durham|St Mary's]] College building on Elvet Hill were laid by Princess Elizabeth (later Queen [[Elizabeth II]]).<ref>{{cite book|title=The Durham Difference|author=Nigel Watson|date=2007|publisher=James & James (Publishers) Ltd, London|page=54}}</ref> The new building opened in 1952. In the same year, tensions surfaced again over the Durham-Newcastle divide, with a proposal to change the name of the university to the \"University of Durham and Newcastle\". This motion was defeated in [[Convocation]] (the assembly of members of the university) by 135 votes to 129.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Durham University Journal|page=121|volume=13\u201314|title=Name of the University|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Er4TAQAAMAAJ&q=%22university+of+durham+and+newcastle%22&dq=%22university+of+durham+and+newcastle%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CB8Q6AEwAGoVChMIrqXugvCjyAIVy5qACh128AKN|publisher=Durham University}}</ref> Eleven years later, with the Universities of Durham and Newcastle upon Tyne Act 1963, King's College became the [[Newcastle University|University of Newcastle upon Tyne]], leaving Durham University based solely in its home city.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Durham Difference|author=Nigel Watson|date=2007|publisher=James & James (Publishers) Ltd, London|page=75}}</ref>\n\n===The modern university, 1963\u20131999===\n\nBy the time of the separation from Newcastle the Elvet Hill site was well established; with the first of the new colleges being founded in 1959, [[Grey College, Durham|Grey College]], named after the [[Charles Grey, 2nd Earl Grey|second Earl Grey]] who was the [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] when the university was founded. Expansion up Elvet Hill continued, with [[Van Mildert College]] and the [[Durham Business School]] (1965), [[Trevelyan College]] (1966) and [[Collingwood College, Durham|Collingwood College]] (1972) all being added to the university, along with a [[Durham University Botanic Garden|Botanic Garden]] (1970).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/botanic.garden/aboutus/history/|title=History of the Garden|accessdate=1 October 2015|publisher=Durham University}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The Durham Difference|author=Nigel Watson|date=2007|publisher=James & James (Publishers) Ltd, London|pages=78\u201382}}</ref>\n\n[[File:St Mary's College Lawn.jpg|thumb|right|The lawn at [[St Mary's College, Durham|St Mary's College]], the first of the [[Colleges of the University of Durham|Hill college]]s]]\nThese were not the only developments in the university, however. The Graduate Society, catering for postgraduate students, was founded in 1965 (renamed [[Ustinov College]] in 2003) and the (now closed) Roman Catholic [[seminary]] of [[Ushaw College]], which had been in Durham since 1808, was licensed as a hall of residence in 1968. In 1988 Hatfield, the last men's college, became mixed; followed by the women's college of Trevelyan in 1992, leaving the original women's college of St Mary's as the last single-sex college.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Durham Difference|author=Nigel Watson|date=2007|publisher=James & James (Publishers) Ltd, London|page=99}}</ref>\n\nIn 1989 the university started its fund-raising and [[alumni]] office, with a virtual community for alumni<ref>{{cite web|title=dunelm.org.uk|url=http://www.dunelm.org.uk|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=8 April 2014}}</ref> and several large gifts made to the university, including for the Centre for Middle Eastern Studies, the [[Durham University Department of Physics|Department of Physics]] and the [[Wolfson Research Institute]].\n\n====Development in Stockton, 1992\u20131999====\nIn 1991, a joint venture between the university and the [[University of Teesside]] saw the Joint University College on Teesside of the Universities of Durham and Teesside (JUCOT) established at [[Thornaby-on-Tees]] in the borough of [[Stockton-on-Tees]] and the ceremonial county of North Yorkshire,  {{convert|30|mi}} to the south of Durham. It opened under the name of University College Stockton (UCS) in 1992.\n\nUCS was initially intended to grant joint degrees validated by both institutions (BAs and BScs). However, Teesside, which had only become a university in 1992, had difficulties in taking on its responsibilities for the college and withdrew in 1994, Durham taking over full responsibility for UCS and the degrees to be awarded there.\n\nA programme of integration with Durham began, with the Privy Council approving changes in Durham's statutes to make UCS a college of the University of Durham. Further integration of the Stockton development with the University led to the formation of the University of Durham, Stockton Campus (UDSC) in 1998 and the separation of teaching responsibilities from UCS.\n\n===21st century===\n[[File:Al-Qasimi Building.jpg|thumb|School of Government and International Affairs]]\nIn 2001, two new colleges, [[John Snow College|John Snow]] and [[Stephenson College, Durham|George Stephenson]] (after the [[John Snow (physician)|physician]] and the [[George Stephenson|engineer]]) were established at Stockton, replacing UCS, and the new [[Durham University School of Medicine, Pharmacy and Health|medical school]] (operating in association with the [[University of Newcastle upon Tyne]]) accepted its first students. In 2002, her [[golden jubilee]] year, the [[Elizabeth II of the United Kingdom|Queen]] granted the title \"Queen's Campus\" to the Stockton site.<ref>{{cite web|title=Durham University Welcomes Her Majesty the Queen|url=http://www.necc.co.uk/member-news-and-events/1079-durham-university-welcomes-her-majesty-the-queen|publisher=The North East Chamber of Commerce|accessdate=1 February 2015}}</ref> By 2005, Queen's Campus, Stockton, accounted for around 18 per cent of the total university student population.<ref>{{cite web|title=The University: Student Statistics|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/about/facts/student/|publisher=Durham University|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100224230410/http://www.dur.ac.uk/about/facts/student/|archivedate=24 February 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, the university unveiled a re-branded [[logotype]] and introduced the trading name of Durham University, although the legal name of the institution remained the University of Durham and the official coat of arms was unchanged.<ref name=\"branding\"/> The same year, [[St Mary's College, Durham|St Mary's College]] had its first mixed undergraduate intake.<ref>{{cite news|title=St Mary's opens door to men after 106 years|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1499996/St-Marys-opens-door-to-men-after-106-years.html|work=The Daily Telegraph|location=London|accessdate=1 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Durham college opens doors to male undergraduates|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2005/oct/05/highereducation.students|work=The Guardian|location=London|accessdate=1 February 2015}}</ref> In October 2006, [[Josephine Butler College]] opened its doors to students as Durham's newest college \u2013 the only purpose-built self-catering college for students within Durham. This was the first new college to open in Durham itself since the creation of Collingwood in the 1970s.<ref>{{cite news|title=New college for Durham University|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/2515027.stm|work=BBC News|accessdate=1 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2010, Durham joined the [[Matariki Network of Universities]] (MNU) together with [[Dartmouth College]] (USA), [[Queen's University at Kingston|Queen's University]] (Canada), [[University of Otago]] (New Zealand), [[University of T\u00fcbingen]] (Germany), [[University of Western Australia]] and [[Uppsala University]] (Sweden).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.matarikinetwork.com/members.html |title=Members of the Matariki Network of Universities |publisher=Matarikinetwork.com |date=n.d.|accessdate=1 November 2011}}</ref> In 2012, Durham (along with [[University of York|York]], [[University of Exeter|Exeter]] and [[Queen Mary, University of London]]) joined the [[Russell Group]] of research-intensive British universities.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2012/mar/12/russell-group-four-more-universities|date=12 March 2012|title=Russell Group extends membership to four more universities|author=Jessica Shepherd}}</ref>\n\nBetween 2010 and 2012 the university was criticised for accepting funds from controversial sources, including the government of [[Iran]], the [[US State Department]], the prime minister of [[Kuwait]] and [[British American Tobacco]].<ref>{{cite news|work=[[BBC]]|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/education-12908507|title=Durham University defends accepting funds from Iran|author=Simon Cox|date=31 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2011/feb/10/wikileaks-durham-university-iran-us-embassy|title=WikiLeaks reveals degree of Durham University's involvement in Iran|author=Ian Black|date=10 February 2011|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.new.spectator.co.uk/2011/04/shaky-dealings-are-damaging-the-reputation-of-britains-universities/|title=Shaky dealings are damaging the reputation of Britain's universities|newspaper=[[The Spectator]]|author=David Blackburn|date=1 April 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151119171502/http://blogs.new.spectator.co.uk/2011/04/shaky-dealings-are-damaging-the-reputation-of-britains-universities/|archivedate=19 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2011/jun/07/durham-university-tobacco-funding-afghan-award|title=Furore over Durham's tobacco funding for Afghan scholarship|author=Lucy Tobin|date=7 June 2011|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref>\n\nThe university announced in 2016 that it would relocate the colleges and academic activities currently at the Queen's Campus to Durham City from 2017;<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazettelive.co.uk/news/teesside-news/durham-university-considering-withdrawing-medical-10950734|work=Gazette Live|title=Durham University considering withdrawing medical school from Stockton|date=25 February 2016|author=James Cain}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.palatinate.org.uk/university-continues-to-consult-on-the-future-of-queen\u2019s-campus/|title=University continues to consult on the future of Queen's Campus|date=10 March 2016|author=Charlie Taylor-Kroll|newspaper=[[Palatinate (newspaper)|Palatinate]]}}</ref> with the School of Medicine, Pharmacy and Health being transferred to [[Newcastle University]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.itv.com/news/tyne-tees/2016-07-13/durham-university-to-move-school-of-medicine-pharmacy-and-health-out-of-teesside/|title=Durham University to move school of medicine, pharmacy and health out of Teesside|date=13 July 2016|work=[[itv.com]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazettelive.co.uk/news/teesside-news/durham-university-confirms-plans-pull-11314325|title=Durham University confirms plans to pull academic and college-based activities from Stockton\n|date=10 May 2016|author=James Cain|work=GazetteLive}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://my.ncl.ac.uk/staff/nuconnections/item/transfer-of-school-of-medicine-pharmacy-and-health-to-newcastle1|title=Transfer of School of Medicine, Pharmacy and Health to Newcastle|accessdate=7 August 2017|date=10 July 2017|publisher=Newcastle University}}</ref> The Queen's Campus became an International Study Centre to prepare overseas students to study at Durham, run by [[Study Group International|Study Group]].<ref name=\"Queen's ISC\">{{cite news|url=http://www.palatinate.org.uk/queens-campus-to-house-new-centre-for-international-students/|title= Queen's Campus to house new centre for international students|date=30 January 2017|author= Eugene Smith|work=[[Palatinate (newspaper)|Palatinate]]}}</ref>\n \n[[File:Ogden Centre (geograph 5908287).jpg|thumb|The Ogden Centre for Fundamental Physics, next to the Department of Physics]]\nIn March 2017 [[Martin Rees|Lord Rees]] opened the Ogden Centre for Fundamental Physics, designed by [[Daniel Libeskind]].<ref>{{cite web |title=University opens \u00a311.5m 'space centre' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-tyne-39249121 |website=BBC News |accessdate=2 November 2018}}</ref> The new building, named after alumnus [[Peter Ogden]], provides extra laboratories and office space for 140 staff.<ref>{{cite web |title=Iconic research centre confirms Durham's international position in space science \u2013 Durham University |url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/news/research/?itemno=30784 |publisher=Durham University |accessdate=2 November 2018 }}</ref> In May 2017 the university announced a new ten-year strategy that proposed investing \u00a3700m in improving the campus, creating 300 new academic posts, increasing the size of the university to 21,500 students while attracting more international students, and expanding the business school and the departments of law, politics, English and history to reach \"critical research mass\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/durhams-repositioning-create-300-academic-jobs|title=Durham's \u2018repositioning\u2019 to create 300 academic jobs|work=[[Times Higher Education]]|date=27 May 2017|author=John Elmes}}</ref><ref name=\"Chronicle Strategy\">{{cite news|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/north-east-news/durham-university-reveals-700m-plan-13077153|title=Durham University reveals \u00a3700m plan to help rejuvenate campus|work=Chronicle Live|date= 23 May 2017|accessdate=2 June 2017|author=Hannah Graham}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 the university announced that a consortium led by [[Interserve]] would design, build and operate two colleges at [[Mount Oswald]] (new buildings for John Snow College and [[South College, Durham|one new college]]) for \u00a3105&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2018/08/17/interserve-wins-105m-construction-contract-durham-university/|title=Interserve wins \u00a3105m construction contract for Durham University|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=17 August 2018|author=Rhiannon Curry}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-tyne-45220845|title=Durham University to spend \u00a3105m on new colleges|work=[[BBC News]]|date=17 August 2018}}</ref> The project company (in which the university has a 15 per cent stake) is financing the construction via a \u00a390&nbsp;million 46-year bond issue.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://ftalphaville.ft.com/2018/08/20/1534771832000/University-accommodation-deals--it-s-a-wrap/|title=University accommodation deals: it's a wrap|date=20 August 2018|author=Thomas Hale|work=[[Financial Times]]}}</ref> Separately, the university announced that it had raised \u00a3225&nbsp;million to fund its estate masterplan through the private sale of long-term bonds to British and US investors.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/business/business-news/durham-university-secures-225m-funding-15091280|title=Durham University secures \u00a3225m of funding from key UK and US investors|date=30 August 2018|author=Coreena Ford|work=Chronicle Live}}</ref>\n\n==Campus==\nDurham University owns a {{convert|227.8|ha|acre|abbr=on}} estate which includes part of a [[UNESCO world heritage site]],<ref name=\"Durham's World Heritage Site expands\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/news/newsitem/?itemno=6941&rehref=%2Fnews%2Farchive%2F&resubj=%20Headlines|title=Durham's World Heritage Site expands|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=11 January 2009}}</ref> one [[ancient monument]], five [[Listed building|grade-one listed building]]s and 68 grade two-listed buildings, along with {{convert|44.9|ha|acre|abbr=on}} of woodland.<ref name=\"Durham Masterplan\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/estates/masterplan/masterplan.pdf|title=University of Durham Framework and Masterplan|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=11 January 2009}}</ref> The estate is divided across two separate locations: Durham City and Queen's Campus, Stockton. The two locations are connected via a free bus service that runs frequently throughout the week. One of the major public attractions in Durham City is the {{convert|7.3|ha|acre|abbr=on}} [[Durham University Botanic Garden|Botanic Gardens]], established in 1970, with over 78,000 visitors (2007/08).<ref name=\"About the Garden\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/botanic.garden/aboutthegarden/|title=About the Garden|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=11 January 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"Estates and Buildings Annual Report 2007/2008\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/estates/documents/AnnualReport0708Final.pdf|title=Estates and Buildings Annual Report 2007/2008|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=11 January 2009}}</ref> {{as of|2018}}, the estate included over 300 buildings with a floor area of more than 380,000&nbsp;m<sup>2</sup> and a 2014 insurance reinstatement value of close to \u00a3850&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aude.ac.uk/Resources/Documents/Content?g=d21f6a53-3473-4208-b747-6b195d04bac1|title=Focus on Estates at Durham University|date=13 September 2018 |author= Cheryl Pick}}</ref>\n\n===Durham City===\n[[File:Hatfield College, Durham.jpg|thumb|[[Hatfield College, Durham|Hatfield College]], one of the five colleges along the Bailey]]\n[[File:Old Elvet, Durham (geograph 3851375).jpg|thumb|[[Old Elvet]] is the home of a number of departments, as well as Old Shire Hall]]\nDurham City is the main location of the university and contains all of the colleges along with most of the academic departments. The Durham City estate is spread across several different sites.\n\n[[The Bailey]] is the historic centre of the university and contains five colleges as well as the departments of Music and of Theology and Religion, the Institute of Advanced Study and [[Palace Green]] Library, housing the University's special collections. The Bailey is linked to Dunelm House, home of the [[Durham Students Union|Students Union]] in New Elvet, by the University's [[Kingsgate Bridge]].\n\nThe [[Elvet|Old and New Elvet]] areas contain a number of departments in Humanities and Social Sciences including Philosophy, and Sociology. The Leazes Road site on the north bank of the Wear, opposite the university's [[The Racecourse|Racecourse]] playing fields and Old Elvet, is home to the School of Education and Hild Bede College. Old Elvet was previously the site of the university's administration in [[Shire Hall, Durham|Old Shire Hall]], which has, since September 2012, been based on the Mountjoy site, in the Palatine Centre on Stockton Road.<ref>{{cite news|title=Former university HQ 'to become hotel within months'|url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/10065509.Former_Durham_University_HQ__to_become_hotel_within_months_/|accessdate=16 September 2015|work=The Northern Echo|date=22 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n====Mountjoy====\n[[File:Palatine Centre, Durham (cropped).jpg|thumb|The Palatine Centre on the Mountjoy Campus, home of the university's administration]]\n\nThe Mountjoy site (formerly the Science site) south of New Elvet contains the vast majority of departments and large lecture theatres such as Appleby, Scarborough, James Duff, Heywood and more recently the Calman Learning Centre, along with the [[Durham University Library|Bill Bryson library]].<ref>{{cite news|title=The Main Library is being renamed 'The Bill Bryson Library'!|date=25 September 2012|publisher=Durham University|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/library/news/?itemno=15355|accessdate=27 November 2012}}</ref> Upper Mountjoy contains the Psychology and Biological & Biomedical schools, along with various research centres.\n\nBuilding work started in 2017 on a Centre for Teaching and Learning on the Montjoy site, to open in 2019;<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/north-east-news/works-starts-new-40m-durham-14072810.amp|title=Works starts on new \u00a340m Durham University education hub|date=26 December 2017|work=ChronicleLive|author=Kali Lindsay}}</ref> the university also intends to build new facilities for mathematics and computer science on the site, to open in 2020.<ref name=\"Roadmap 2027\"/>\n\n====Elvet Hill====\n[[File:Sheraton Park Durham.jpg|thumb|Sheraton Park, site of a former teacher training college and home to Ustinov College since 2017]]\nElvet Hill, south of the Mountjoy site, has 8 of the colleges as well as the [[Durham University Botanic Garden|Botanic Garden]] and the Vice-Chancellor's residence in Hollingside House. It is also home to the [[Durham University Business School|Business School]] and the department of Government and International Affairs, as well as the [[Teikyo University of Japan in Durham]] and the Oriental Museum.\n\nAs part of the transfer of colleges from the Queen's Campus in 2017, a number of colleges changed location. Stephenson College moved to the site at Howlands Farm (also on Elvet Hill) previously occupied by Ustinov College. Ustinov itself moved to a new site at Sheraton Park in Neville's Cross from the 2017/18 academic year. For a transition period, John Snow and Stephenson will both be located at Howlands Farm during the 2018/19 academic year.<ref name=\"Roadmap 2027\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/14756619.University_college_move_approved/|work=Northern Echo|title=University college move approved|author=Rachel Conner|date=22 September 2016|accessdate=24 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n====Mount Oswald====\nTwo new colleges are currently being built at the former Mount Oswald golf course on Elvet Hill and are due to be occupied in 2020. John Snow college will move into one college, with the other forming an (as yet unnamed) 17th college. The new colleges at Mount Oswald will have around 500 self-catered rooms each. As of 2016, when bids were solicited for the construction, the first 700 rooms were hoped to be available for the 2019/20 academic year and the remaining 300 by the 2021/22 academic year.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theconstructionindex.co.uk/news/view/durham-uni-seeks-contractor-for-two-new-colleges|work=The Construction Index|title= Durham Uni seeks contractor for two new colleges|date=9 September 2016|accessdate=14 September 2016}}</ref> Construction began in September 2018, with \"Hub building\" expected to be ready for 2019/20 but the first students not expected to move into the new accommodation until the 2020/21 academic year.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/16693505.work-starts-on-durham-universitys-new-80m-colleges/|title=ConstructionWork starts on Durham University's new \u00a380m colleges|work=Northern Echo|date=7 September 2018|author=Rachel Conner-Hill}}</ref> John Snow college will still move out of Howlands in 2019/20, being located for one year at Rushford Court (owned by [[Unite Students]]) in the viaduct area of the city before moving to Mount Oswald for 2020/21.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/experience/news/?itemno=36995|title=Bright future for John Snow College, as 2019/20 location is announced|date=14 December 2018|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=16 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Development plans====\nThe university's 2017\u20132027 strategy document calls for the development of a new home for the business school at Elvet Waterside (Old Elvet), to open in 2021, and for the redevelopment of the arts and humanities facilities at Elvet Riverside (New Elvet), opening from 2022.<ref name=\"Roadmap 2027\"/> The plans are, however, contingent on the university being granted a Certificate of Immunity from Listing for the current student union building, Dunelm House, which would allow it to be demolished.<ref name=\"Chronicle Strategy\"/> Following an appeal by the [[Twentieth Century Society]] against the 2016 decision of the Secretary of State, [[Karen Bradley]], not to list the building, the [[Department of Culture, Media and Sport]] reconsidered the case in 2017 and confirmed that it would not list the building and was minded to issue a certificate of immunity.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://archpaper.com/2017/01/durham-students-union-risk-loss/#gallery-0-slide-0|work=The Architects Newspaper|author=Jason Sayer|date=5 January 2017|title=The birthplace of Brutalism in the U.K. is at risk of losing its most outstanding concrete building}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/north-east-news/ugly-iconic-durhams-student-union-12328491|work=ChronicleLive|title=Ugly or iconic? Durham's student union building could be demolished|author=Laura Hill |date=5 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.architectsjournal.co.uk/news/culture-secretary-refuses-to-reverse-dunelm-house-listing-decision/10024892.article|title=Culture secretary refuses to reverse Dunelm House listing decision|date=1 November 2017|author= Colin Marrs |work=The Architects Newspaper}}</ref> The [[Twentieth Century Society]] have placed Dunelm House on their 'Buildings at Risk List'.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-38689831|work=BBC News|date=20 January 2017|title=Ten 20th Century buildings named as 'at risk'}}</ref>\n\nIn total, the university expects to build four to six new colleges by 2027.<ref>{{cite video|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cON8a-Qwlu8|title=An update from Professor Stuart Corbridge, Vice-Chancellor and Warden|date=26 January 2017|publisher=Durham University|via=YouTube}}</ref><ref name=\"Roadmap 2027\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/strategy2027/Roadmap2027.pdf|title=A Roadmap to 2027|work=University Strategy 2017\u20132027|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=25 May 2017}}</ref> The university's Estate Masterplan for 2017\u20132027 identified the area around Howlands Farm, the Leazes Road site (Hild Bede College), and the current Business School site as locations for new accommodation development.<ref name=\"Colleges Masterplan\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/about/DurhamUniversityMasterplanExecutiveSummaryRevCSML.pdf|work=University Estate Masterplan 2017\u20132027 Executive Summary|page=8|title=Academic and Collegiate Zoning|year=2017|publisher=Durham University}}</ref>\n\n====Ushaw College====\n[[Ushaw College]], 5 miles west of Durham, is a former Catholic seminary that is a licensed hall of residence of the university. It hosts parts of the Business School and of the Centre for Catholic Studies, with the university having committed to leasing the East Wing until 2027 and to establishing a residential research library at Ushaw.<ref name=\"Ushaw Library\"/> It formerly housed some students from [[Josephine Butler College]], but since summer 2015 the only students at Ushaw are business marketing students.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/greenspace/travel/public/bus/ushawcollege/|title=Changes to the Bus Service between Ushaw College and Durham City}}</ref> In 2017 the university's Centre for Evaluation and Monitoring, part of the School of Education, moved to Ushaw College.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/estates-developments/past/cem/|title=CEM move to Ushaw|accessdate=1 September 2018|publisher=Durham University}}</ref>\n\n===Queen's Campus===\n[[File:Wolfson Institute.jpg|thumb|upright=2.0|right|[[Wolfson Research Institute]] at the Queen's Campus]]\n\nQueen's Campus, Stockton was established in 1992 and is located in [[Thornaby-on-Tees]] in the [[borough of Stockton-on-Tees]], some 30 miles from Durham City. Until 2017\u201318, the campus was home to around 2,000 full-time students in two colleges ([[John Snow College|John Snow]] and [[Stephenson College, Durham|Stephenson College]]s) and the [[Wolfson Research Institute]].<ref name=\"Welcome to Queen's - A Cosmopolitan Campus\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/queens-campus/|title=Welcome to Queen's \u2013 A Cosmopolitan Campus|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=11 January 2009}}</ref> A bus connects Queen's Campus to Durham City, with a one-way journey usually taking 45 minutes.<ref name=\"Stockton\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/travel/durham.queens/|title=Travelling between Durham City and Queen's Campus, Stockton|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=11 January 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe colleges and academic departments were relocated to Durham City (or transferred to [[Newcastle University]] in the case of the School of Medicine, Pharmacy and Health) between 2017 and 2018, and the Queen's Campus became an International Study Centre (ISC), run by [[Study Group International|Study Group]]. This prepares non-EU foreign students to enter degree courses at the university, with the first students having started in September 2017.<ref name=\"Queen's ISC\"/><ref name=\"Roadmap 2027\"/> The ISC has taken over the former college accommodation on the campus, with the former Stephenson College buildings becoming Endeavour Court and the former John Snow College buildings becoming Infinity House. The ISC also continues to use the privately owned Rialto Court accommodation, which was previously used by the Queen's Campus colleges.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.durhamisc.com/international-study-centre/accommodation|title=Student Accommodation|website=Durham University International Study Centre|publisher=Study Group|accessdate=1 September 2018}}</ref> The university had said, as part of its 2017\u20132027 masterplan, that it is continuing to explore other options for the use of the Queen's Campus and will be developing a separate masterplan for the campus.<ref name=\"Colleges Masterplan\"/>\n\nThe [[Wolfson Research Institute]] was established at the Queen's Campus in 2001 to conduct and facilitate interdisciplinary research in health and wellbeing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/wolfson.institute/abouttheinstitute/|title=About the Institute|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=1 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Libraries===\n[[File:Palace Green Library (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright=2.0|The original university library is now known as the [[Palace Green]] Library (centre) and the School of Music (left)]]\n\nThe [[Durham University Library]] system holds over 1.5&nbsp;million printed items.<ref name=\"Library History\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/library/about/history/|title=Library History|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=11 January 2009}}</ref> The library was founded in January 1833 at [[Palace Green]] with a 160-volume donation by the Bishop of Durham, William Van Mildert.<ref name=\"Library History\"/> The library operates five branches: Bill Bryson Library (the main library), Leazes Road Library, Queen's Campus Library, Durham University Business School Library and the Palace Green Library, which holds the special and heritage collections.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/library/services/|title=Services and sites |website=Durham University Library|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, designated status was granted by the [[Museums, Libraries and Archives Council]] to two of the special collections: Bishop Cosin's Library on Palace Green (an endowed public library dating from 1669 of which the University is the trustee), which contains medieval manuscripts and over 5,000 printed books, many early, and the Sudan Archive, described by the university as \"the pre-eminent archive on the Sudan outside Khartoum\".<ref name=\"Library: Designation\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/library/asc/collection_information/designation2005/|title=Designation|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=11 January 2009}}</ref> Since the Museums, Libraries and Archives Council was abolished in 2012, the designation scheme has been managed by [[Arts Council England]]; the two special collections remain Designated as of July 2016, along with the [[Durham University Oriental Museum]]'s Egyptian and Chinese collections.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artscouncil.org.uk/sites/default/files/download-file/Collections_List_July_2016_.pdf|title=Currently Designated Collections|date=July 2016|accessdate=30 March 2017|pages=22\u201323|publisher=Arts Council England}}</ref>\n\n[[File:St_Cuthbert_Gospel_-_f.1.jpg|thumb|upright|St Cuthbert Gospel, an 8th-century [[gospel book]]]]\nIn 2012 the university, together with the [[British Library]] and [[Durham Cathedral]], purchased Europe's oldest intact book, the [[St Cuthbert Gospel]], for the nation for \u00a39&nbsp;million. It is displayed equally in London and Durham, being shown at the University's Palace Green Library for the first time as part of the Lindisfarne Gospels Durham exhibition in 2013.<ref>[http://pressandpolicy.bl.uk/Press-Releases/British-Library-acquires-the-St-Cuthbert-Gospel-the-earliest-intact-European-book-58c.aspx \"British Library acquires the St Cuthbert Gospel \u2013 the earliest intact European book\"], BL Press release. Retrieved 17 April 2012</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/palace.green/whatson/details/?id=18081|title=Lindisfarne Gospels Durham|website=Palace Green Library|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=3 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.palatinate.org.uk/st-cuthbert-gospel-returns-to-palace-green-library/|newspaper=[[Palatinate (newspaper)|Palatinate]]|date=23 October 2014|author=Rose Malleson|title=St Cuthbert Gospel returns to Palace Green Library}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to the central library system, each College maintains its own library and reading rooms such as the Bettenson, Brewis, Williams and Fenton Libraries of St Chad's College, which contain over 38,000 volumes.<ref name=\"St Chad's: Library\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/StChads/libraries.html|title=St Chad's Library|publisher=St Chad's College|accessdate=11 January 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081226115308/http://www.dur.ac.uk/StChads/libraries.html|archivedate=26 December 2008}}</ref> Many departments also maintain a library in addition to the subject collections in the central and college libraries. Readers are also entitled to use the theology library housed by [[Durham Cathedral]] in its cloister.\n\nIn February 2017, the university announced a \u00a32&nbsp;million investment to establish a residential research library at [[Ushaw College]]. This would be the first residential research library at a UK university, and would offer researchers access to the collections of Ushaw College and [[Durham Cathedral]] as well as the university's special collections at the Palace Green Library. It is planned that visiting researchers would also participate in the public engagement programme at Ushaw.<ref name=\"Ushaw Library\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/15067492.Multi_million_pound_plans_for_new_international_residential_research_library_unveiled/|title= Multi-million pound plans for new international residential research library at Ushaw College unveiled|date=3 February 2017|accessdate=3 February 2017|author=Gavin Engelbrecht|work=Northern Echo}}</ref>\n\n===Museums===\n[[File:Durham Kathedrale.jpg|thumb|right|The Old Fulling Mill, original home of the University Museum in 1833, on the bank of the River Wear below Durham Cathedral]]\nThe university manages a number of museums. Built in the 1960s, the [[Durham University Oriental Museum]] grew predominantly from the acquisitions of the university's former School of Oriental Studies.<ref name=\"Oriental Museum:History of the Museum\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/oriental.museum/history/|title=History of the Museum|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=11 January 2009}}</ref> Initially housed across the university and used as a teaching collection, the size of the collection led to the building of the current museum to house the material.<ref name=\"Oriental Museum:History of the Museum\"/> The collection to date contains over 30,000 objects from Asian art to antiquities, covering the [[Orient]] and [[Levant]] to the Far East and the [[Indian Sub-continent]], with over a third of the collection relating to China.<ref name=\"Oriental Museum:History of the Museum\"/><ref name=\"Oriental Museum:Chinese\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/oriental.museum/collections/chinese/|title=Chinese|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=11 January 2009}}</ref> The national importance of the Chinese and Egyptian collections can be seen in the Designated Status from the [[Museums, Libraries and Archives Council]] achieved in 2008.<ref name=\"Oriental Museum:Chinese\"/><ref name=\"Oriental Museum:Egyptian\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/oriental.museum/collections/egypt/|title=Egypt|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=11 January 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"DESIGNATION UPDATE Spring 2008\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mla.gov.uk/what/raising_standards/~/media/Files/pdf/2008/designation_update_spring2008|title=Museums, Libraries and Archives Council DESIGNATION UPDATE Spring 2008|publisher=Museums, Libraries and Archives Council|accessdate=11 January 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090210224051/http://www.mla.gov.uk/what/raising_standards/~/media/Files/pdf/2008/designation_update_spring2008|archivedate=10 February 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Durham University Museum of Archaeology]] moved to Palace Green in 2014, having previously been housed in the Old Fulling Mill on the banks of the Wear. The museum was opened in 1833, being the second university museum in England to allow admittance to the general public.<ref name=\"Museum of Archaeology:History of the Museum\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/archaeology.museum/about/history/|title=History of the Museum|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=5 February 2009}}</ref> The museum focuses on the heritage of North East England and includes national and international collections spanning the [[Prehistoric]], Ancient Greek, [[Roman Britain|Roman]], [[Anglo-Saxon]], [[Medieval]] and [[Post Medieval]] periods.<ref name=\"Museum of Archaeology:Collections of the Museum\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/archaeology.museum/whatshere/|title=What's Here|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=5 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Organisation and administration==\n\n===Academic year===\nThe academic year at Durham is divided into three terms: [[Michaelmas term]], which lasts 10 weeks from October to December; [[Epiphany term]], which lasts nine weeks from January to March; and [[Easter term]], which lasts nine weeks from April to June. All terms start on a Monday. The weeks of term are called \"Teaching Weeks\", numbered from 1 (start of Michaelmas) to 28 (end of Easter), although this period is used for teaching and exams. Additionally, there is an \"Induction Week\" (informally known as \"Freshers' Week\" or Week 0) for first year students prior to the start of Michaelmas term, starting on the first Monday in October.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/dates/|title=Dates of meetings and events|accessdate=3 October 2015|publisher=Durham University}}</ref>\n\nStudents at the university are also expected to \"Keep Term\", whereby students must fulfil their academic requirements at the university. As such Heads of Departments must be satisfied that each student has attended all necessary tutorials, seminars and practical work throughout the term and vacation period.<ref>{{cite web|title=Regulations \u2013 Keeping Terms|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/university.calendar/volumei/current/regs.keeping_terms.pdf|archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20070926121421/http://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/university.calendar/volumei/current/regs.keeping_terms.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=26 September 2007|publisher=Durham University}}</ref>\n\n===Colleges===\n{{main|Colleges of the University of Durham}}\n[[File:Durham Castle Innenhof.jpg|thumb|[[University College, Durham|University College]] is the oldest of the Durham colleges]]\nDurham operates a collegiate structure similar to that of the University of Oxford and the University of Cambridge, in that all the colleges at Durham (and the [[Wesley Study Centre]]) are \"listed bodies\" in part two of the Education (Listed Bodies) (England) Order 2013 made under the [[Education Reform Act 1988]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2013/2993/made|title=The Education (Listed Bodies) (England) Order 2013|date=30 December 2013|accessdate=4 October 2015}}</ref> as bodies that appear to the Secretary of State \"to be a constituent college, school, hall or other institution of a university which is such a recognised body\" (the \"recognised body\" being, in this case, Durham University).<ref>{{cite web|title=Recognised UK Degrees|url=http://www.dfes.gov.uk/recognisedukdegrees/index.cfm?fuseaction=institutes.list&InstituteCategoryID=2|publisher=DFES|accessdate=4 October 2015}}</ref> Though most of the Durham colleges are governed and owned directly by the university itself (the exceptions being St John's and St Chad's), the legal status of the Durham colleges is similar to Oxbridge colleges, setting them apart from those at the universities of Kent, Lancaster, and York.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=U7H_m5ji-IwC&pg=PA72#v=onepage&q&f=false|pages=72\u201373|title=The Collegial Tradition in the Age of Mass Higher Education|author1=Ted Tapper|author2=David Palfreyman|date=20 July 2010|publisher=[[Springer Science+Business Media]]}}</ref> However, unlike at Oxford and Cambridge, there is no formal teaching at Durham colleges (with the exception of [[Cranmer Hall, Durham|Cranmer Hall]] theological college within St John's), although colleges are active in research.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/collegesresearch/|title=Research in Colleges|accessdate=4 October 2015|publisher=Durham University}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://community.dur.ac.uk/cranmer.hall/|title=Welcome to Cranmer Hall|accessdate=4 October 2015|publisher=Cranmer Hall}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk/durham/international|title=Durham University|quote=Colleges are not teaching bodies and are not linked to any particular academic department; all teaching is delivered through the various departments.|publisher=Complete University Guide|accessdate=4 October 2015}}</ref> The colleges dominate the residential, social, sporting, and pastoral functions within the university, and there is heavy student involvement in their operation.\n\n[[Formal (university)|Formal dinner]]s (known as \"formals\") are held at every college; [[Academic dress of Durham University|gowns]] are worn to these events at just over half of the colleges. Gowns are not worn for formals at Collingwood, St Aidan's, St Cuthbert's, Hild Bede, Van Mildert, Stephenson or Ustinov.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://issuu.com/communicationsoffice/docs/ugp2016_singlepages_v4_final|title=Durham University Undergraduate Prospectus 2016|page=26|publisher=Durham University}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/postgraduate/accommodation/features/|title=Which College is right for me?|accessdate=3 October 2015|publisher=Durham University}}</ref> There is a great deal of intercollegiate rivalry, particularly in [[Durham College Rowing|rowing]] and other sporting activities. There is also rivalry between the older \"[[Bailey Colleges|Bailey]]\" colleges and the newer \"Hill\" colleges.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.durhamstudent.co.uk/colleges/|title=The Ultimate Guide to Durham's Colleges|accessdate=3 October 2015|publisher=Durham Student}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.palatinate.org.uk/?p=35020|title=Reviewed and interviewed: Novice Cup 2013|accessdate=3 October 2015|work=[[Palatinate (newspaper)|Palatinate]]}}</ref>\n\nThe colleges are:\n{{Div col|colwidth=20em}}\n{{ordered list|type=none\n | [[File:Durham - Collingwood arms.png|15px]] [[Collingwood College, Durham|Collingwood College]]\n | [[File:Durham - Grey arms.png|15px]] [[Grey College, Durham|Grey College]]\n | [[File:Durham - Hatfield arms.png|15px]] [[Hatfield College]]\n | [[File:Durham - John Snow arms.png|15px]] [[John Snow College]]\n | [[File:Josephine Butler College Crest.png|15px]] [[Josephine Butler College]]\n | [[File:Durham - St Aidan's arms.png|15px]] [[St Aidan's College, Durham|St Aidan's College]]\n | [[File:Durham - St Chads arms.png|15px]] [[St Chad's College]]\n | [[File:Durham - St Cuthberts arms.png|15px]] [[St Cuthbert's Society]]\n | [[File:Durham - St Hild and Bede arms.png|15px]] [[College of St Hild and St Bede]]\n | [[File:Durham - St Johns arms.png|15px]] [[St John's College, Durham|St John's College]]\n | [[File:Durham - St Marys arms.png|15px]] [[St Mary's College, Durham|St Mary's College]]\n | [[South College, Durham|South College]] (due to open in 2020)\n | [[File:Durham - George Stephenson arms.png|15px]] [[Stephenson College, Durham|Stephenson College]]\n | [[File:Durham - Trevelyan arms.png|15px]] [[Trevelyan College]]\n | [[File:Durham - University College arms.png|15px]] [[University College, Durham|University College]]\n | [[File:Durham - Ustinov arms.png|15px]] [[Ustinov College]]\n | [[File:Van Mildert Coll Durham shield.svg|15px]] [[Van Mildert College]]\n}}\n{{Div col end}}\n\n===Governance===\n{{see also|List of Chancellors of the University of Durham|List of Vice-Chancellor & Wardens of the University of Durham}}\n[[File:The Venerable Charles Thorp.jpg|thumb|right|Archdeacon [[Charles Thorp]], founder and first Warden of Durham]]\nThe University is governed by the Statutes put in place by the Universities of Durham and Newcastle upon Tyne Act, 1963, and subsequently amended by the [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Council]]. The Statutes provide that: \"The University shall be governed by a Visitor, Chancellor, Vice-Chancellor, Convocation, Council, Senate, and Boards of Studies.\" (Statute 4).\n<ref name=Statutes>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/university.calendar/volumei/statutes/|title=University Statues|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=1 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Visitor]] for the University of Durham is the [[Bishop of Durham]]. The Visitor is the final arbiter of any dispute within the university, except in those areas where legislation has removed this to the law courts or other [[ombudsman|ombudsmen]], or in matters internal to the two non-maintained colleges (St Chad's College and St John's College), each of which has its own Visitor. Student complaints and appeals were heard by the Visitor until the [[Higher Education Act 2004]] came into force.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.opsi.gov.uk/ACTS/acts2004/40008--c.htm#20 |title=Section 20 of the Higher Education Act 2004 |publisher=Government of the United Kingdom |date=26 October 2011 |accessdate=1 November 2011}}</ref> All student complaints are now heard by the [[Office of the Independent Adjudicator]] for Higher Education.\n\nThe [[Chancellor (education)|Chancellor]] of the university is [[Thomas Allen (baritone)|Sir Thomas Allen]], who succeeded [[Bill Bryson]] in January 2012.<ref name=\"chancellor\"/> The Chancellor is appointed by Convocation for \"a fixed period of not normally less than five years as determined by the Council\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/university.calendar/volumei/statutes/|title=University Statutes|publisher=Durham University|at=Statue 6|accessdate=1 March 2016}}</ref> which can be renewed. The role of the Chancellor is mainly ceremonial; The Vice-Chancellor (formally the ''Vice-Chancellor and Warden'') is the Chief Executive Officer of the University and is appointed by Council.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/vice.chancellor/|title=Vice-Chancellor|accessdate=1 March 2016|publisher=Durham University}}</ref> As Warden the Vice-Chancellor is responsible for the 14 maintained colleges of the University.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/about/governance/|title=How the University is run|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=2 March 2016|quote=\"In his role as Warden, the Vice-Chancellor and Warden also has overall responsibility for fourteen of the University's Colleges \u2013 the Heads of College are directly responsible to the Vice-Chancellor through the Pro-Vice-Chancellor and Deputy Warden of the Colleges. The two recognised Colleges, St John's and St Chad's, are independent foundations with separate Governing Councils.\"}}</ref> Since September 2015 this has been [[Stuart Corbridge]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Tallentire|first1=Mark|title=Durham University names new head|url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/11885190.Durham_University_names_new_head/|accessdate=31 March 2015|work=The Northern Echo|date=27 March 2015}}</ref> succeeding [[Chris Higgins (academic)|Chris Higgins]] who retired in September 2014.<ref name=\"Northern Echo - Durham University vice-chancellor to retire in September\">{{cite news|last=Tallentire|first=Mark|title=Durham University vice-chancellor to retire in September|url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/11054695.Durham_University_vice_chancellor_to_retire_in_September|accessdate=5 March 2014|newspaper=The Northern Echo|date=5 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Durham Graduation.jpg|thumb|left|The university's graduation ceremonies take place in [[Durham Cathedral]] with receptions on [[Palace Green]]]]\n[[Convocation]] is the assembly of the university. Membership of Convocation is open to: the Chancellor, Vice-Chancellor, and Pro-Vice-Chancellors, all graduates, the teaching staff (lecturers, senior lecturers, readers, and professors), and the heads of colleges and licensed halls of residence. It must meet once each year in order to hear the Vice-Chancellor's Address and to debate any business relating to the university. Further meetings can be called if representation is made by a minimum of 50 members. Its powers are limited to appointing the Chancellor (and even then, only on the nomination of Council and Senate) and the making of representations to the university on any business debated (Statute 30).<ref name=Statutes />\n\n[[University council|Council]] is the executive body of the university. In addition to representatives from the university it includes up to 12 lay members (not being teachers or salaried staff in the university or any of its colleges), the [[Dean of Durham]] and the President of Durham Students' Union (Statute 10). Its powers include establishing and maintaining colleges, and recognising non-maintained colleges and licensed halls of residence (Statutes 12 & 13).\n\n[[File:Bill Bryson Chancellor.JPG|thumb|upright|[[Bill Bryson]] (Chancellor 2005\u20132012) in the academic dress of Chancellor of Durham University]]\n[[Academic Senate|Senate]] is the supreme governing body of the university in academic matters. It nominates the Vice-Chancellor and Pro-Vice-Chancellors to Council, and recommends the establishment of Faculties and Boards of Studies. It is Senate that grants degrees, and has the authority to revoke them. It also regulates the use of [[Academic dress of Durham University|academic dress]] of the university (Statutes 19 & 20).<ref name=Statutes />\n\nThe day-to-day running of the University is in the hands of the University Executive Committee (UEC), which is also responsible for the development of the policies and strategies. This is a joint subcommittee of Senate and Council and consists of the Vice-Chancellor and Warden, the Deputy Vice-Chancellor and Provost ([[Chief Academic Officer]]), the two portfolio Pro-Vice-Chancellors (for Education and Research), the three faculty Pro-Vice-Chancellors, the Pro-Vice-Chancellor and Deputy Warden (who has responsibility for the colleges), the Registrar (chief operating officer) and the Treasurer (chief financial officer). All heads of departments and of colleges report directly to one of the members of the UEC.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/committees/uec/ways_working/|title=Ways of Working: Roles and Responsibilities|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=2 March 2016|date=29 January 2016|author=[[Stuart Corbridge]]}}</ref><ref name=\"University Executive Committee\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/committees/uec_standing_orders/|title=University Executive Committee|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=2 March 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"University Executive Committee\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/news/newsitem/?id=29142&itemno=29142|title= Durham appoints Deputy Vice-Chancellor and Provost|date=10 October 2016|publisher=Durham University}}</ref>\n\n===Schools and faculties===\nThe teaching departments of the university are divided into four faculties: Science, Arts and Humanities, Social Sciences and Health, and the Business School. Each faculty is headed by a Pro-Vice-Chancellor and one or more Deputies. These, along with the heads of the departments in the faculty and the Vice-Chancellor, make up the Faculty Board for that faculty. Each department also has a Board of Studies consisting of the Pro-Vice-Chancellor of their faculty, the teaching staff of the department, and student representatives (Statute 29).<ref name=Statutes /> Associated with the first three faculties are three combined honours degrees: Natural Sciences (BSc & MSci), Liberal Arts (BA), and Combined Honours in Social Sciences (BA).<ref>{{cite book|url=https://issuu.com/CommunicationsOffice/docs/ugp2017|pages=54\u201355, 80\u201381, 90\u201391|publisher=Durham University|date=March 2016|title=Undergraduate Prospectus 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe largest degree programmes offered by the university, by number of entrants from the 2013\u201314 admissions cycle, were Business, Accounting and Finance (395), Natural Sciences (221), Modern Languages and Cultures (216), and Geography (216).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/ug.admissions/admindocuments/admincycle1314/2-1-5DepartmentalSummaryFinalAS12Replies.pdf|title=2\u20131\u20135 Departmental Summary \u2013 Final (AS12 Replies) 2013/2014 Admissions Cycle|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=1 October 2015|format=PDF}}</ref>\n\n{{Div col}}\n\n'''Faculty of Social Science & Health'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/socialsciences.health/|title=Faculty of Social Sciences & Health|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=4 March 2016}}</ref>\n* Department of Anthropology\n* Department of Archaeology\n* School of Education\n* Department of Geography\n* School of Government and International Affairs <br /> (''Including the Politics Department and the Institute for Middle East and Islamic Studies'')\n* [[Durham Law Department|Durham Law School]]\n* Department of Sociology\n*Department of Sport and Exercise Sciences\n\n'''Faculty of Arts and Humanities'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/arts.humanities/aboutfaculty/|title=About The Faculty|website=Faculty of Arts and Humanities|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=3 March 2016}}</ref>\n*Department of Classics & Ancient History\n*Department of English Studies\n*Department of History\n*School of Modern Languages and Cultures <br /> (''Includes Arabic, Chinese, Japanese, French, German, Italian, Russian, and Hispanic Studies Departments'')\n* [[Durham University Department of Music|Department of Music]]\n*Department of Philosophy\n*Department of Theology and Religion\n*English Language Centre\n*Centre for Foreign Language Study\n\n'''Faculty of Science'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/science.faculty/|title=Faculty of Science|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=4 March 2016}}</ref>\n*Department of Biosciences\n*Department of Chemistry\n*Department of Computer Science\n*Department of Earth Sciences\n*[[Durham University School of Engineering|Department of Engineering]]\n*Department of Mathematical Science\n*[[Durham University Department of Physics|Department of Physics]]\n*Department of Psychology\n\n'''Faculty of Business ([[Durham University Business School]])'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/university.calendar/volumei/boards_of_studies/|title=University Calendar|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=31 August 2019}}</ref>\n*Department of Accounting\n*Department of Economics and Finance\n*Department of Management and Marketing\n\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==Academic profile==\n\n===Admissions===\n{| class=\"wikitable floatright\" style=\"font-size:85%; text-align:center;\"\n|+ UCAS Admission Statistics\n!\n!2017\n!2016\n!2015\n!2014\n!2013\n|-\n|'''Applications'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ucas.com/file/144241/download?token=nlVZq6el|title=End of Cycle 2017 Data Resources DR4_001_03 Applications by provider|year=2017|website=UCAS|publisher=UCAS|access-date=25 January 2018}}</ref>\n|28,895\n|29,485\n|28,085\n|26,635\n|25,895\n|-\n|'''Offer Rate (%)'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Sex, area background and ethnic group: D86 Durham University|url=https://www.ucas.com/file/145051/download?token=BOfbnBrr|year=2017|website=UCAS|publisher=UCAS|accessdate=25 January 2018}}</ref>\n|74.2\n|70.7\n|69.0\n|68.4\n|58.9\n|-\n|'''Enrols'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ucas.com/file/144196/download?token=JEpp6fiF|title=End of Cycle 2017 Data Resources DR4_001_02 Main scheme acceptances by provider|year=2017|website=UCAS|publisher=UCAS|access-date=25 January 2018}}</ref>\n|4,510\n|4,475\n|4,190\n|4,175\n|4,165\n|-\n|[[Yield (college admissions)|'''Yield (%)''']]\n|21.0\n|21.5\n|21.6\n|22.9\n|27.3\n|-\n|'''Applicant/Enrolled Ratio'''\n|6.41\n|6.59\n|6.70\n|6.38\n|6.22\n|-\n|'''[[UCAS Tariff|Average Entry Tariff]]'''<ref name=\"Complete League Table 2019\">{{cite-web|url=https://www.thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk/league-tables/rankings|title=Top UK University League Table and Rankings|publisher=Complete University Guide}}</ref><ref group=note>New [[UCAS]] points from 2016</ref>\n|n/a\n|197\n|519\n|524\n|521\n|}\n\n[[File:Cosin's Hall, Durham.jpg|right|thumb|Cosin's Hall, home to the [[Institute of Advanced Study (Durham)|Institute of Advanced Study]]]]\nThe average [[UCAS]] point score for new entrants in 2016\u201317 was 197 points, placing Durham University eighth in the country in terms of entrants' points.<ref name=\"CUG UCAS\" /> Durham's student body consists of {{HESA undergraduate population|INSTID=0116}} undergraduates and {{HESA postgraduate population|INSTID=0116}}  postgraduate students ({{HESA year}}).<ref name=\"HESA citation\"/> In 2014/15, Durham had the fourth highest number of students from middle class backgrounds at 85.8 per cent.<ref name=\"Most Middle Class\">{{cite news|url=http://st.hitcreative.com/education/university_guide/active/UniversityGuide/table/year/2016/type/derived/id/106|title=Most Middle Class |work=[[The Times]]/[[Sunday Times]]}}</ref> For the same year, 34.3 per cent of the undergraduate full-time student population came from independent schools and 8.75% from [[grammar schools]],<ref name=\"Total Undergraduate by School Type - Full-Time 2014/2015\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/student.registry/statistics/undergraduate/2.7school/2.7total/142-7b.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160201065236/https://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/student.registry/statistics/undergraduate/2.7school/2.7total/142-7b.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=1 February 2016|title=Total Undergraduate by School Type \u2013 Full-Time 2014/2015|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=4 October 2015}}</ref> 19.35 per cent of full-time students are of ethnic minorities.<ref name=\"Undergraduate Total Students Ethnicity - Full-Time 2014/2016\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/student.registry/statistics/undergraduate/2.10ethnicity/2.10full/142-10a.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160201065237/https://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/student.registry/statistics/undergraduate/2.10ethnicity/2.10full/142-10a.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=1 February 2016|title=Undergraduate Total Students Ethnicity \u2013 Full-Time 2014/2015|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=4 October 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Undergraduate Students by Gender - Full-Time 2007/2008\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/student.registry/statistics/undergraduate/2.4gender/2.4ft/142-4a.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160201065236/https://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/student.registry/statistics/undergraduate/2.4gender/2.4ft/142-4a.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=1 February 2016|title=Undergraduate Students by Gender \u2013 Full-Time 2014/2015|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=4 October 2015}}</ref> In 2014\u201315, 44.8 per cent of full-time undergraduate students lived in University (including St John's and St Chad's colleges) accommodation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/student.registry/statistics/college/4.1accommodation/4.1ft/144-1a.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160201065236/https://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/student.registry/statistics/college/4.1accommodation/4.1ft/144-1a.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=1 February 2016|title=Undergraduate Student Accommodation \u2013 Full Time 2014/2015|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=4 October 2015}}</ref> The university gave offers of admission to 69 per cent of 18-year-old applicants in 2015, the 9th lowest amongst the [[Russell Group]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Which elite universities have the highest offer rates |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/education/2016/10/19/which-elite-universities-have-the-highest-offer-rates/|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=21 October 2016}}</ref> In the 2016\u201317 academic year, the university had a domicile breakdown of 73:6:22 of UK:EU:non-EU students respectively with a female to male ratio of 55:45.<ref>{{cite web|title=Where do HE students study?|url=https://www.hesa.ac.uk/data-and-analysis/students/where-study#provider|website=hesa.ac.uk|publisher=Higher Education Statistics Authority|accessdate=9 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nDurham charges undergraduate fees of \u00a39,250 for home/EU students.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/treasurer/students/tuition_fees/full_time_undergraduates/years/1920/|title=Finance Department|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=26 June 2019}}</ref> Following the Government's announcement in 2016 that fees in England would be allowed to rise by 2.8 per cent (from the then maximum level of\u00a39,000), Durham became one of the first universities in the country to announce it intended to take advantage of this to raise fees to the new maximum of \u00a39,250 for students entering from 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2016/jul/20/english-universities-to-raise-tuition-fees-for-first-time-since-they-trebled|title=English universities to raise tuition fees for first time since they trebled|date=20 July 2016|author=Richard Adams|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref>\n\nFor the undergraduate admissions cycle 2013\u201314, Durham received 26,030 applications (for around 4,200 places),<ref name=\"Total Applications 2013/2014\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/ug.admissions/admindocuments/admincycle1314/1-1TotalApplications.pdf|title=Total Application 2013/2014|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=4 October 2015}}</ref> of which 38.4 per cent were from independent schools<ref name=\"School Types (State/Independent) 2013/2014\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/ug.admissions/admindocuments/admincycle1314/1-4ApplicationsbySchoolTypeState-Independent.pdf|title=Admissions Statistics Documents:School Types (State/Independent) 2013/2014|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=4 October 2015}}</ref> and 13.8 per cent (of UK applications) from ethnic minorities,<ref name=\"Ethnicity and Fee Status Detail: Applications 2013/2014\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/ug.admissions/admindocuments/admincycle1314/1-5-1EthnicityandFeeStatusDetail-Applications.pdf|title=Ethnicity and Fee Status Detail: Applications 2013/2014|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=4 October 2015}}</ref> overall 64.2 per cent of applicants were successful in receiving an offer of admissions.<ref name=\"Total Applications 2013/2014\"/> Durham requires students applying for degrees in law to sit the [[LNAT]] admission test.<ref name=\"LNAT\">{{cite web|url=http://www.lnat.ac.uk/what-is-lnat/do-i-need-to-sit-the-test/|title=Do I need to sit the test??|publisher=LNAT|accessdate=4 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Widening access===\nDurham has been criticised for not accepting as many students from low participation neighbourhoods, and from state schools, as might be expected from its admission standards and course offerings. For admissions in 2015/16, Durham had the third lowest percentage of state school students (among higher education institutions with over 1,000 full-time first-degree entrants) at 60.5 per cent, compared to a [[Higher Education Statistics Agency]] benchmark of 75 per cent. According to pro-vice-chancellor, Alan Hudson, this was a temporary drop from the 63 per cent level the university has reached in recent years, and to which it was expected to return in 2016/17. The university also fell short of its benchmark for admissions from low participation neighbourhoods, accepting 5.1 per cent, compared to a benchmark of 6 per cent.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/data-analysis-latest-hesa-figures-state-school-entrants|work=Times Higher Education|title=Data analysis: latest Hesa figures on state school entrants|date=3 February 2017|author=John Elmes}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/north-east-news/durham-university-one-lowest-admission-12554295|work=Chronicle Live|author=Hannah Graham|date=4 February 2017|title=Durham University has one of the lowest admission rates for pupils from state schools}}</ref> The data for 2016/17 showed that admissions from state schools had recovered to 62.9 per cent, still short of the location-adjusted benchmark of 74.9 per cent, and that admissions from low participation neighbourhoods were 5.2 per cent compared to the location-adjusted benchmark of 6.6 per cent.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hesa.ac.uk/news/01-02-2018/widening-participation-tables|title=Widening participation: UK Performance Indicators 2016/17|publisher=Higher Education Statistics Agency|accessdate=1 September 2018|date=1 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nSince 1992 the university has run a widening access programme, originally called the Centre for Lifelong Learning and now known as the Durham Centre for Academic Development. The centre provides access to Durham degrees for mature students who show academic promise but do not hold the traditional entry requirements. The centre runs a range of [[foundation year]] courses associated with specific degree courses. For the 2013\u201314 admissions cycle, 153 students took up offers of places in the programme.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/foundation.programme/|title=The Foundation Programme|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=1 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/ug.admissions/admindocuments/admissions-2007-08/1-5.pdf|title=Departmental Summary \u2013 Final (AS12) Replies 2013/2014 Admissions Cycle|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=1 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nDurham has partnered with the [[Sutton Trust]] since 2012 to run the Durham University Sutton Trust Summer School for [[Gifted education#United Kingdom|gifted and talented]] school children from underrepresented backgrounds, leading to qualification with 16 to 32 [[UCAS Tariff]] points and a guaranteed conditional offer from Durham if they choose to apply.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://summerschools.suttontrust.com/host-universities/durham-university/|title=Durham University|accessdate=1 October 2015|publisher=[[Sutton Trust]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150721193349/http://summerschools.suttontrust.com/host-universities/durham-university/|archive-date=21 July 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/news/newsitem/?itemno=35514|title=State school students helped to reach university|date=29 August 2018|accessdate=1 September 2018|publisher=Durham University}}</ref> The University also runs the Durham International Summer School<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/international/summerschool/|title=International Summer School|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=1 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151004064836/https://www.dur.ac.uk/international/summerschool/|archive-date=4 October 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> and partners with the Sutton Trust to run the Durham Teacher Summer School.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.suttontrust.com/programmes/teacher-summer-schools/partner-universities/|title=Partner Universities|publisher=Sutton Trust|accessdate=23 February 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160302143703/http://www.suttontrust.com/programmes/teacher-summer-schools/partner-universities/|archive-date=2 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Durham became the first UK university to participate in the [[Inside-Out Prison Exchange Program]].<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2016/feb/22/prison-education-university-kent-jail-swaleside|title=Prison no bar to higher education as university \u2018campus\u2019 opens in Kent jail|date=22 February 2016|author=Eric Allison}}</ref> The scheme, where students study alongside inmates, ran in [[Durham Prison]] and the high-security [[HM Prison Frankland|Frankland Prison]] in 2015 and was expanded to include [[HM Prison Low Newton|Low Newton Prison]] in 2016.<ref>{{cite news|work=BBC News|title=Durham University's Inside-Out scheme sees students study with prisoners|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-tyne-35409927|date=30 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/sociology/crim/insideout/|title=Durham University Inside-Out Prison Exchange Programme|website=Durham University Department of Sociology|accessdate=11 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nDurham gives a bursary, known as the Durham Grant, of \u00a32,000 per year to students from households with an annual income of less than \u00a325,000. The University planned to reduce this to \u00a31,800 per year for students entering from 2016 onwards, after the [[Office for Fair Access]] encouraged moving away from bursaries to other schemes to widen participation. However, this decision was reversed after the government decided to abolish maintenance grants.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.palatinate.org.uk/university-backtracks-on-durham-grant-scheme/|title=University backtracks on Durham Grant Scheme|date=25 February 2016|newspaper=[[Palatinate (newspaper)|Palatinate]]}}</ref> The University also runs the \"Supported Progression\" programme for sixth-form students, aimed at helping talented young people from the North East, Cumbria and Yorkshire to fulfill their potential via a two-year structured programme of events.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cumbriacrack.com/2017/01/26/st-benedicts-sixth-form-students-accepted-onto-durham-university-programme/|title=St Benedict's Sixth Form Students accepted onto Durham University programme|work=Cumbria Crack|author=Carl Fallowfield |date= 26 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Research===\n[[File:View from the 4th floor of the Calman centre.jpg|thumb|right|The Dawson Building houses the departments of Archaeology and Anthropology]]\nThe university is part of the [[Russell Group]], [[Virgo Consortium]] and the [[N8 Group]] of Universities.\nAccording to the latest [[CWTS Leiden Ranking]] 2018 that measures the scientific performance of 500 major universities worldwide, Durham is ranked 89th in the world in terms of the proportion of its academic papers in the top 10 per cent for impact (the \"PP(top 10%)\" measure).<ref name=Leiden2018>{{cite web|url=http://www.leidenranking.com/ranking/2018/list |title=Leiden Ranking 2018 |publisher= Leiden University |accessdate=11 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nResearch institutes at the university include the [[Centre for the Advanced Study of the Arab World]], the [[Durham Energy Institute]], the Institute for Hazard and Risk Research, the [[Institute of Advanced Study (Durham)|Institute of Advanced Study]], the [[International Boundaries Research Unit]] and the [[Institute for Computational Cosmology]].\n\nIn the 2014 [[Research Excellence Framework]], Durham was assessed to have a research profile of 33 per cent world class (4*), 50 per cent internationally important (3*), 15 per cent internationally recognised (2*), and 1 per cent nationally recognised (1*).<ref name=\"THE REF 2014\">{{cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/ref-2014-results-table-of-excellence/2017590.article|title=REF 2014 results: table of excellence|newspaper=[[Times Higher Education]]|date=18 December 2014|author=Paul Jump}}</ref> which was an improvement on the 2008 [[Research Assessment Exercise]].<ref name=\"THE RAE 2008\">{{cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/features/research-assessment-exercise-rae-results-2008/404786.article|title=Research Assessment Exercise (RAE) results, 2008|newspaper=[[Times Higher Education]]|date=18 December 2008}}</ref> However, this was in the context of a rise in the average profile from 2008 to 2015.<ref name=\"THE REF 2014\"/> In the [[Times Higher Education]] ranking by [[grade point average]] (GPA; measuring average quality), Durham fell from joint 14th in 2008 to 20th in 2014 despite a rise in GPA from 2.72 to 3.14.<ref name=\"THE REF 2014\"/> Similarly, Durham fell from 19th to 20th in the Times Higher Education ranking by total research power.<ref name=\"THE REF 2014\"/> However, in Research Fortnight's ranking by total research power (which uses a weighting closer to that used by [[HEFCE]] in making funding allocations, with 2* and 1* research zero-weighted<ref name=\"RSS REF\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rss.org.uk/Images/PDF/about/press-releases/rss-press-release-ref-league-tables-report-11-05-2015.pdf|title=Report from the RSS Working Group on Research Excellence Framework (REF) League Tables|publisher=[[Royal Statistical Society]]|date=11 May 2015}}</ref>) Durham rose from 19th in 2008 to 18th in 2014.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/education/universityeducation/11299261/League-tables-the-top-universities-for-research.html|title=League tables: the top universities|date=18 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Rankings and reputation===\n{{Infobox UK university rankings\n| ARWU_W = 201\u2013300\n| QS_W = =78\n| THE_W = 133\n| LEIDEN_W = 97\n| LINE_1 = 0\n| Complete = 6\n| The_Guardian = 5\n| Times/Sunday_Times = 7\n| LINE_2 = 0\n| TEF = Gold\n}}\n[[File:Durham Law School.jpg|thumb|right|[[Durham Law School]]]]\n\n<!-- note RAE/REF ratings discussed under \"research\" above -->\nDurham University's Strategic Plan 2017\u20132027 defines targets of being in the top 5 nationally on the Times/Sunday Times league table, of having 50 per cent of eligible subjects in the top 50 globally on the QS world rankings, and of being in the top three UK institutions by citations per academic staff member.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/strategy2027/performance/|title=Measuring our Performance|work=University Strategy 2017\u20132027|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=25 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe earlier 2010\u20132020 strategic plan called for it \"to be in the top 5 universities in major UK league tables\" (defined as the Times/Sunday Times Good University Guide and the Complete University Guide) and \"to be in the top 50 universities in the Times Higher Education world rankings by 2020\".<ref name=kpi2015>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/treasurer/financial_statements/Financial_Statements_2015.pdf|title=Financial Statements for the year ended 31 July 2015|publisher=Durham University|page=7}}</ref> The first objective was met in 2012 and 2015, the second remains as yet unmet, with Durham ranking 70th in the world in 2015.<ref name=kpi2015/> The previous 2005\u20132010 strategic plan called for Durham \"to be ranked among the top 30 universities in Europe and the top 100 in the world in the Times Higher Education Supplement international league tables\";<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/treasurer/financial_statements/947FinancialStatementsALL_A4.pdf|title=Financial Statements for the year ended 31 July 2009|publisher=Durham University|page=6}}</ref> Durham ranked 85th in the world (19th in Europe) in 2010 and has since maintained its position in the top 100.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The Guardian|title=The top 100 universities 2010 \u2013 how the Times Higher Education ranks them|url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/datablog/2010/sep/16/top-100-universities-times-higher-education|author=Simon Rogers|date=16 September 2010}}</ref>\n\n;National\nDurham consistently places in the top ten in [[rankings of universities in the United Kingdom]].<ref group=note>It has ranked in the Times top ten since the 2004 tables, the Complete University Guide top ten since it was founded in 2007 (2008 tables) and the Guardian top ten since the 2012 tables.{{cite web|title=Domestic Ranking of British Universities over a 10-Year Period|url=http://theuniversitybuzz.blogspot.co.uk/2017/01/domestic-ranking-of-british.html|publisher=The University Buzz}}</ref> The 2018 ''[[Complete University Guide]]'' ranks Durham 6th overall,<ref name=\"CUG 2018 Durham\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk/durham/performance|title=Durham University|publisher=Complete University Guide|accessdate=25 May 2017}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]] University Guide 2018'' ranks Durham 4th overall<ref name=\"Durham Guardian\"/> and the 2018 ''[[The Times]]/[[Sunday Times]] Good University Guide'' ranks Durham 5th overall.\n\n;Subject\n\nIn the 2020 ''[[Complete University Guide]]'' subject rankings, Durham is top in the UK for English and Music. The university ranks second for French, Geography & Environmental Science, Iberian Languages, Middle Eastern & African Studies, and Theology & Religious Studies. Third for Archaeology, Chemistry, Classics & Ancient History, German, History, Italian, and Russian & East European Languages.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk/durham/performance|title=League Table Performance \u2013 Durham University|website=thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk|access-date=12 May 2019}}</ref> With 30/33 subjects ranked in the top 10, Durham is one of only four universities (along with [[University of Oxford|Oxford]], [[Cambridge]], and [[Imperial College London]]) to have over 90 per cent of their subjects in the top 10 in this ranking.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk/league-tables/who-ranks-top-of-the-tables-by-subject-2020/|title=Who Ranks Top of the Tables by Subject 2020|website=thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk|access-date=12 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn ''[[The Guardian]]'' 2018 subject rankings Durham ranks first in Archaeology, second in Education, and third in Chemistry, Earth Sciences, English, Geography & Environmental Studies, and Religious Studies & Theology.<ref name=\"Durham Guardian\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/news/newsitem/?itemno=31396|title=Durham ranked 4th in The Guardian University Guide|accessdate=25 May 2017|date=16 May 2017|publisher=Durham University}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2018 ''[[The Times]]/[[Sunday Times]] Good University Guide'' subject rankings, Durham is top in music and joint top in English.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/news/newsitem/?itemno=32371|title=Durham ranked 5th in the UK|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=26 November 2017}}</ref> It also ranks second in archaeology and forensic science, East and South Asian studies, geography and environmental science, history, Iberian languages, Italian, and theology and religious studies; joint second in Russian and East European languages: and third in chemistry and education.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://st.hitcreative.com/education/university_guide/active/UniversityGuide/index/goto/league-tables|title=Good University Guide 2017|accessdate=26 November 2017|work=[[The Times]]/[[The Sunday Times]]}}</ref>\n\n;International\nDurham has been placed in the top 100 universities in the world in both the ''[[Times Higher Education]]'' (THE) and [[Quacquarelli Symonds]] (QS) rankings since 2010.<ref group=note>The university monitored both THE and QS rankings as part of its strategic plan until 2017, but did not monitor the Academic Ranking of World Universities (ARWU) or other international rankings.{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/strategic.planning/dataandanalysis/performanceevaluation/leaguetables/|title=Benchmarking League Table Performance|accessdate=24 February 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306103625/https://www.dur.ac.uk/strategic.planning/dataandanalysis/performanceevaluation/leaguetables/|archive-date=6 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Times Higher Education World University Rankings]] for 2017 place Durham 96th in the world (12th in the UK) in 2016, down from 70th in 2015. In the individual subject area rankings for 2016-7, Durham is placed 60th (2015-6: 83rd) in the world (8th in the UK) for physical sciences,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/world-university-rankings/2017/subject-ranking/physical-sciences#!/page/0/length/25/country/2784/sort_by/rank_label/sort_order/asc/cols/rank_only|title= World University Rankings 2016\u20132017 by subject: physical sciences |accessdate=30 September 2016|work=Times Higher Education}}</ref> 60th (2015-6: 36th) in the world (9th in the UK) for social sciences,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/world-university-rankings/2017/subject-ranking/social-sciences#!/page/0/length/25/country/2784/sort_by/rank_label/sort_order/asc/cols/rank_only|title= World University Rankings 2016\u20132017 by subject: social sciences |accessdate=30 September 2016|work=Times Higher Education}}</ref> and 29th (2015-6: 28th)in the world (6th in the UK) for arts and humanities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/world-university-rankings/2017/subject-ranking/arts-and-humanities#!/page/0/length/25/country/2784/sort_by/rank_label/sort_order/asc/cols/rank_only|title= World University Rankings 2016\u20132017 by subject: arts and humanities |accessdate=30 September 2016|work=Times Higher Education}}</ref> Durham is not ranked on the other top-100 subject tables (business and economics; computer science; engineering and technology; life sciences; clinical, pre-clinical and health). Durham re-entered the [[Times Higher Education World Reputation Rankings]] in the 91\u2013100 band in 2017, having not been ranked in the top 100 in 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/world-university-rankings/2017/reputation-ranking#!/page/0/length/25/locations/GB/sort_by/rank/sort_order/asc/cols/stats|title= World Reputation Rankings 2017|work=[[Times Higher Education]]|accessdate=14 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/world-university-rankings/2016/reputation-ranking#!/page/0/length/25/locations/GB/sort_by/rank/sort_order/asc/cols/stats|title=World Reputation Rankings 2016|work=[[Times Higher Education]]|accessdate=14 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe [[QS World University Rankings]] 2018 places Durham 78th in the world (12th in the UK), down from 74th in 2016/2017 and 61st in 2015 \u2013 the fall experienced by many UK universities in the rankings has been attributed to uncertainty over [[Brexit]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/student/into-university/applying/how-brexit-is-affecting-british-universities-funding-issues-higher-education-qs-world-university-a7227911.html|title= Post-Brexit uncertainty and long-term funding issues hit UK higher education, university rankings show|date=6 September 2016|author=Aftab Al|newspaper=[[The Independent]]}}</ref> In the \"faculty\" subject areas for 2017, Durham ranks 45th in the world (9th in the UK) for arts and humanities,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/university-subject-rankings/2017/arts-humanities|title=Arts and Humanities|publisher=QS Quacquarelli Symonds Limited|accessdate=8 July 2017}}</ref> 242nd in the world (26th in the UK) for engineering and technology,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/university-subject-rankings/2017/engineering-technology|title=Engineering and Technology|publisher=QS Quacquarelli Symonds Limited|accessdate=8 July 2017}}</ref> 368th in the world (31st in the UK) for life sciences and medicine,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/university-subject-rankings/2017/life-sciences-medicine|title=Life Sciences and Medicine|publisher=QS Quacquarelli Symonds Limited|accessdate=8 July 2017}}</ref> 72nd in the world (8th in the UK) for natural sciences,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/university-subject-rankings/2017/natural-sciences|title=Natural Sciences|publisher=QS Quacquarelli Symonds Limited|accessdate=8 July 2017}}</ref> and 98th in the world (13th in the UK) for social sciences and management.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/university-subject-rankings/2017/social-sciences-management|title=Social Sciences and Management|publisher=QS Quacquarelli Symonds Limited|accessdate=8 July 2017}}</ref> In the subject rankings for 2017, Durham was ranked 3rd in the world for theology, divinity and religious studies, 4th for archaeology and 7th for geography. Earth and marine sciences (24th), anthropology (35th), English language and literature (35th), history (37th) and law and legal studies (40th) also featured in the top 50 in the world, while Durham also ranked in the top 100 for chemistry, modern languages, physics and astronomy, politics, psychology, and sociology.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/research/news/item/?id=27614&itemno=27614|title=Durham rises in prestigious world rankings|date=22 March 2016|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=23 March 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"QS Durham\">{{cite web|url=http://www.topuniversities.com/universities/durham-university|publisher=QS Quacquarelli Symonds Limited|title=Durham University|accessdate=8 July 2017}}</ref> One of Durham's 2017\u20132027 strategic goals is to have half of its subjects in the top 50 globally on the QS ranking; in 2017 it had 8 in the top 50 out of 27 subjects ranked (30 per cent).<ref name=\"QS Durham\"/> Another 2017\u20132027 strategic goal is for Durham to be in the top three universities in the UK for research citations per faculty; the QS ranking 2018 placed Durham fourth in the UK (82nd globally) for this measure, behind the [[London Business School]], Cambridge and Oxford,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/world-university-rankings/2018|title=QS World University Rankings 2018 \u2013 Rankings indicators \u2013 Citations per faculty|publisher=QS Quacquarelli Symonds Limited|accessdate=10 June 2017}}</ref> slipping from second in the UK (43rd globally) in 2017.<ref name=\"Durham Guardian\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/world-university-rankings/2016|title=QS World University Rankings 2017 \u2013 Rankings indicators \u2013 Citations per faculty|publisher=QS Quacquarelli Symonds Limited|accessdate=25 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Shanghai [[Academic Ranking of World Universities]] placed Durham in the 201\u2013300 bracket. In individual subject areas, Durham is placed in the 51\u201375 bracket for science and the 101\u2013150 bracket for social science, it is not ranked in engineering, life sciences or medical sciences. In individual subjects, the ARWU places Durham 27th in the world (5th in the UK) for physics, and gives no rank for chemistry, mathematics, computer science, or economics/business.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shanghairanking.com/World-University-Rankings/Durham-University.html|title=Durham University|work=Academic Ranking of World Universities|accessdate=25 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe [[CWTS Leiden Ranking]], based on bibliometric indicators of research, placed Durham 89th in the world (16th in the UK) in 2018. In scientific subject areas, Durham ranked 251st in the world (35th in the UK) for biomedical and health science, 104th in the world (26th in the UK) for life and earth sciences, 389th in the world (36th in the UK) for mathematics and computer science, 76th in the world (10th in the UK) for physical sciences and engineering, and 69th in the world (11th in the UK) in social sciences and humanities.<ref name=Leiden2018/>\n\nThe [[Round University Ranking]] placed Durham 94th in the world (12th in the UK) in 2016. In certain subject areas, Durham ranked 30th in the world (8th in the UK) for the humanities, 44th in the world (12th in the UK) for social sciences, 153rd in the world (27th in the UK) for technical sciences, 191st in the world (21st in the UK) for natural sciences, 269th in the world (33rd in the UK) for life sciences and 418th in the world (61st in the UK) for medical sciences.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://roundranking.com/ranking.html|title=Round University Rankings 2016|publisher=RUR Rankings Agency|accessdate=22 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n;Employment\nIn 2017, Durham had the highest graduate employment rate of any UK university, with 97.9 per cent of its graduates in work or further study three and a half years after graduation.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Grove|first1=Jack|title=Russell Group dominates UK's graduate employment charts|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/russell-group-dominates-uk-graduate-employment-charts|accessdate=11 August 2017|work=Times Higher Education}}</ref> In 2015, Durham was placed 47th in the world (8th in the UK) in QS's pilot global employability ranking,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iu.qs.com/qs-graduate-employability-rankings-year-2016-pilot/|title=QS Graduate Employability Rankings \u2013 Year 2016 (Pilot)|publisher=QS Quacquarelli Symonds Limited|accessdate=16 February 2016}}</ref> and 8th in the UK for graduate prospects by the Times and Sunday Times 2016.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=Times Higher Education|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/carousels/top-25-uk-universities-graduate-employment|title=Top 25 UK universities for graduate employment|date=21 September 2015}}</ref> It did not, however, feature in the Times Higher Education Top 150 Global Employability rankings,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/carousels/global-employability-university-ranking-2015-results|title=Global Employability University Ranking 2015 results|date=6 November 2015|newspaper=Times Higher Education|author=Ellie Bothwell}}</ref> but was placed joint 16th in the UK for the employability of its graduates according to recruiters of the UK's major companies.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/student/news/best-uk-universities-chosen-major-employers|title=The best UK universities chosen by major employersdate=12 November 2015|newspaper=Times Higher Education|author=Carly Minsky}}</ref> The ''High Fliers Research'' UK graduate market report for 2016 placed Durham 8th in its table of universities targeted by the largest number of top employees.<ref name=highfliers2016>{{cite web|url=http://www.highfliers.co.uk/download/2016/graduate_market/GMReport16.pdf|page=33|title=The Graduate Market in 2016|publisher=High Fliers Research Limited|date=18 January 2016|accessdate=10 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n;Other indications\nIn 2013, Durham was judged to have the best quality of student life in the country in the inaugural [[Lloyds Bank]] rankings and has never (in 2015) been out of the top three, coming in third in 2014 and second in 2015.<ref>{{cite news|title=Out of 91 UK universities, Durham students have the best quality of life|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/student/news/out-of-91-uk-universities-durham-students-have-the-best-quality-of-life-8844763.html|newspaper=The Independent|date=28 September 2013|location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Durham Students top of the pile in first University Quality of Student Life Survey|url=http://www.lloydsbankinggroup.com/media/pdfs/LTSB/2013/2809_Student_Life.pdf|accessdate=3 October 2013|date=28 September 2015|publisher=Lloyds Bank|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004220307/http://www.lloydsbankinggroup.com/media/pdfs/LTSB/2013/2809_Student_Life.pdf|archivedate=4 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lloydsbankinggroup.com/Media/Press-Releases/2014/lloyds-bank/loughborough-university-races-to-the-top-of-the-lloyds-bank-quality-of-student-life-survey/|title=Loughborough University races to the top of the Lloyds Bank Quality of Student Life Survey|accessdate=4 October 2015|date=3 October 2014|publisher=Lloyd's Bank}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lloydsbankinggroup.com/Media/Press-Releases/2015/lloyds-bank/loughborough-university-retains-top-spot-in-the-2015-lloyds-bank-student-life-survey/|title=Loughborough University retains top spot in the 2015 Lloyds Bank Student Life Survey|date=21 September 2015|accessdate=4 October 2015|publisher=Lloyd's Bank}}</ref>\nThe ''Complete University Guide'' ranked Durham as the 29th safest university in England and Wales for crime in 2016, although with large differences between the two campuses: Durham City had 24.4 incidents per 1000 residents while the Queen's Campus in Stockton had 56.0 incidents per 1000 residents.<ref>{{cite web|title=Crime in University Cities|url=http://www.thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk/crime-in-university-cities/|accessdate=25 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nDurham is listed as part of the [[Sutton Trust 30]] \"most highly selective\" British universities,<ref name=\"Old school 'key to student place'\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/education/7003253.stm|title=Old school 'key to student place'|publisher=BBC |accessdate=31 January 2009 | date=20 September 2007}}</ref> and is one of the few universities to have won [[University Challenge]] more than once (1977 and 2000).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blanchflower.org/uc/winners_teams.html |title=University Challenge \u2013 Series Champions |publisher=Blanchflower.org |date=n.d.|accessdate=1 November 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Student life==\n{{See also|List of social activities at Durham University}}\n\n===Residential life===\n[[File:Great Hall.jpg|thumb|The [[University College, Durham#Great Hall|Great Hall]] at [[University College, Durham|University College]] \u2013 communal dining is traditional at most Durham colleges]]\nDurham students belong to a college for the duration of their time at the university. Most students live in their college for the first year of their undergraduate life, then choose to 'live-out' in their second year, and subsequently have the option of moving back into college for their final year, usually via a ballot system.<ref name=\"DSU: QAA Student Written Submission\">{{cite web|url= http://www.dsu.org.uk/export/sites/Durham/upload_gallery/Appendix_I_-_QAA_Student_Written_Submission.pdf|title=DSU: QAA Student Written Submission|publisher=Durham Students' Union (DSU)|accessdate=5 February 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090326202147/http://www.dsu.org.uk/export/sites/Durham/upload_gallery/Appendix_I_-_QAA_Student_Written_Submission.pdf|archivedate=26 March 2009}}</ref> The Colleges provide a key role in the pastoral care and social centre of students with each running a college tutorial system,<ref name=\"DSU: QAA Student Written Submission\"/><ref name=\"Colleges: Support Structure\">{{cite web|url= http://www.dur.ac.uk/colleges/experience/support/|title=College support structure|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=5 February 2009}}</ref> along with [[Junior Common Room|JCR]]s providing events and societies for undergraduate members, [[Middle Common Room|MCR]]s being a centre for postgraduate students and the [[Senior Common Room|SCR]]s for the college officers, fellows and tutors. These common rooms are run by an executive committee, usually headed by a President. Some colleges use other titles for the head of their JCR: Hatfield retains \"Senior Man\", having rejected a motion to move to \"JCR President\" in May 2014<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thetab.com/uk/durham/2014/05/15/hatfield-crush-senior-man-13235|title=Hatfield JCR crush motion to rename Senior Man|accessdate=3 October 2015|publisher=[[The Tab]]}}</ref> and a motion to allow the incumbent to choose between \"Senior Man\", \"Senior Woman\" or \"Senior Student\" in January 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.palatinate.org.uk/hatfield-college-jcr-rejects-motion-to-change-jcr-president-title-to-\u2018senior-student\u2019/|title=Hatfield College JCR rejects motion to change JCR President title to \u2018Senior Student\u2019|newspaper=[[Palatinate (newspaper)|Palatinate]]|date=24 January 2016|author=Charlie Taylor-Kroll}}</ref> University College voted to allow \"Senior Man\", \"Senior Woman\" or \"Senior Student\" in June 2015,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://community.dur.ac.uk/student.elections/university/index.php?results=186|publisher=University College JCR|title=University College online voting: Results|accessdate=3 October 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160201065236/https://community.dur.ac.uk/student.elections/university/index.php?results=186|archivedate=1 February 2016}}</ref> the incumbent switching to using \"Senior Student\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/university.college/about/staff/|title=Who's Who|publisher=University College|accessdate=3 October 2015}}</ref> and St Chad's uses \"Senior Man\" or \"Senior Woman\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/education-30211616|title='Sexist' job title stays at University College, Durham|date=26 November 2014|accessdate=3 October 2015|publisher=BBC}}</ref>\n\nEach college has a unique identity and a variety of facilities for students ranging from computer rooms and libraries to tennis courts and gyms.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/university.college/undergraduate/facilities/|title=University College : Facilities|publisher=Durham University}}</ref> In 2015, Durham University was voted number 1 in the UK for best university WiFi, on the review platform StudentCrowd.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.studentcrowd.com/article/3-best-universities-for-wifi-2015|title=Best Uni Awards 2015 \u2013 Wifi and Internet|author=Paul Humphreys|date=11 August 2015|work=studentcrowd.com}}</ref> Most colleges have their own sports teams and compete in the collegiate leagues (such as [[Durham College Rowing]]) and have their own theatre company and orchestra which operate parallel to the university level sports teams and organisations.<ref name=\"Colleges: Sports and societies\">{{cite web|url= http://www.dur.ac.uk/colleges/experience/sport/|title=Sports and societies|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=5 February 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Student organisations===\n[[File:Durham Union Palace Green.jpg|thumb|The [[Durham Union Society]] is the university's largest student society]]\nApproximately 200 student clubs and organisations run on Durham's campuses, covering academic, arts, culture and faith, hobbies and games, outdoors, politics, law and music interests.<ref name=\"DSU: societies\">{{cite web|url=http://www.durhamsu.com/main-menu/activities/societies|title=Societies|publisher=DSU|accessdate=15 February 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160125212006/http://www.durhamsu.com/main-menu/activities/societies|archivedate=25 January 2016}}</ref> [[Durham Students' Union]] (DSU) charters and provides most of the funding for these organisations. The DSU runs a Comedy Caf\u00e9, Fresher's Ball, Silent Discos and Vintage fashion fair.<ref name=\"DSU: Events\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dsu.org.uk/pages/events/ |title=Durham Student's Union: Events |publisher=DSU |accessdate=5 February 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090224043511/http://dsu.org.uk/pages/events/ |archivedate=24 February 2009 }}</ref> The largest independent student society in Durham is the [[Durham Union Society]], founded in 1842 as Durham's Student Debating & Union Society.\n\n===Civic engagement===\nDurham's Student Community Action (SCA) oversees 45 volunteer projects in Durham and the surrounding area.<ref name=\"DSU Handbook 2007\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dsu.org.uk/export/sites/Durham/upload_gallery/DSU_Handbook_2007.pdf|title=DAU Handbook 2007|publisher=Durham Students' Union|accessdate=5 February 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090326202139/http://www.dsu.org.uk/export/sites/Durham/upload_gallery/DSU_Handbook_2007.pdf|archivedate=26 March 2009}}</ref> Colleges often organise their own outreach and charitable activities.\n\nDurham University Charity Kommittee (or DUCK) is the university's equivalent of student's [[rag week]].<ref name=\"Community Activities\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/about/community/|title=Durham University: Community Activities|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=5 February 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100413093908/http://www.dur.ac.uk/about/community/|archivedate=13 April 2010 }}</ref> Originally set up as a week event, DUCK has become a permanent feature in raising money for local or national charities with events taking place throughout the year. Activities take place within each college, as well as centrally over the university.<ref name=\"DUCK: Get Involved!\">{{cite web|url=http://duck.dsu.org.uk/?p=involved/index|title=DUCK: Get Involved!|publisher=DUCK|accessdate=5 February 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090212201120/http://duck.dsu.org.uk/?p=involved%2Findex|archivedate=12 February 2009}}</ref> DUCK also organises expeditions to the Himalayas,<ref name=\"DUCK: Expeditions\">{{cite web|url=http://duck.dsu.org.uk/?p=expeditions/index|title=DUCK: BE ON OUR NEXT TREK!|publisher=DUCK|accessdate=5 February 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090212204828/http://duck.dsu.org.uk/?p=expeditions%2Findex|archivedate=12 February 2009}}</ref> Jordan<ref name=\"DUCK: Expeditions\"/> and Mount Kilimanjaro<ref name=\"DUCK: Expeditions\"/> to raise money as well as being involved in the university-run 'Project Sri Lanka'<ref name=\"Project Sri Lanka\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/project.srilanka/|title=Durham University: Project Sri Lanka|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=5 February 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090118163048/http://www.dur.ac.uk/project.srilanka/|archivedate=18 January 2009}}</ref> and 'Project Thailand'.<ref name=\"Project Thailand\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/project.thailand/|title=Durham University: Project Thailand|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=5 February 2009}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Dunelm3.jpg|thumb|Dunelm House, home of the [[Durham Students' Union]]]]\nTeam Durham Community Outreach is a sports community programme aimed at giving support and opportunities through the use of sport.<ref name=\"Community Activities\"/> The programme runs projects such as Summer Camps for children from the Youth Engagement Service and fostered backgrounds along with providing coaching at local schools as well as participating in sports in action.<ref name=\"Sports in Action\">{{cite web|url=http://www.teamdurham.com/community/sportinaction/|title=Team Durham: Sports in Action|publisher=Team Durham|accessdate=5 February 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Town and gown relations===\n\nThe relationship between [[town and gown|the university and the wider city]] has not always been free of tension.<ref>{{cite web |title=Council condemns \u2018insular and selfish\u2019 Durham University students |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/council-condemns-insular-andselfish-durham-university-students-kctv0rszz |website=The Times |accessdate=6 November 2018 }}</ref> University plans for expansion have also faced local opposition.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Banfield |first1=Joe |title=Students may be wrecking Durham. But the university is to blame|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2018/jun/29/students-durham-university-blame-council-selfish |website=The Guardian |accessdate=6 November 2018  |date=29 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Gaspar |first1=Clara |title=Durham University expansion plans prompt anger from local community |url=https://www.palatinate.org.uk/durham-university-expansion-plans-prompt-anger-from-local-community/ |website=Palatinate |accessdate=6 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Student media===\n''[[Palatinate (newspaper)|Palatinate]]'', Durham's independent student run fortnightly newspaper, has been continually published since 1948.<ref name=Echo>{{cite news|title=Future of student paper at risk |work=The Northern Echo |date=7 June 2005 |url=http://archive.thenorthernecho.co.uk/2005/6/7/10844.html |accessdate=28 August 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929110713/http://archive.thenorthernecho.co.uk/2005/6/7/10844.html |archivedate=29 September 2007 }}</ref> Notable former editors include [[George Alagiah]],<ref name=Echo/> [[Hunter Davies]],<ref>{{cite news|first=Jackie |last=McGlone |title=A life in the day of Hunter Davies |work=[[Scotland on Sunday]] |location=Edinburgh |date=20 August 2006 |url=http://living.scotsman.com/people.cfm?id=1212712006 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120721165449/http://living.scotsman.com/people.cfm?id=1212712006 |url-status=dead |archive-date=21 July 2012 |accessdate=28 August 2007 }}</ref> [[Piers Merchant]], [[Timothy Laurence|Sir Timothy Laurence]],<ref>{{cite news|first=Stuart |last=Qualtrough |title=People's Prince Wills may go to Durham University |work=Sunday Mirror |location=London |date=23 May 1999 |url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4161/is_19990523/ai_n14489282 |accessdate=28 August 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090211074040/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4161/is_19990523/ai_n14489282 |archivedate=11 February 2009 }}</ref> [[Jeremy Vine]]<ref name=Echo /> and [[Harold Evans]].<ref name=Echo />\n\n[[Purple Radio]] is Durham's student radio station. It broadcasts live from the [[Durham Students' Union|DSU]] 24 hours a day during term time. The station has existed since the 1980s and is a recognised DSU society. Two daily news bulletins are broadcast every weekday, as well as a Breakfast Show and an Evening Show.<ref name=\"Purple Radio Schedule\">{{cite web|url=http://www.purpleradio.co.uk/schedule|title=Purple Radio Schedule|accessdate=10 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe Bubble, founded in 2010, is an online magazine based at the university covering various subjects, including student and university news.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thebubble.org.uk/site/about|title=The Bubble|accessdate=2 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Sport===\n[[File:Durham regatta Univ College Durham v's Newcastle Uni.jpg|left|thumb|[[University College Boat Club (Durham)|University College Boat Club]] and Newcastle University racing at [[Durham Regatta]]]]\nSport at Durham is a key aspect of student life with some 92 per cent of students regularly taking part.<ref name=\"Sports Uni 2015\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/undergraduate/life/times-sport-uni-2015/|title=Durham University named The Times and Sunday Times Sports University of the Year 2015|work=The Sunday Times|date=21 September 2014|author=Zoe Thomas|accessdate=15 February 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305140224/https://www.dur.ac.uk/undergraduate/life/times-sport-uni-2015/|archive-date=5 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> As of 2018, the university caters for more than 50 different sports, organised under the umbrella name of [[Durham University Athletic Union|Team Durham]], with many being predominantly based at the Graham Sports Centre at Maiden Castle. This facility has 26 courts and pitches for sports ranging from rugby to lacrosse to netball, additional facilities include eleven boat houses and two astroturfs, a fitness studio, and a weights room.<ref>{{cite web |title=University Performance Programmes \u2013 Durham University |url=https://www.teamdurham.com/universitysport/ |website=Team Durham |accessdate=10 October 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Our Facilities \u2013 Durham University |url=https://www.teamdurham.com/facilities/ |website=Team Durham |accessdate=10 October 2018 }}</ref> The university also owns [[The Racecourse]] which has a further eight courts and pitches for cricket, rugby (union and league), squash and football.<ref name=\"Team Durham: Facilities\">{{cite web|url=http://www.teamdurham.com/about/hello/|title=Team Durham: Facilities|publisher=Team Durham|accessdate=5 February 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090302220743/http://www.teamdurham.com/about/hello/|archivedate=2 March 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe university is recognised as a [[Durham MCC University|Centre of Cricketing Excellence]] (one of only six [[MCC Universities|university centres]] to play first-class matches) by the [[England and Wales Cricket Board]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lords.org/mcc/youth-cricket/mcc-universities/ |title= MCC Universities \u2013 investing in a cricketing education |work=lords.org |date=n.d.|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref> The university also has Performance Centres for [[Rowing (sport)|rowing]], [[lacrosse]], [[tennis]] and [[fencing]].<ref name=\"Team Durham: About\">{{cite web|url=http://www.teamdurham.com/about/|title=Team Durham: About|publisher=Team Durham|accessdate=5 February 2009}}</ref>\n\nDurham has been 2nd across all sports in the [[British Universities & Colleges Sport]] (BUCS) table since 2011/12. In 2014/15 it became only the second University (after Loughborough) to pass 4000 BUCS points and the top university in the country for team sports. Both of these were repeated in 2015/16, which also saw Durham beat its own records for total BUCS scores in League and Cup competitions.<ref>{{cite web|date=26 June 2016|url=https://www.teamdurham.com/universitysport/|title=University Sport|accessdate=15 February 2015|publisher=Team Durham}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.teamdurham.com/about/directorsviews/|title=Dean's Update|accessdate=30 August 2016|publisher=Team Durham}}</ref> In rowing, it has a good record at the [[University rowing (UK)|BUCS Regatta]], having won the title for ten consecutive years (2004\u20132013) before coming second in 2014, then regaining the title in 2015<ref name=\"Stage is set for rowing showdown\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/news/newsitem/?itemno=7929|title=Stage is set for rowing showdown|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=7 May 2009}}</ref> before losing it again in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldrowing.com/news/newcastle-triumphant-2016-bucs-regatta|title= Newcastle triumphant at 2016 BUCS regatta|date=5 May 2016|website=World Rowing|accessdate=30 August 2016}}</ref> In 2017 the club finished in 7th place, from 52 ranked teams.<ref>{{cite web |title=BUCS Regatta 2017 \u2013 Overall Victor Ludorum |url=https://www.bucs.org.uk/core/core_picker/download.asp?id=35259 |accessdate=10 October 2018}}</ref> [[Durham University Boat Club]] also competes in [[Durham Regatta]] and [[the Boat Race of the North]] against Newcastle University, which ran 1997 \u2013 2010 and was revived in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thetab.com/uk/newcastle/2015/04/25/boating-hell-newcastle-vs-durham-boat-race-back-11054|title=Aboat time! Newcastle vs Durham boat race is back|publisher=[[The Tab]]|date=25 April 2015|accessdate=3 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Durham University Racecourse.JPG|thumb|[[The Racecourse]] is one of the university's main sites for sporting facilities]]\nDurham University is one of four universities to compete in the unofficial \"Doxbridge\" Tournament in Dublin, a sporting competition between Durham University, the University of Oxford, the University of Cambridge and the University of York.<ref name=\"Doxbridge\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsparty.co.uk/doxbridge/|title=Doxbridge|publisher=Sweet Chariot Ltd|accessdate=15 February 2016}}</ref> Durham colleges also compete officially with colleges from the [[University of York]] in the annual College Varsity tournament held since 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.palatinate.org.uk/?p=46289|title=Durham wins College Varsity|date=3 March 2014|accessdate=3 October 2015|work=[[Palatinate (newspaper)|Palatinate]]}}</ref> Durham won this tournament in 2014 (in York) and 2015 (in Durham) before York recorded their first victory in 2016 (in York).  Durham also competes again long-standing BUCS champions [[Loughborough University]] in the 'BUCS Varsity', a coordinated set of BUCS matches across multiple sports, and in a competition between Durham colleges and Loughborough halls of residence, both of which were organised for the first time in 2015/16. Durham won the BUCS Varsity both home and away in 2015/16 but lost the colleges' competition, held in Durham.<ref>{{cite news|work=[[Palatinate (newspaper)|Palatinate]]|date=6 May 2016|author=Matt Roberts|title= Durham denied Varsity hat-trick over Loughborough|url=http://www.palatinate.org.uk/durham-denied-varsity-hat-trick-over-loughborough/}}</ref>\n\n[[Palatinate (award)|Palatinate]]s are given to athletes who demonstrate a high standard (such as international representation) in their sport. It is similar to a [[blue (university sport)|blue]] awarded at other British universities. The award is named after the colour palatinate associated with the university.\n\n===Music and drama===\n[[File:Durham University Botanic Garden.jpg|thumb|[[Durham University Botanic Garden]]]]\nThe central body for theatre at the university is known as [[Durham Student Theatre]] (DST), with around 700 active student members throughout 27 separate, student-run theatre societies as of 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.durhamstudenttheatre.org/|title=Durham Student Theatre|accessdate=14 October 2018|publisher=Durham Student Theatre}}</ref> The Assembly Rooms is the university-owned theatre, located on [[The Bailey]], which hosts a number of student productions each term. Alongside this, student drama productions are held at Durham City's Gala Theatre (notably Durham University Light Opera Group (DULOG) and Durham Opera Ensemble (DOE), which both perform one show in the Gala every year in Epiphany term), venues around Durham University and within the colleges, [[Durham Castle]], [[Durham Cathedral]], as well as in national and international venues and the [[Edinburgh Fringe Festival]].\n\nSince 1975, the university has played host to the Durham Drama Festival which celebrates new theatrical and dramatic material written by Durham students.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.palatinate.org.uk/?p=54664|title=Durham Drama Festival 2015|work=[[Palatinate (newspaper)|Palatinate]]|accessdate=3 October 2015|date=4 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe Durham Revue is the university's [[sketch comedy]] group. Tracing its roots back to the early 1950s, and known under its current name since 1988, the group consists of six writer-performers (auditioned, interviewed and chosen each Michaelmas Term) and produces a series of shows each year. The group performs annually with [[Cambridge University]]'s [[Footlights]] and [[Oxford University]]'s [[The Oxford Revue]], as well as at the [[Edinburgh Fringe Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/experiencedurham/theatre/companies/durhamrevue/|title=Durham Revue|publisher=Durham Revue|accessdate=3 October 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160201065236/https://www.dur.ac.uk/experiencedurham/theatre/companies/durhamrevue/|archivedate=1 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nMusic is particularly marked by the Durham University Chamber Choir and Orchestral Societies (including the Palatinate Orchestra<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/palatinate.orchestra/ |title=Durham University Palatinate Orchestra |publisher=Durham University |date=n.d.|accessdate=1 November 2011}}</ref>). The Durham Cathedral Choir offers choral scholarships to male students, and several of the colleges (University, Hatfield, Hild Bede, St John's, St Chad's, St Cuthbert's, Grey and St Mary's) also offer organ and/or choral scholarships, as does the Catholic Chaplaincy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.musicdurham.org/scholarships/|accessdate=3 October 2015|publisher=Music Durham |title=Scholarships}}</ref>\n\nDurham is also home to the oldest [[Gamelan]] [[slendro]] set in the UK with an active community group and an artist in residence. The instruments are currently housed in the Grade II listed [[Durham University Observatory]].<ref>{{cite web|title=DGS Observatory|url=http://www.durhamgamelan.org.uk/where.aspx|accessdate=8 June 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130526133033/http://www.durhamgamelan.org.uk/where.aspx|archive-date=26 May 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> Recently a set tuned to peloghas been added meaning that Durham now has a complete Gamelan orchestra. In recent years, the Durham Gamelan Society has performed at several major public events such as the Gong Festivals 2011 & 2012<ref>{{cite web|title=Gong Festival 2012|url=http://gongfestival.co.uk/|accessdate=8 June 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120625122957/http://www.gongfestival.co.uk/|archive-date=25 June 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> and at the Gamelan Lokananta all night [[wayang kulit]] in celebration of York University's Gamelan Sekar Petak 30th anniversary in 2012,<ref>{{cite web|title=Gathering of the Gamelans|url=http://www.york.ac.uk/music/conferences/gathering-of-the-gamelans/ | accessdate=8 June 2012}}</ref> as well as many smaller performances for the International Students' Festival and college events.\n{{clear}}\n\n==Notable alumni==\n{{further|List of Durham University people}}\n\n[[File:General Sir Francis Richard Dannatt, KCB, CBE, MC - York 2007-09-22 (RLH).jpg|upright|thumb|General [[Richard Dannatt, Baron Dannatt|Sir Richard Dannatt]], [[Chief of the General Staff (United Kingdom)|Chief of the General Staff]]]]\n\nDurham alumni are active through organisations and events such as the annual Reunions, Dinners and Balls. There are 67 Durham associations ranging from international to college and sports affiliated groups that cater for the more than 109,000 living alumni.<ref name=\"Durham Diff Alumni\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/DARO/TheDurhamDifference.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629183326/http://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/DARO/TheDurhamDifference.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=29 June 2011 |title=The Durham Difference |publisher=Durham University |accessdate=3 April 2009 }}</ref>\n\nA number of Durham alumni have made significant contributions in the fields of government, law, science, academia, business, arts, journalism, and athletics, among others. These have included [[Justin Welby]], Archbishop of Canterbury (St John's, 1992), [[Milton Margai|Sir Milton Margai]], first prime minister of [[Sierra Leone]] (MD, 1926),<ref name=\"Sierra Leone People's Party\">{{cite web|url=http://www.slpp.ws/browse.asp?page=438|title=Sierra Leone People's Party Official Biography|publisher=Sierra Leone People's Party|accessdate=14 March 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090104142331/http://www.slpp.ws/browse.asp?page=438|archive-date=4 January 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref> the 7th Queensland Premier [[John Douglas (Queensland politician)|John Douglas]] (BA, 1850),<ref name=\"Douglas, John (1828 - 1904)\">{{cite web|url=http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A040087b.htm|title=Douglas, John (1828\u20131904) |publisher=Australian Dictionary of Biography, Volume 4, Melbourne University Press|accessdate=14 March 2009}}</ref> [[Henry Holland, 1st Viscount Knutsford]], [[Secretary of State for the Colonies]] from 1887 to 1892 (Law, 1847), [[Herbert Laming, Baron Laming]], head of the [[Harold Shipman]] inquiry and the investigation of Britain's social services following the [[death of Baby P]], (Applied Social Studies, 1960),<ref name=\"Lord Laming\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/baby-p/4977353/Lord-Laming-Renowned-Social-Worker.html |title=Lord Laming: Renowned Social Worker |work=The Daily Telegraph, 12 March 2009 |accessdate=14 March 2009 |location=London }}</ref> Dame [[Caroline Swift]], the lead counsel to the Shipman inquiry,<ref name=\"Caroline Swift\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pm.gov.uk/output/Page8467.asp |title=DBE Appointment of Caroline Swift QC and Julia Macur QC |publisher=UK Government |accessdate=14 March 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201201151/http://www.pm.gov.uk/output/Page8467.asp |archivedate=1 December 2008  }}</ref> and [[Mo Mowlam]], [[Secretary of State for Northern Ireland]] at the time of the [[Good Friday Peace Agreement]] (Sociology and Anthropology).<ref name=\"Mo Mowlam\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/news/newsitem/?itemno=3971|title=Mo Mowlam: College Principal recalls a student rebel with a love of people|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=14 March 2009}}</ref> Durham graduate [[Libby Lane]] was the first woman to be consecrated bishop in the [[Church of England]].<ref name=\"Libby Lane\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/11672347.Durham_trained_Rev_Libby_Lane_makes_history_as_Church_of_England_appoints_first_female_bishop/|title= Durham trained Rev Libby Lane makes history as Church of England appoints first female bishop |work=[[The Northern Echo]]|accessdate=17 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nDurham graduates also hold noteworthy positions in the law, including Supreme Court Justices [[Anthony Hughes, Lord Hughes of Ombersley|Lord Hughes]] (Law) and [[Jill Black, Lady Black of Derwent|Lady Black]] (Law), the President of the Family Division [[Andrew McFarlane (judge)|Sir Andrew McFarlane]] and the current Lord Chancellor [[Robert Buckland]] (Law) amongst others.\n\nWithin the military graduates include General [[Richard Dannatt, Baron Dannatt]] (Economic History), the [[Chief of the General Staff (United Kingdom)|Chief of the General Staff]], the professional head of the [[British Army]],<ref name=\"Richard Dannatt\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/defence/4269997/Head-of-Army-General-Sir-Richard-Dannatt-given-honorary-degree.html|title=Head of Army General Sir Richard Dannatt given honorary degree|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=14 March 2009 | location=London | date=16 January 2009}}</ref> Vice-Admiral [[Tim Laurence|Sir Tim Laurence]] (Geography), Chief Executive of [[Defence Estates]] and husband to [[Anne, Princess Royal|The Princess Royal]],<ref name=\"Durham Military Alumni\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/durham.first/spring08/armedforces/|title=Alumni in the Armed Forces|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=14 March 2009}}</ref> and Rear-Admiral [[Amjad Hussain]] (Engineering, 1979) highest-ranking officer from an ethnic minority in the [[British Armed Forces]].<ref name=\"Amjad Hussain\">{{cite news|url=http://news.independent.co.uk/uk/this_britain/article357835.ece |title=Admiral becomes highest-ranking officer from an ethnic minority |work=The Independent |location=London |date=15 April 2006 |accessdate=14 March 2008 |first=Arifa |last=Akbar |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071001030538/http://news.independent.co.uk/uk/this_britain/article357835.ece |archivedate=1 October 2007  }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Tim Smit (6509919409).jpg|thumb|upright|left|[[Tim Smit]], founder of the [[Eden Project]]]]\nIn academia, Durham graduates include [[John D. Barrow]] (Mathematics and Physics, 1974), winner of the [[Templeton Prize]],<ref name=\"John D. Barrow\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/physics/news/?itemno=4169&rehref=%2Fphysics%2Fnews%2Farchive%2F&resubj=%20Headlines|title=Durham graduate wins $1M prize|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=14 March 2009}}</ref> [[George Malcolm Brown|Sir George Malcolm Brown]] (Chemistry & Geology, 1950), invited by [[NASA]] to work on the [[moon rock]] samples recovered from the [[Apollo 11]] lunar mission,<ref name=\"George Malcolm Brown\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/obituary-professor-sir-malcolm-brown-1265092.html|title=Obituary: Professor Sir Malcolm Brown |work=The Independent |location=London |date=4 April 1997|accessdate=14 March 2008 | first1=Kingsley | last1=Dunham | first2=Granville | last2=Holland}}</ref> [[George Rochester]] (1926), co-discoverer of the [[kaon]] sub-atomic particle,<ref name=\"George Rochester\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/professor-george-rochester-729830.html|title=Professor George Rochester|work=The Independent |location=London |date=18 March 2002|accessdate=14 March 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080412070220/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/professor-george-rochester-729830.html |archivedate=12 April 2008}}</ref> alongside [[Harold Jeffreys|Sir Harold Jeffreys]] (Mathematics, 1919), winner of the [[Royal Society]]'s [[Copley Medal]],<ref name=\"Harold Jeffreys\">{{cite web|url=http://www-groups.dcs.st-and.ac.uk/~history/Biographies/Jeffreys.html|title=Harold Jeffreys|publisher=School of Mathematics and Statistics University of St Andrews, Scotland|accessdate=14 March 2009}}</ref> [[Kingsley Charles Dunham|Sir Kingsley Charles Dunham]] (Geology 1930) former director of the [[British Geological Survey]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Dunham, Sir Kingsley Charles (1910\u20132001) |url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/10.1093/ref:odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-75702?rskey=J0ve7q&result=1 |website=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography |accessdate=20 September 2018  }}</ref> and [[E. J. Field]], early discoverer of what are now called [[prion]]s and significant contributor to [[Multiple sclerosis|MS]] research. The current Vice-chancellor of the [[University of Wollongong]] ([[Paul Wellings (academic)|Paul Wellings]]),<ref>{{cite web| url=http://media.uow.edu.au/news/UOW116856.html|title=New Vice-Chancellor takes the helm|author=Bernie Goldie|date=3 January 2012|publisher=University of Wollongong|accessdate=5 March 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Paul Wellings\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2009/feb/24/paul-wellings-1994-group-research|title=Paul Wellings appointed as head of 1994 group|work=The Guardian |location=London |accessdate=14 March 2009 | first=Anthea | last=Lipsett | date=24 February 2009}}</ref> former Vice-chancellor of [[Cardiff University]] ([[David Grant (academic)|David Grant]]),<ref name=\"David Grant\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cardiff.ac.uk/about/whoswho/vicechancellor/index.html|title=Vice-Chancellor: Dr David Grant CBE, FREng, FIEE|publisher=Cardiff University|accessdate=14 March 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100919140628/http://cardiff.ac.uk/about/whoswho/vicechancellor/index.html|archive-date=19 September 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> and [[Chris Higgins (academic)|Chris Higgins]], former vice-chancellor of Durham, are also graduates.<ref name=\"Chris Higgins\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/news/newsitem/?itemno=5338|title=Durham welcomes new Vice Chancellor|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=14 March 2009}}</ref>\n\nSeveral alumni hold top positions in the business world. [[Richard Adams (Traidcraft)|Richard Adams]] (Sociology), founder of [[fair trade]] organisation [[Traidcraft]],<ref name=\"Richard John Adams\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/ceremonies/congregation/adams_richard.pdf|archive-url=https://www.webarchive.org.uk/wayback/archive/20160108194743/https://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/ceremonies/congregation/adams_richard.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=8 January 2016|title=Richard John Adams: Doctor of Civil Law, Durham Cathedral, 28&nbsp;June 2007|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=14 March 2009}}</ref> Paul Hawkins (PhD in Artificial Intelligence), inventor of the [[Hawk-Eye]] ball-tracking system,<ref name=\"Paul Hawkins\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/tennis/paul-hawkins-doctors-antidote-to-court-controversies-470422.html|title=Paul Hawkins: Doctor's antidote to court controversies|work=The Independent |location=London |accessdate=14 March 2009 | date=19 March 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121110022957/http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/tennis/paul-hawkins-doctors-antidote-to-court-controversies-470422.html |archivedate=10 November 2012}}</ref> Dame [[Elisabeth Hoodless]] (Sociology), former Executive Director of [[Community Service Volunteers]],<ref name=\"Elisabeth Hoodless\">{{cite web|url=http://www.csv.org.uk/News/Press+Releases/Press+Releases+Honour.htm |title=Dame Elisabeth puts lifetime achievement down to volunteers |publisher=Community Service Volunteers |accessdate=14 March 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081012002226/http://www.csv.org.uk/News/Press%2BReleases/Press%2BReleases%2BHonour.htm |archivedate=12 October 2008 }}</ref> Sir [[Nick Scheele]] (German, 1966), former President and chief operating officer of [[Ford Motor Company]],<ref name=\"Nick Scheele\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/news/newsitem/?itemno=3328|title=Men of Business and Law to receive honorary degrees|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=14 March 2009}}</ref> entrepreneur [[Brenda Lindiwe Mabaso-Chipeio]], [[David Sproxton]] (Geography, 1976), co-founder of [[Aardman Animations]] who produce [[Wallace & Gromit]],<ref name=\"David Sproxton\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/news/newsitem/?itemno=6679|title=Wallace and Gromit producer, David Sproxton, receives honorary degree|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=14 March 2009}}</ref> [[Tim Smit]] (Archaeology and Anthropology), co-founder of the [[Eden Project]] and [[David Walton (economist)|David Walton]] (Economics and Mathematics, 1984), member of the [[Bank of England]]'s [[Monetary Policy Committee (United Kingdom)|Monetary Policy Committee]].<ref name=\"David Walton\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/david-walton-405087.html|title=Obituary: David Walton|work=The Independent|location=London|accessdate=14 March 2009|date=23 June 2006|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722142744/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/david-walton-405087.html|archivedate=22 July 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Sir Harold Evans 6 Shankbone 2009 NYC.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Harold Evans|Sir Harold Evans]], Editor at Large, [[Reuters]]]]\n[[File:Jonathan Edwards olympics 2000.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Jonathan Edwards (triple jumper)|Jonathan Edwards]], [[Van Mildert College]], Physics]]\nProminent journalists and media specialists include: [[George Entwistle]], former Director-General of the BBC,<ref>{{cite news|author=John Plunkett |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2012/jul/04/george-entwistle-director-general-profile |title=BBC director general: George Entwistle profile |work=The Guardian |date=4 July 2012 |accessdate=1 June 2017}}</ref> [[Harold Evans|Sir Harold Evans]] (Politics and Economics), editor of ''[[The Sunday Times (UK)|The Sunday Times]]'' from 1967 to 1981 and ''[[The Times]]'' from 1981 to 1982, [[Nigel Farndale]] (Philosophy), ''[[Sunday Telegraph]]'' journalist, [[George Alagiah]] (Politics), presenter of the ''[[BBC News at Six]]'', [[Matthew Amroliwala]] (Law and Politics, 1984), [[BBC News]] channel presenter, [[Biddy Baxter]] (1955), former producer of ''[[Blue Peter]]'', [[Arthur Bostrom]] (BA Hons), [[Officer Crabtree]] in  ''[['Allo 'Allo!]]'', [[Nish Kumar]] (English with History), stand-up comedian, [[Jamie Campbell (British documentary filmmaker)|Jamie Campbell]] (English Literature), filmmaker, [[Alastair Fothergill]] (Zoology, 1983), series producer of ''[[The Blue Planet]]'', ''[[Planet Earth (2006 TV series)|Planet Earth]]'' and the director of ''[[Earth (2007 film)|Earth]]'', [[Shelagh Fogarty]] (Modern Languages, 1988), host of the [[BBC Radio 5 Live]] breakfast show, [[Lorraine Heggessey]] (English Language & Literature), the first female Controller of [[BBC One]] and [[Chris Terrill]] (Anthropology and Geography), documentary maker, writer and adventurer. Other BBC hosts who have graduated from Durham include [[Chris Hollins]], sports presenter on [[BBC Breakfast]], [[Gabby Logan]] (Law, 1995), [[Kate Silverton]] (Psychology), [[Jeremy Vine]] (English), [[Tim Willcox]] (Spanish) and [[Nina Hossain]] (English Language and Linguistics).\n\nNoted writers include [[Edward Bradley (writer)|Edward Bradley]] author of ''[[The Adventures of Mr. Verdant Green]]'', [[Minette Walters]] (French, 1971), author of ''[[The Sculptress]]'' and ''[[The Scold's Bridle]]'', [[Graham Hancock]] (Sociology, 1973) author of ''[[The Sign and the Seal]]'', [[Tim FitzHigham]], comedian and author, [[James Kirkup]], travel writer, poet and playwright, [[Patrick Tilley]], science fiction author, and [[Lorna Hill]] (born Lorna Leatham, English, 1926), children's writer, author of the Sadlers Wells series.\n\nIn the sports realm, former England rugby captains [[Will Carling]] (Psychology),<ref name=\"Sports Alumni\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/student/into-university/az-uni-colleges/durham-university-of-458918.html|title=Durham, University of|work=The Independent |location=London |accessdate=14 March 2009 }}</ref> [[Phil de Glanville]] (Economics),<ref name=\"Sports Alumni\"/> and vice-captain [[Will Greenwood]] (Economics, 1994),<ref name=\"Sports Alumni\"/> alongside Olympic gold-medal triple jumper [[Jonathan Edwards (triple jumper)|Jonathan Edwards]] (Physics, 1987),<ref name=\"Jonathan Edwards\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/4049800.Jonathan_Edwards_to_receive_honorary_degree/|title=Durham University hands out honorary degrees|work=The Northern Echo|accessdate=14 March 2009}}</ref> Beijing Olympics Bronze-medallist rower [[Stephen Rowbotham]] (Business Economics),<ref name=\"Durham Rowers Beijing\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sportengland.org/iyr_north_east-newpage-94.htm |title=Durham Rowers in Olympics |publisher=Durham University |accessdate=14 March 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081122084043/http://www.sportengland.org/iyr_north_east-newpage-94.htm |archivedate=22 November 2008 }}</ref> London 2012 Gold-medallist rower [[Sophie Hosking]] (Chemistry and Physics),<ref>{{cite web|last=Unwin |first=Bruce |title=Olympic gold medal winner returns to Durham University |url=http://www.durhamtimes.co.uk/news/10020429.Olympic_gold_medal_winner_returns_to_her_former_university/ |work=Durham Times |date=1 November 2012 |accessdate=13 August 2013}}</ref> former England cricket captains [[Nasser Hussain]] (Geochemistry)<ref name=\"Sports Alumni\"/> and [[Andrew Strauss]] (Economics) are among the most famous.<ref name=\"Andrew Strauss\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bucs.org.uk/news.asp?itemid=2530&itemTitle=Durham+alumni+Andrew+Strauss+named+England+Test+and+One+Day+Cricket+captain&section=8&sectionTitle=News+from+BUCS|title=Durham alumni Andrew Strauss named England Test and One Day Cricket captain|publisher=BUCS|accessdate=14 March 2009}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Colleges of Durham University|Historical list of Durham University Colleges]]\n* [[List of modern universities in Europe (1801\u20131945)]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|group=\"note\"}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin|2}}\n* Brickstock, Richard. (2007) ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=eZwyC18W1fkC&printsec=frontcover&client=firefox-a Durham Castle: Fortress, Palace, College.]'' Huddersfield: Jeremy Mills Publishing. \n* Fowler, Joseph Thomas (1904), ''[https://archive.org/download/durhamuniversity00fowluoft/durhamuniversity00fowluoft.pdf Durham University: Earlier Foundations and Present Colleges]'', Kessinger Publishing\n* Heesom, Alan, (1982) ''The founding of the University of Durham'', Durham Cathedral lecture 1982 (Durham, 1982)\n* The [[Surtees Society]], (1853) [https://books.google.com/books/pdf/the_durham_.pdf?id=5d8NAAAAQAAJ&output=pdf&sig=ACfU3U2RvHWnvSDt1cR0FDm9HprARFR_6g The Durham University Calendar with Almanack], Durham: W. E. Duncan and Sons \n* Watson, Nigel (2007), ''Durham Difference: The Story of Durham University'', James & James\n* Whiting, C.E., (1932) ''The University of Durham 1832\u20131932'' (London, 1932)\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links|wikt=no|b=no|v=no|commons=Durham University}}\n* {{Official website}}\n\n{{Durham University|state=expanded}}\n{{Navboxes|list1=\n{{Universities and colleges in North East England}}\n{{Universities in the United Kingdom}}\n{{Coimbra Group}}\n{{Russell Group}}\n{{N8 Group}}\n{{Matariki Network}}\n{{stockton}}<!--Queens Campus-->\n}}\n{{coord|54.773|-1.574|display=title}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Durham University| ]]\n[[Category:Russell Group|Durham University]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1832|Durham University]]\n[[Category:Organisations based in England with royal patronage|Durham University]]\n[[Category:1832 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Durham, England]]\n[[Category:Cross country running venues]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|collegiate public research university in Durham, United Kingdom}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox university\n|name            = Durham University\n|latin_name      = Universitas Dunelmens\u012bs\n|image_name      = Durham shield.png\n|image_size      = 150px\n|caption         = [[Coat of arms]] of the University of Durham\n|motto           = {{lang-la|Fundamenta eius super montibus sanctis}}\n|mottoeng        = Her foundations are upon the holy hills ([[Psalm 87]]:1)\n|established     = 1832 (university status)\n|type            = [[public university|Public]]\n|academic_staff = 1,720 (2018/19)<ref name=HESAstaff>{{cite web|url=https://www.hesa.ac.uk/data-and-analysis/staff/working-in-he#provider|publisher=[[Higher Education Statistics Agency]] |title=Who's working in HE |accessdate=1 March 2020|at=Staff numbers by HE provider }}</ref>\n|administrative_staff = 2,640 (2018/19)<ref name=HESAstaff/>\n|chancellor      = [[Thomas Allen (baritone)|Sir Thomas Allen]]\n|vice_chancellor = [[Stuart Corbridge]]\n|city            = [[Durham, England|Durham]] and [[Stockton-on-Tees]]\n|state           =\n|country         = England\n|campus          =\n| students       = {{HESA student population|INSTID=0116}} ({{HESA year}})<ref name=\"HESA citation\">{{HESA citation}}</ref>\n| undergrad      = {{HESA undergraduate population|INSTID=0116}} ({{HESA year}})<ref name=\"HESA citation\"/>\n| postgrad       = {{HESA postgraduate population|INSTID=0116}} ({{HESA year}})<ref name=\"HESA citation\"/>\n|free_label      = Student newspaper\n|free            = ''[[Palatinate (newspaper)|Palatinate]]''\n|colours         = {{color box|#72246C}} [[Palatinate (colour)|Palatinate]]\n|endowment       = \u00a381.9&nbsp;million {{small|(as of 31 July 2019; exclusive of colleges)}}<ref name=\"Durham Financial Statement 18/19\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/treasurer/financial_statements/AnnualReportandFinancialStatements2018-2019.pdf|title=Annual Report and Financial Statements for the year ended 31 July 2019|publisher=Durham University|date=n.d.|accessdate=18 December 2019}}</ref>\n|budget = \u00a3452.1&nbsp;million {{small|(2018\u201319)}}<ref group=\"note\">Includes a provision of \u00a379.1&nbsp;million for the [[Universities Superannuation Scheme]]</ref><ref name=\"Durham Financial Statement 18/19\"/>\n|affiliations    =[[Association of Commonwealth Universities|ACU]] <br />[[Coimbra Group]] <br />[[European University Association|EUA]] <br />[[N8 Group]] <br />[[Matariki Network of Universities]] <br /> [[Russell Group]] <br />[[University of the Arctic]]<br />[[Universities UK]] <br />[[Virgo Consortium]] <br />[[Wallace Group (universities)|Wallace Group]] \n|athletics       = [[Team Durham]]\n|website         = {{official URL}}\n|logo            = [[File:Durham University logo.svg|200px]]\n|embedded = {{designation list | embed=yes\n   | designation1 = WHS\n   | designation1_offname = [[Durham Castle and Cathedral]]\n   | designation1_type = Cultural\n   | designation1_criteria = ii, iv, vi\n   | designation1_date = 1986 <small>(10th [[World Heritage Committee|session]])</small>\n   | designation1_number = [https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/370 370]\n   | designation1_free1name = Extension\n   | designation1_free1value = 2008\n   | designation1_free2name = State party\n   | designation1_free2value = United Kingdom\n   | designation1_free3name = Region\n   | designation1_free3value = [[List of World Heritage Sites in Western Europe|Western Europe]]\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Durham University''' (legally the '''University of Durham''')<ref name=\"branding\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/about/trading_name/ |title=The University: Trading Name&nbsp;|publisher=Durham University |date=8 April 2011 |accessdate=1 November 2011}}</ref> is a [[collegiate university|collegiate]] [[public university|public]] [[research university]] in [[Durham, England|Durham]], England, founded by an [[Act of Parliament]] in 1832 and incorporated by [[royal charter]] in 1837. It was the first recognised university to open in England for more than 600 years, after [[University of Oxford|Oxford]] and [[University of Cambridge|Cambridge]], and is thus one of the institutions to be described as the [[third-oldest university in England debate|third-oldest university in England]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/education/sunday_times_university_guide/article4767634.ece|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716104807/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/education/sunday_times_university_guide/article4767634.ece|archive-date=16 July 2011|title=Profile: Durham University|work=The Sunday Times |location=London  | date=13 September 2009 | accessdate=15 September 2010 |first1=Anushka |last1=Asthana |author-link1=Anushka Asthana|first2=Jill |last2=Sherman}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/student/into-university/az-uni-colleges/ucl-university-college-london-459098.html |title=Reference to UCL as third oldest university in England |work=The Independent |date=31 May 2013 |accessdate=16 August 2013 |location=London}}</ref> As a collegiate university its main functions are divided between the academic departments of the university and its 16 colleges. In general, the departments perform research and provide teaching to students, while the colleges are responsible for their domestic arrangements and welfare.\n\nThe university is a member of the [[Russell Group]] of British research universities<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.qmul.ac.uk/media/news/items/65620.html |title=Queen Mary, University of London to join Russell Group of universities |publisher=Queen Mary, University of London |date=12 March 2012 |accessdate=14 March 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171011225547/http://www.qmul.ac.uk/media/news/items/65620.html |archive-date=11 October 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> after previously being a member of the [[1994 Group]].  Durham is also affiliated with the regional [[N8 Research Partnership]] and international university groups including the [[Matariki Network of Universities]] and the [[Coimbra Group]].  The university estate includes 63 [[listed buildings]], ranging from the 11th-century [[Durham Castle]] to a 1930s [[Art Deco]] chapel. The university also owns and manages the Durham [[World Heritage Site]] in partnership with [[Durham Cathedral]]. The university's ownership of the World Heritage Site includes [[Durham Castle]], [[Palace Green]], and the surrounding buildings including the historic [[Durham University Library#Cosin's Library|Cosin's Library]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.durhamworldheritagesite.com/heritage/site-boundaries|publisher=Durham World Heritage Site|title=Site Boundaries: An Evolving Definition of Heritage|accessdate=4 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nAmong British universities, it had the eighth highest average [[UCAS Tariff]] for new entrants in 2016<ref name=\"CUG UCAS\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk/league-tables/rankings?o=Entry+Standards|website=Complete University Guide|title=University League Table 2019|accessdate=12 July 2018}}</ref> and the third lowest proportion of state-school educated students starting courses in 2016, at 62.9 per cent (fifth lowest compared to its benchmark).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/oxford-universities-both-struggling-state-school-recruitment|title=Oxford universities both struggling on state school recruitment|author= Simon Baker|date=1 February 2018|work=Times Higher Education|accessdate=7 February 2018}}</ref> The university is currently ranked 5th to 7th by recent national [[Rankings of universities in the United Kingdom|league tables of the British universities]], 78th to 133rd in three of the four major global tables and in the 201\u2013300 range in the fourth (see [[#Rankings and reputation|below]]). It was [[Sunday Times University of the Year|''Sunday Times'' University of the Year]] for 2005,<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/news/allnews/?itemno=971 |work=The Times | location=Durham | title=The Sunday Times university of the year | date=12 September 2004 | accessdate=10 September 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.milkround.com/article/durham-university/|title=Durham University|accessdate=15 February 2016|publisher=Milkround Online Ltd|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160223094630/http://www.milkround.com/article/durham-university/|archive-date=23 February 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> and the ''Times'' and ''Sunday Times'' Sports University of the Year for 2015,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/news/newsitem/?itemno=22113|date=19 September 2014|title=Durham University named as Times and Sunday Times Sports University of the Year 2015|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=4 October 2015}}</ref> and was awarded a [[Queen's Anniversary Prize]] in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/news/newsitem/?itemno=33775|title=Royal Honour for baby and parent sleep research|date=22 February 2018|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=11 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Chancellor (education)|chancellor]] of the university is [[Thomas Allen (baritone)|Sir Thomas Allen]], who succeeded [[Bill Bryson]] in 2012.<ref name=\"chancellor\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/news/newsitem/?itemno=12950 |title=World-famous opera star Sir Thomas Allen appointed Chancellor of Durham University |publisher=Durham University \u2013 Dur.ac.uk |date=13 October 2011 |accessdate=1 November 2011}}</ref> Current and emeritus academics include 14 Fellows of the [[Royal Society]], 17 Fellows of the [[British Academy]], 14 Fellows of the [[Academy of Social Sciences]], 5 Fellows of the [[Royal Society of Edinburgh]], 2 Fellows of the [[Royal Society of Arts]] and 2 Fellows of the [[Academy of Medical Sciences]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Members of learned societies|publisher=University of Durham|accessdate=4 October 2015|date=3 September 2015|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/research/news/learned_societies/}}</ref> Durham graduates have long used the Latin [[post-nominal letters]] ''Dunelm'' after their degree, from ''Dunelmensis'' (of, belonging to, or from Durham).<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/durham.first/autumn09/whatsinaname/|title=What's in a Name?|volume=27|date=Autumn 2009|accessdate=4 October 2015|journal=Durham First|publisher=Durham University}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{main|History of Durham University}}\n\n===Origins===\n[[File:William_Van_Mildert_by_Thomas_Lawrence.jpg|thumb|upright|[[William van Mildert]], Bishop of Durham and one of the founders of the university]]\n\nThe strong tradition of theological teaching in Durham gave rise to various attempts to form a university there, notably under King [[Henry VIII of England|Henry VIII]] and [[Oliver Cromwell]], who issued [[letters patent]] and nominated a proctor and fellows for the establishment of a [[Durham College (17th-century)|college]] in 1657.<ref name=\"Penny Cyclop\u00e6dia\">{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_7KsrAAAAYAAJ|page=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_7KsrAAAAYAAJ/page/n386 381]|quote=durham university Calendar.|title=The Penny Cyclop\u00e6dia of the Society for the Diffusion of Useful Knowledge|publisher=C. Knight, 1838|accessdate=31 May 2009|year=1838}}</ref> However, there was deep concern expressed by Oxford and Cambridge that the awarding of degree powers could hinder their position.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|title=Historical note|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/university.calendar/volumei/current/historical_note.pdf|archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20070808151224/http://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/university.calendar/volumei/current/historical_note.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=8 August 2007|publisher=Durham University}}</ref> Consequently, it was not until 1832 when [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]], at the instigation of Archdeacon [[Charles Thorp]] and with the support of the Bishop of Durham, [[William van Mildert]], passed \"an Act to enable the Dean and Chapter of Durham Cathedral to appropriate part of the property of their church to the establishment of a University in connection therewith\" that the university came into being. The act received Royal Assent from King [[William IV of the United Kingdom|William IV]] on 4 July 1832.\n\n===The church university, 1832\u20131909===\n[[File:ExamInCosin.jpg|thumb|An examination taking place in [[Durham University Library#Cosin's Library|Cosin's Library]], 1842]]\n[[File:Durham Castle Gatehouse (geograph 2907552).jpg|thumb|[[Durham Castle]] (gatehouse pictured) houses [[University College, Durham|University College]], making it one of the oldest buildings currently being used to house a university in the world<ref>{{cite news|url=http://castle-jcr.dur.ac.uk/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=94&Itemid=78 |title=Castle JCR |author=Castle JCR |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061010134853/http://castle-jcr.dur.ac.uk/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=94&Itemid=78 |archivedate=10 October 2006 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/education/sunday_times_university_guide/article570365.ece |work=The Times |location=London  | title=Widening access without diluting quality | date=2 October 2005 | accessdate=1 May 2010 | first1=Anushka | last1=Asthana | author-link1=Anushka Asthana|first2=Jill | last2=Sherman}}</ref>]]\n\nThe university opened on 28 October 1833. In 1834 all but two of the bishops of the Church of England confirmed that they would accept holders of Durham degrees for ordination. In 1835 a fundamental statute was passed by the Dean and Chapter, as governors of the University, setting up [[Convocation]] and laying down that Durham degrees would only be open to members of the Church of England. Regulations for degrees were finalised in 1836 and the university was incorporated by [[Royal Charter]] granted by William IV on 1 June 1837 as the \"Warden, Masters and Scholars of the University of Durham\", with the first students graduating a week later.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /> Accommodation was provided in the Archdeacon's Inn (now Cosin's Hall) from 1833 to 1837. On the accession of [[Queen Victoria]] an order of the [[Queen-in-Council]] was issued granting the use of [[Durham Castle]] (previously a palace of the Bishop of Durham) to the university.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" />\n\nIn 1846, [[Thomas Hatfield|Bishop Hatfield]]'s Hall (later to become [[Hatfield College]]) was founded, providing the opportunity for students to obtain affordable lodgings with fully catered communal eating, a revolutionary idea at the time, endorsed by a Royal Commission in 1862 and later spread to other universities. Those attending [[University College, Durham|University College]] were expected to bring a servant with them to deal with cooking, cleaning and so on. The level of applications to Bishop Hatfield's Hall led to a second hall along similar lines, [[Bishop Cosin's Hall]], being founded in 1851, although this only survived until 1864. Elsewhere, the university expanded from Durham into [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]] in 1852 when the medical school there (established in 1834) became a college of the university.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /> This was joined in 1871 by the College of Physical Sciences (renamed the College of Science in 1884 and again renamed Armstrong College in 1904). [[St Cuthbert's Society]] was founded in 1888 for non-collegiate, mostly mature, male students as a non-residential society run by the students themselves. Two teacher-training colleges \u2013 St Hild's for women, established in 1858, and The College of the Venerable Bede for men, established in 1839,<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /> also existed in the city and these merged to form the mixed [[College of St Hild and St Bede]] in 1975. From 1896 these were associated with the university and graduates of St Hild's were the first female graduates from Durham in 1898.\n\nDuring its expansion phase the University also became the first English university to establish relationships with overseas institutions;<ref>{{cite web|title=Our history and values|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/about/shaped/|publisher=Durham University|date=1 February 2015}}</ref> firstly in 1875 with [[Codrington College]], Barbados, and secondly in early 1876 with [[Fourah Bay College]], Sierra Leone.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|title=Imperial Echos|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/features/imperial-echoes/419239.article|work=Times Higher Education|date=8 March 2012}}</ref> Under the arrangements the two colleges became affiliated colleges of the university with their students sitting examinations for and receiving Durham degrees.<ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Uncommon problems|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2004/may/11/internationaleducationnews.highereducation|publisher=JOURNAL OF SIERRA LEONE STUDIES|date=1 January 2013}}</ref> The landmark event was not met with universal applause, with the [[London Times]] stating \"it would not be much longer before the University of Durham was affiliated to the Zoo\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Rebuilding the Athens of West Africa: Education in the 21st Century in Sierra Leone|url=http://www.thejournalofsierraleonestudies.com/downloads/Version2.pdf|publisher=The Guardin|date=11 May 2004}}</ref> After nearly a century of affiliation and with the prevailing winds of decolonisation Fourah Bay became independent of the university in 1968 to form part of the [[University of Sierra Leone]], while Codrington College retained its affiliation with the university until the 2000s.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|title=Historical Dictionary of Sierra Leone (Historical Dictionaries of Africa)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=q31SWae8fhIC&pg=RA1-PA54&lpg=RA1-PA54&dq=Fourah+Bay+College+1876+durham&source=bl&ots=s1rWTrYYEj&sig=xx7FbifMOMCJj_fGe3UD6b41_y4&hl=en&sa=X&ei=ZUjOVKrCHMzxaJbxgKAC&ved=0CDYQ6AEwBTgK#v=onepage&q=Fourah%20Bay%20College%201876%20durham&f=false|publisher=Scarecrow Press |date=1 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe first debating society in Durham was founded in 1835, but may have closed by 1839. The Durham University Union was established in 1842, and revived and moved to [[Palace Green]] in 1872-3 as the [[Durham Union Society]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://reed.dur.ac.uk/xtf/view?docId=ead/uni/undg.xml#UNDall-3507|title=Durham University Records: Associations and Societies \u2013 Durham Union Society|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=3 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://dus.org.uk/our-history/|title=Our History|publisher=Durham Union Society|accessdate=3 October 2015}}</ref> Notable past presidents of the Durham Union have included [[Richard Dannatt]], [[Sir Edward Leigh]], and [[Crispin Blunt]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Dannatt|first1=Gen. Sir (Francis) Richard|title=Who's Who|journal=A & C Black|year=2011|issue=online edn|url=http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.001.0001/ww-9780199540884-e-12817|accessdate=12 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=EDWARD LEIGH MEMBER OF PARLIAMENT FOR GAINSBOROUGH|url=https://www.conservatives.com/OurTeam/Members_of_Parliament/Leigh_Edward|website=Conservatives|publisher=The Conservative and Unionist Party|accessdate=12 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Blunt|first1=Crispin|url=https://hansard.parliament.uk/commons/2016-10-21/debates/DD6089AE-523C-4707-9773-4262BB9415BD/SexualOffences(PardonsEtc)Bill|title=Sexual Offences (Pardons Etc) Bill|work=Hansard|accessdate=12 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Durham Colleges Students Representative Council (SRC) was founded around 1900 after the model of the College of Medicine SRC (in Newcastle). The Durham University SRC was formed in 1907 with representatives from the Durham Colleges, the College of Medicine, and Armstrong College (also in Newcastle). In 1963, after the creation of Newcastle University, the Durham Colleges SRC became the Durham University SRC, and was renamed as the [[Durham Students' Union]] in 1970.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://reed.dur.ac.uk/xtf/view?docId=ead/uni/undg.xml#UNDall-1409|title=Durham University Records: Associations and Societies \u2013 Student Representative Bodies|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=3 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nUntil the mid 19th century, University of Durham degrees were subject to a religion test and could only be taken by members of the established church. Medical degrees in Newcastle were exempt from this requirement from the start of the affiliation of the medical school, but in Durham it lasted until the revision of the statutes in 1865.<ref>{{cite news |title=University of Durham|work=Morning Post |date=18 September 1865 |accessdate=5 December 2015 |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000174/18650918/038/0006| via = [[British Newspaper Archive]]|url-access=subscription }}</ref> Despite the opening of degrees, staff and members of Convocation were still required to be members of the Church of England until the [[Universities Tests Act 1871]]. However, \"dissenters\" were able to attend Durham and then sit the examinations for degrees of the [[University of London]], which were not subject to any religious test.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.senatehouselibrary.ac.uk/our-collections/historic-collections/archives-manuscripts/university-of-london-student-records-1836-1931/ |title=University of London student records 1836\u20131931 |publisher=senatehouselibrary.ac.uk |date=12 March 2013 |accessdate=12 March 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100914105055/http://www.shl.lon.ac.uk/specialcollections/archives/studentrecords.shtml |archivedate=14 September 2010  }}</ref> Following the grant of a supplemental charter in 1895 allowing women to receive degrees of the university, the Women's Hostel ([[St Mary's College, Durham|St Mary's College]] from 1919) was founded in 1899.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Durham Difference|author=Nigel Watson|date=2007|publisher=James & James (Publishers) Ltd, London|page=29\n}}</ref>\n\n===The federal university, 1909\u20131963===\n[[File:Durham Heritage Centre.jpg|right|thumb|[[St Chad's College]], one of the two independent colleges]]\nThe Newcastle division of the university, which comprised both Armstrong College (named after Lord Armstrong) and Durham University College of Medicine, quickly grew to outnumber the Durham colleges, despite the addition of two independent [[Anglicanism|Anglican]] foundations: [[St Chad's College]] (1904) and [[St John's College, Durham|St John's College]] (1909). A parliamentary bill proposed in 1907 would have fixed the seat of the university in Durham for only ten years, allowing the Senate to choose to move to Newcastle after this. This was blocked by a local [[Member of parliament|MP]]{{who|date=October 2018}}, with the support of graduates of the Durham colleges, until the bill was modified to establish a federal university with its seat fixed in Durham. This reform also removed the university from the authority of the Dean and Chapter of [[Durham Cathedral]], who had been the governors of the university since its foundation.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Durham Difference|author=Nigel Watson|date=2007|publisher=James & James (Publishers) Ltd, London|pages=30\u201331}}</ref> Thirty years after this, the [[Royal Commission]] of 1937 recommended changes in the constitution of the federal university, resulting in the merger of the two Newcastle colleges in the Newcastle Division to form King's College. The Vice-Chancellorship alternated between the Warden of the Durham Division and the Rector of the Newcastle Division.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Durham Difference|author=Nigel Watson|date=2007|publisher=James & James (Publishers) Ltd, London|page=45}}</ref> (The legacy of this lives on, in that the de facto head of the university is still called \"The Vice-Chancellor and Warden\".)<ref group=note>The title \"warden\" was not used between 1909 and 1937, as the 1909 statutes assigned the title to the Council of the Durham Colleges collectively. Its readoption in 1937 had to do with distinguishing between the two Divisions, the Durham Colleges headed by a warden and King's College (Newcastle) by a rector. It signified that the postholders were \"the chief academic and administrative officers of the Divisions respectively\" (art 45).</ref>\n\nAfter World War II, the Durham division expanded rapidly. St Aidan's Society ([[St Aidan's College, Durham|St Aidan's College]] from 1961) was founded in 1947 to cater for non-resident women and the decision was made to expand further on Elvet Hill (where the science site had been established in the 1920s), relocating St Mary's College, building new men's colleges, vastly expanding the existing pure science provision in Durham, and adding applied science (1960) and engineering (1965).<ref>{{cite web|title=Durham University Records|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=3 October 2015|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/library/asc/collection_information/cldload/?collno=150|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151005154338/https://www.dur.ac.uk/library/asc/collection_information/cldload/?collno=150|archive-date=5 October 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 1947, the foundation stones for the new [[St Mary's College, Durham|St Mary's]] College building on Elvet Hill were laid by Princess Elizabeth (later Queen [[Elizabeth II]]).<ref>{{cite book|title=The Durham Difference|author=Nigel Watson|date=2007|publisher=James & James (Publishers) Ltd, London|page=54}}</ref> The new building opened in 1952. In the same year, tensions surfaced again over the Durham-Newcastle divide, with a proposal to change the name of the university to the \"University of Durham and Newcastle\". This motion was defeated in [[Convocation]] (the assembly of members of the university) by 135 votes to 129.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Durham University Journal|page=121|volume=13\u201314|title=Name of the University|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Er4TAQAAMAAJ&q=%22university+of+durham+and+newcastle%22&dq=%22university+of+durham+and+newcastle%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CB8Q6AEwAGoVChMIrqXugvCjyAIVy5qACh128AKN|publisher=Durham University}}</ref> Eleven years later, with the Universities of Durham and Newcastle upon Tyne Act 1963, King's College became the [[Newcastle University|University of Newcastle upon Tyne]], leaving Durham University based solely in its home city.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Durham Difference|author=Nigel Watson|date=2007|publisher=James & James (Publishers) Ltd, London|page=75}}</ref>\n\n===The modern university, 1963\u20131999===\n\nBy the time of the separation from Newcastle the Elvet Hill site was well established; with the first of the new colleges being founded in 1959, [[Grey College, Durham|Grey College]], named after the [[Charles Grey, 2nd Earl Grey|second Earl Grey]] who was the [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] when the university was founded. Expansion up Elvet Hill continued, with [[Van Mildert College]] and the [[Durham Business School]] (1965), [[Trevelyan College]] (1966) and [[Collingwood College, Durham|Collingwood College]] (1972) all being added to the university, along with a [[Durham University Botanic Garden|Botanic Garden]] (1970).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/botanic.garden/aboutus/history/|title=History of the Garden|accessdate=1 October 2015|publisher=Durham University}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The Durham Difference|author=Nigel Watson|date=2007|publisher=James & James (Publishers) Ltd, London|pages=78\u201382}}</ref>\n\n[[File:St Mary's College Lawn.jpg|thumb|right|The lawn at [[St Mary's College, Durham|St Mary's College]], the first of the [[Colleges of the University of Durham|Hill college]]s]]\nThese were not the only developments in the university, however. The Graduate Society, catering for postgraduate students, was founded in 1965 (renamed [[Ustinov College]] in 2003) and the (now closed) Roman Catholic [[seminary]] of [[Ushaw College]], which had been in Durham since 1808, was licensed as a hall of residence in 1968. In 1988 Hatfield, the last men's college, became mixed; followed by the women's college of Trevelyan in 1992, leaving the original women's college of St Mary's as the last single-sex college.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Durham Difference|author=Nigel Watson|date=2007|publisher=James & James (Publishers) Ltd, London|page=99}}</ref>\n\nIn 1989 the university started its fund-raising and [[alumni]] office, with a virtual community for alumni<ref>{{cite web|title=dunelm.org.uk|url=http://www.dunelm.org.uk|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=8 April 2014}}</ref> and several large gifts made to the university, including for the Centre for Middle Eastern Studies, the [[Durham University Department of Physics|Department of Physics]] and the [[Wolfson Research Institute]].\n\n====Development in Stockton, 1992\u20131999====\nIn 1991, a joint venture between the university and the [[University of Teesside]] saw the Joint University College on Teesside of the Universities of Durham and Teesside (JUCOT) established at [[Thornaby-on-Tees]] in the borough of [[Stockton-on-Tees]] and the ceremonial county of North Yorkshire,  {{convert|30|mi}} to the south of Durham. It opened under the name of University College Stockton (UCS) in 1992.\n\nUCS was initially intended to grant joint degrees validated by both institutions (BAs and BScs). However, Teesside, which had only become a university in 1992, had difficulties in taking on its responsibilities for the college and withdrew in 1994, Durham taking over full responsibility for UCS and the degrees to be awarded there.\n\nA programme of integration with Durham began, with the Privy Council approving changes in Durham's statutes to make UCS a college of the University of Durham. Further integration of the Stockton development with the University led to the formation of the University of Durham, Stockton Campus (UDSC) in 1998 and the separation of teaching responsibilities from UCS.\n\n===21st century===\n[[File:Al-Qasimi Building.jpg|thumb|School of Government and International Affairs]]\nIn 2001, two new colleges, [[John Snow College|John Snow]] and [[Stephenson College, Durham|George Stephenson]] (after the [[John Snow (physician)|physician]] and the [[George Stephenson|engineer]]) were established at Stockton, replacing UCS, and the new [[Durham University School of Medicine, Pharmacy and Health|medical school]] (operating in association with the [[University of Newcastle upon Tyne]]) accepted its first students. In 2002, her [[golden jubilee]] year, the [[Elizabeth II of the United Kingdom|Queen]] granted the title \"Queen's Campus\" to the Stockton site.<ref>{{cite web|title=Durham University Welcomes Her Majesty the Queen|url=http://www.necc.co.uk/member-news-and-events/1079-durham-university-welcomes-her-majesty-the-queen|publisher=The North East Chamber of Commerce|accessdate=1 February 2015}}</ref> By 2005, Queen's Campus, Stockton, accounted for around 18 per cent of the total university student population.<ref>{{cite web|title=The University: Student Statistics|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/about/facts/student/|publisher=Durham University|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100224230410/http://www.dur.ac.uk/about/facts/student/|archivedate=24 February 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, the university unveiled a re-branded [[logotype]] and introduced the trading name of Durham University, although the legal name of the institution remained the University of Durham and the official coat of arms was unchanged.<ref name=\"branding\"/> The same year, [[St Mary's College, Durham|St Mary's College]] had its first mixed undergraduate intake.<ref>{{cite news|title=St Mary's opens door to men after 106 years|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1499996/St-Marys-opens-door-to-men-after-106-years.html|work=The Daily Telegraph|location=London|accessdate=1 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Durham college opens doors to male undergraduates|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2005/oct/05/highereducation.students|work=The Guardian|location=London|accessdate=1 February 2015}}</ref> In October 2006, [[Josephine Butler College]] opened its doors to students as Durham's newest college \u2013 the only purpose-built self-catering college for students within Durham. This was the first new college to open in Durham itself since the creation of Collingwood in the 1970s.<ref>{{cite news|title=New college for Durham University|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/2515027.stm|work=BBC News|accessdate=1 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2010, Durham joined the [[Matariki Network of Universities]] (MNU) together with [[Dartmouth College]] (USA), [[Queen's University at Kingston|Queen's University]] (Canada), [[University of Otago]] (New Zealand), [[University of T\u00fcbingen]] (Germany), [[University of Western Australia]] and [[Uppsala University]] (Sweden).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.matarikinetwork.com/members.html |title=Members of the Matariki Network of Universities |publisher=Matarikinetwork.com |date=n.d.|accessdate=1 November 2011}}</ref> In 2012, Durham (along with [[University of York|York]], [[University of Exeter|Exeter]] and [[Queen Mary, University of London]]) joined the [[Russell Group]] of research-intensive British universities.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2012/mar/12/russell-group-four-more-universities|date=12 March 2012|title=Russell Group extends membership to four more universities|author=Jessica Shepherd}}</ref>\n\nBetween 2010 and 2012 the university was criticised for accepting funds from controversial sources, including the government of [[Iran]], the [[US State Department]], the prime minister of [[Kuwait]] and [[British American Tobacco]].<ref>{{cite news|work=[[BBC]]|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/education-12908507|title=Durham University defends accepting funds from Iran|author=Simon Cox|date=31 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2011/feb/10/wikileaks-durham-university-iran-us-embassy|title=WikiLeaks reveals degree of Durham University's involvement in Iran|author=Ian Black|date=10 February 2011|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.new.spectator.co.uk/2011/04/shaky-dealings-are-damaging-the-reputation-of-britains-universities/|title=Shaky dealings are damaging the reputation of Britain's universities|newspaper=[[The Spectator]]|author=David Blackburn|date=1 April 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151119171502/http://blogs.new.spectator.co.uk/2011/04/shaky-dealings-are-damaging-the-reputation-of-britains-universities/|archivedate=19 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2011/jun/07/durham-university-tobacco-funding-afghan-award|title=Furore over Durham's tobacco funding for Afghan scholarship|author=Lucy Tobin|date=7 June 2011|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref>\n\nThe university announced in 2016 that it would relocate the colleges and academic activities currently at the Queen's Campus to Durham City from 2017;<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazettelive.co.uk/news/teesside-news/durham-university-considering-withdrawing-medical-10950734|work=Gazette Live|title=Durham University considering withdrawing medical school from Stockton|date=25 February 2016|author=James Cain}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.palatinate.org.uk/university-continues-to-consult-on-the-future-of-queen\u2019s-campus/|title=University continues to consult on the future of Queen's Campus|date=10 March 2016|author=Charlie Taylor-Kroll|newspaper=[[Palatinate (newspaper)|Palatinate]]}}</ref> with the School of Medicine, Pharmacy and Health being transferred to [[Newcastle University]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.itv.com/news/tyne-tees/2016-07-13/durham-university-to-move-school-of-medicine-pharmacy-and-health-out-of-teesside/|title=Durham University to move school of medicine, pharmacy and health out of Teesside|date=13 July 2016|work=[[itv.com]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazettelive.co.uk/news/teesside-news/durham-university-confirms-plans-pull-11314325|title=Durham University confirms plans to pull academic and college-based activities from Stockton\n|date=10 May 2016|author=James Cain|work=GazetteLive}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://my.ncl.ac.uk/staff/nuconnections/item/transfer-of-school-of-medicine-pharmacy-and-health-to-newcastle1|title=Transfer of School of Medicine, Pharmacy and Health to Newcastle|accessdate=7 August 2017|date=10 July 2017|publisher=Newcastle University}}</ref> The Queen's Campus became an International Study Centre to prepare overseas students to study at Durham, run by [[Study Group International|Study Group]].<ref name=\"Queen's ISC\">{{cite news|url=http://www.palatinate.org.uk/queens-campus-to-house-new-centre-for-international-students/|title= Queen's Campus to house new centre for international students|date=30 January 2017|author= Eugene Smith|work=[[Palatinate (newspaper)|Palatinate]]}}</ref>\n \n[[File:Ogden Centre (geograph 5908287).jpg|thumb|The Ogden Centre for Fundamental Physics, next to the Department of Physics]]\nIn March 2017 [[Martin Rees|Lord Rees]] opened the Ogden Centre for Fundamental Physics, designed by [[Daniel Libeskind]].<ref>{{cite web |title=University opens \u00a311.5m 'space centre' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-tyne-39249121 |website=BBC News |accessdate=2 November 2018}}</ref> The new building, named after alumnus [[Peter Ogden]], provides extra laboratories and office space for 140 staff.<ref>{{cite web |title=Iconic research centre confirms Durham's international position in space science \u2013 Durham University |url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/news/research/?itemno=30784 |publisher=Durham University |accessdate=2 November 2018 }}</ref> In May 2017 the university announced a new ten-year strategy that proposed investing \u00a3700m in improving the campus, creating 300 new academic posts, increasing the size of the university to 21,500 students while attracting more international students, and expanding the business school and the departments of law, politics, English and history to reach \"critical research mass\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/durhams-repositioning-create-300-academic-jobs|title=Durham's \u2018repositioning\u2019 to create 300 academic jobs|work=[[Times Higher Education]]|date=27 May 2017|author=John Elmes}}</ref><ref name=\"Chronicle Strategy\">{{cite news|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/north-east-news/durham-university-reveals-700m-plan-13077153|title=Durham University reveals \u00a3700m plan to help rejuvenate campus|work=Chronicle Live|date= 23 May 2017|accessdate=2 June 2017|author=Hannah Graham}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 the university announced that a consortium led by [[Interserve]] would design, build and operate two colleges at [[Mount Oswald]] (new buildings for John Snow College and [[South College, Durham|one new college]]) for \u00a3105&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2018/08/17/interserve-wins-105m-construction-contract-durham-university/|title=Interserve wins \u00a3105m construction contract for Durham University|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=17 August 2018|author=Rhiannon Curry}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-tyne-45220845|title=Durham University to spend \u00a3105m on new colleges|work=[[BBC News]]|date=17 August 2018}}</ref> The project company (in which the university has a 15 per cent stake) is financing the construction via a \u00a390&nbsp;million 46-year bond issue.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://ftalphaville.ft.com/2018/08/20/1534771832000/University-accommodation-deals--it-s-a-wrap/|title=University accommodation deals: it's a wrap|date=20 August 2018|author=Thomas Hale|work=[[Financial Times]]}}</ref> Separately, the university announced that it had raised \u00a3225&nbsp;million to fund its estate masterplan through the private sale of long-term bonds to British and US investors.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/business/business-news/durham-university-secures-225m-funding-15091280|title=Durham University secures \u00a3225m of funding from key UK and US investors|date=30 August 2018|author=Coreena Ford|work=Chronicle Live}}</ref>\n\n==Campus==\nDurham University owns a {{convert|227.8|ha|acre|abbr=on}} estate which includes part of a [[UNESCO world heritage site]],<ref name=\"Durham's World Heritage Site expands\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/news/newsitem/?itemno=6941&rehref=%2Fnews%2Farchive%2F&resubj=%20Headlines|title=Durham's World Heritage Site expands|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=11 January 2009}}</ref> one [[ancient monument]], five [[Listed building|grade-one listed building]]s and 68 grade two-listed buildings, along with {{convert|44.9|ha|acre|abbr=on}} of woodland.<ref name=\"Durham Masterplan\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/estates/masterplan/masterplan.pdf|title=University of Durham Framework and Masterplan|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=11 January 2009}}</ref> The estate is divided across two separate locations: Durham City and Queen's Campus, Stockton. The two locations are connected via a free bus service that runs frequently throughout the week. One of the major public attractions in Durham City is the {{convert|7.3|ha|acre|abbr=on}} [[Durham University Botanic Garden|Botanic Gardens]], established in 1970, with over 78,000 visitors (2007/08).<ref name=\"About the Garden\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/botanic.garden/aboutthegarden/|title=About the Garden|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=11 January 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"Estates and Buildings Annual Report 2007/2008\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/estates/documents/AnnualReport0708Final.pdf|title=Estates and Buildings Annual Report 2007/2008|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=11 January 2009}}</ref> {{as of|2018}}, the estate included over 300 buildings with a floor area of more than 380,000&nbsp;m<sup>2</sup> and a 2014 insurance reinstatement value of close to \u00a3850&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aude.ac.uk/Resources/Documents/Content?g=d21f6a53-3473-4208-b747-6b195d04bac1|title=Focus on Estates at Durham University|date=13 September 2018 |author= Cheryl Pick}}</ref>\n\n===Durham City===\n[[File:Hatfield College, Durham.jpg|thumb|[[Hatfield College, Durham|Hatfield College]], one of the five colleges along the Bailey]]\n[[File:Old Elvet, Durham (geograph 3851375).jpg|thumb|[[Old Elvet]] is the home of a number of departments, as well as Old Shire Hall]]\nDurham City is the main location of the university and contains all of the colleges along with most of the academic departments. The Durham City estate is spread across several different sites.\n\n[[The Bailey]] is the historic centre of the university and contains five colleges as well as the departments of Music and of Theology and Religion, the Institute of Advanced Study and [[Palace Green]] Library, housing the University's special collections. The Bailey is linked to Dunelm House, home of the [[Durham Students Union|Students Union]] in New Elvet, by the University's [[Kingsgate Bridge]].\n\nThe [[Elvet|Old and New Elvet]] areas contain a number of departments in Humanities and Social Sciences including Philosophy, and Sociology. The Leazes Road site on the north bank of the Wear, opposite the university's [[The Racecourse|Racecourse]] playing fields and Old Elvet, is home to the School of Education and Hild Bede College. Old Elvet was previously the site of the university's administration in [[Shire Hall, Durham|Old Shire Hall]], which has, since September 2012, been based on the Mountjoy site, in the Palatine Centre on Stockton Road.<ref>{{cite news|title=Former university HQ 'to become hotel within months'|url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/10065509.Former_Durham_University_HQ__to_become_hotel_within_months_/|accessdate=16 September 2015|work=The Northern Echo|date=22 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n====Mountjoy====\n[[File:Palatine Centre, Durham (cropped).jpg|thumb|The Palatine Centre on the Mountjoy Campus, home of the university's administration]]\n\nThe Mountjoy site (formerly the Science site) south of New Elvet contains the vast majority of departments and large lecture theatres such as Appleby, Scarborough, James Duff, Heywood and more recently the Calman Learning Centre, along with the [[Durham University Library|Bill Bryson library]].<ref>{{cite news|title=The Main Library is being renamed 'The Bill Bryson Library'!|date=25 September 2012|publisher=Durham University|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/library/news/?itemno=15355|accessdate=27 November 2012}}</ref> Upper Mountjoy contains the Psychology and Biological & Biomedical schools, along with various research centres.\n\nBuilding work started in 2017 on a Centre for Teaching and Learning on the Montjoy site, to open in 2019;<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/north-east-news/works-starts-new-40m-durham-14072810.amp|title=Works starts on new \u00a340m Durham University education hub|date=26 December 2017|work=ChronicleLive|author=Kali Lindsay}}</ref> the university also intends to build new facilities for mathematics and computer science on the site, to open in 2020.<ref name=\"Roadmap 2027\"/>\n\n====Elvet Hill====\n[[File:Sheraton Park Durham.jpg|thumb|Sheraton Park, site of a former teacher training college and home to Ustinov College since 2017]]\nElvet Hill, south of the Mountjoy site, has 8 of the colleges as well as the [[Durham University Botanic Garden|Botanic Garden]] and the Vice-Chancellor's residence in Hollingside House. It is also home to the [[Durham University Business School|Business School]] and the department of Government and International Affairs, as well as the [[Teikyo University of Japan in Durham]] and the Oriental Museum.\n\nAs part of the transfer of colleges from the Queen's Campus in 2017, a number of colleges changed location. Stephenson College moved to the site at Howlands Farm (also on Elvet Hill) previously occupied by Ustinov College. Ustinov itself moved to a new site at Sheraton Park in Neville's Cross from the 2017/18 academic year. For a transition period, John Snow and Stephenson will both be located at Howlands Farm during the 2018/19 academic year.<ref name=\"Roadmap 2027\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/14756619.University_college_move_approved/|work=Northern Echo|title=University college move approved|author=Rachel Conner|date=22 September 2016|accessdate=24 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n====Mount Oswald====\nTwo new colleges are currently being built at the former Mount Oswald golf course on Elvet Hill and are due to be occupied in 2020. John Snow college will move into one college, with the other forming an (as yet unnamed) 17th college. The new colleges at Mount Oswald will have around 500 self-catered rooms each. As of 2016, when bids were solicited for the construction, the first 700 rooms were hoped to be available for the 2019/20 academic year and the remaining 300 by the 2021/22 academic year.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theconstructionindex.co.uk/news/view/durham-uni-seeks-contractor-for-two-new-colleges|work=The Construction Index|title= Durham Uni seeks contractor for two new colleges|date=9 September 2016|accessdate=14 September 2016}}</ref> Construction began in September 2018, with \"Hub building\" expected to be ready for 2019/20 but the first students not expected to move into the new accommodation until the 2020/21 academic year.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/16693505.work-starts-on-durham-universitys-new-80m-colleges/|title=ConstructionWork starts on Durham University's new \u00a380m colleges|work=Northern Echo|date=7 September 2018|author=Rachel Conner-Hill}}</ref> John Snow college will still move out of Howlands in 2019/20, being located for one year at Rushford Court (owned by [[Unite Students]]) in the viaduct area of the city before moving to Mount Oswald for 2020/21.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/experience/news/?itemno=36995|title=Bright future for John Snow College, as 2019/20 location is announced|date=14 December 2018|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=16 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Development plans====\nThe university's 2017\u20132027 strategy document calls for the development of a new home for the business school at Elvet Waterside (Old Elvet), to open in 2021, and for the redevelopment of the arts and humanities facilities at Elvet Riverside (New Elvet), opening from 2022.<ref name=\"Roadmap 2027\"/> The plans are, however, contingent on the university being granted a Certificate of Immunity from Listing for the current student union building, Dunelm House, which would allow it to be demolished.<ref name=\"Chronicle Strategy\"/> Following an appeal by the [[Twentieth Century Society]] against the 2016 decision of the Secretary of State, [[Karen Bradley]], not to list the building, the [[Department of Culture, Media and Sport]] reconsidered the case in 2017 and confirmed that it would not list the building and was minded to issue a certificate of immunity.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://archpaper.com/2017/01/durham-students-union-risk-loss/#gallery-0-slide-0|work=The Architects Newspaper|author=Jason Sayer|date=5 January 2017|title=The birthplace of Brutalism in the U.K. is at risk of losing its most outstanding concrete building}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/north-east-news/ugly-iconic-durhams-student-union-12328491|work=ChronicleLive|title=Ugly or iconic? Durham's student union building could be demolished|author=Laura Hill |date=5 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.architectsjournal.co.uk/news/culture-secretary-refuses-to-reverse-dunelm-house-listing-decision/10024892.article|title=Culture secretary refuses to reverse Dunelm House listing decision|date=1 November 2017|author= Colin Marrs |work=The Architects Newspaper}}</ref> The [[Twentieth Century Society]] have placed Dunelm House on their 'Buildings at Risk List'.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-38689831|work=BBC News|date=20 January 2017|title=Ten 20th Century buildings named as 'at risk'}}</ref>\n\nIn total, the university expects to build four to six new colleges by 2027.<ref>{{cite video|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cON8a-Qwlu8|title=An update from Professor Stuart Corbridge, Vice-Chancellor and Warden|date=26 January 2017|publisher=Durham University|via=YouTube}}</ref><ref name=\"Roadmap 2027\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/strategy2027/Roadmap2027.pdf|title=A Roadmap to 2027|work=University Strategy 2017\u20132027|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=25 May 2017}}</ref> The university's Estate Masterplan for 2017\u20132027 identified the area around Howlands Farm, the Leazes Road site (Hild Bede College), and the current Business School site as locations for new accommodation development.<ref name=\"Colleges Masterplan\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/about/DurhamUniversityMasterplanExecutiveSummaryRevCSML.pdf|work=University Estate Masterplan 2017\u20132027 Executive Summary|page=8|title=Academic and Collegiate Zoning|year=2017|publisher=Durham University}}</ref>\n\n====Ushaw College====\n[[Ushaw College]], 5 miles west of Durham, is a former Catholic seminary that is a licensed hall of residence of the university. It hosts parts of the Business School and of the Centre for Catholic Studies, with the university having committed to leasing the East Wing until 2027 and to establishing a residential research library at Ushaw.<ref name=\"Ushaw Library\"/> It formerly housed some students from [[Josephine Butler College]], but since summer 2015 the only students at Ushaw are business marketing students.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/greenspace/travel/public/bus/ushawcollege/|title=Changes to the Bus Service between Ushaw College and Durham City}}</ref> In 2017 the university's Centre for Evaluation and Monitoring, part of the School of Education, moved to Ushaw College.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/estates-developments/past/cem/|title=CEM move to Ushaw|accessdate=1 September 2018|publisher=Durham University}}</ref>\n\n===Queen's Campus===\n[[File:Wolfson Institute.jpg|thumb|upright=2.0|right|[[Wolfson Research Institute]] at the Queen's Campus]]\n\nQueen's Campus, Stockton was established in 1992 and is located in [[Thornaby-on-Tees]] in the [[borough of Stockton-on-Tees]], some 30 miles from Durham City. Until 2017\u201318, the campus was home to around 2,000 full-time students in two colleges ([[John Snow College|John Snow]] and [[Stephenson College, Durham|Stephenson College]]s) and the [[Wolfson Research Institute]].<ref name=\"Welcome to Queen's - A Cosmopolitan Campus\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/queens-campus/|title=Welcome to Queen's \u2013 A Cosmopolitan Campus|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=11 January 2009}}</ref> A bus connects Queen's Campus to Durham City, with a one-way journey usually taking 45 minutes.<ref name=\"Stockton\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/travel/durham.queens/|title=Travelling between Durham City and Queen's Campus, Stockton|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=11 January 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe colleges and academic departments were relocated to Durham City (or transferred to [[Newcastle University]] in the case of the School of Medicine, Pharmacy and Health) between 2017 and 2018, and the Queen's Campus became an International Study Centre (ISC), run by [[Study Group International|Study Group]]. This prepares non-EU foreign students to enter degree courses at the university, with the first students having started in September 2017.<ref name=\"Queen's ISC\"/><ref name=\"Roadmap 2027\"/> The ISC has taken over the former college accommodation on the campus, with the former Stephenson College buildings becoming Endeavour Court and the former John Snow College buildings becoming Infinity House. The ISC also continues to use the privately owned Rialto Court accommodation, which was previously used by the Queen's Campus colleges.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.durhamisc.com/international-study-centre/accommodation|title=Student Accommodation|website=Durham University International Study Centre|publisher=Study Group|accessdate=1 September 2018}}</ref> The university had said, as part of its 2017\u20132027 masterplan, that it is continuing to explore other options for the use of the Queen's Campus and will be developing a separate masterplan for the campus.<ref name=\"Colleges Masterplan\"/>\n\nThe [[Wolfson Research Institute]] was established at the Queen's Campus in 2001 to conduct and facilitate interdisciplinary research in health and wellbeing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/wolfson.institute/abouttheinstitute/|title=About the Institute|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=1 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Libraries===\n[[File:Palace Green Library (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright=2.0|The original university library is now known as the [[Palace Green]] Library (centre) and the School of Music (left)]]\n\nThe [[Durham University Library]] system holds over 1.5&nbsp;million printed items.<ref name=\"Library History\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/library/about/history/|title=Library History|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=11 January 2009}}</ref> The library was founded in January 1833 at [[Palace Green]] with a 160-volume donation by the Bishop of Durham, William Van Mildert.<ref name=\"Library History\"/> The library operates five branches: Bill Bryson Library (the main library), Leazes Road Library, Queen's Campus Library, Durham University Business School Library and the Palace Green Library, which holds the special and heritage collections.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/library/services/|title=Services and sites |website=Durham University Library|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=30 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, designated status was granted by the [[Museums, Libraries and Archives Council]] to two of the special collections: Bishop Cosin's Library on Palace Green (an endowed public library dating from 1669 of which the University is the trustee), which contains medieval manuscripts and over 5,000 printed books, many early, and the Sudan Archive, described by the university as \"the pre-eminent archive on the Sudan outside Khartoum\".<ref name=\"Library: Designation\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/library/asc/collection_information/designation2005/|title=Designation|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=11 January 2009}}</ref> Since the Museums, Libraries and Archives Council was abolished in 2012, the designation scheme has been managed by [[Arts Council England]]; the two special collections remain Designated as of July 2016, along with the [[Durham University Oriental Museum]]'s Egyptian and Chinese collections.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artscouncil.org.uk/sites/default/files/download-file/Collections_List_July_2016_.pdf|title=Currently Designated Collections|date=July 2016|accessdate=30 March 2017|pages=22\u201323|publisher=Arts Council England}}</ref>\n\n[[File:St_Cuthbert_Gospel_-_f.1.jpg|thumb|upright|St Cuthbert Gospel, an 8th-century [[gospel book]]]]\nIn 2012 the university, together with the [[British Library]] and [[Durham Cathedral]], purchased Europe's oldest intact book, the [[St Cuthbert Gospel]], for the nation for \u00a39&nbsp;million. It is displayed equally in London and Durham, being shown at the University's Palace Green Library for the first time as part of the Lindisfarne Gospels Durham exhibition in 2013.<ref>[http://pressandpolicy.bl.uk/Press-Releases/British-Library-acquires-the-St-Cuthbert-Gospel-the-earliest-intact-European-book-58c.aspx \"British Library acquires the St Cuthbert Gospel \u2013 the earliest intact European book\"], BL Press release. Retrieved 17 April 2012</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/palace.green/whatson/details/?id=18081|title=Lindisfarne Gospels Durham|website=Palace Green Library|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=3 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.palatinate.org.uk/st-cuthbert-gospel-returns-to-palace-green-library/|newspaper=[[Palatinate (newspaper)|Palatinate]]|date=23 October 2014|author=Rose Malleson|title=St Cuthbert Gospel returns to Palace Green Library}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to the central library system, each College maintains its own library and reading rooms such as the Bettenson, Brewis, Williams and Fenton Libraries of St Chad's College, which contain over 38,000 volumes.<ref name=\"St Chad's: Library\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/StChads/libraries.html|title=St Chad's Library|publisher=St Chad's College|accessdate=11 January 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081226115308/http://www.dur.ac.uk/StChads/libraries.html|archivedate=26 December 2008}}</ref> Many departments also maintain a library in addition to the subject collections in the central and college libraries. Readers are also entitled to use the theology library housed by [[Durham Cathedral]] in its cloister.\n\nIn February 2017, the university announced a \u00a32&nbsp;million investment to establish a residential research library at [[Ushaw College]]. This would be the first residential research library at a UK university, and would offer researchers access to the collections of Ushaw College and [[Durham Cathedral]] as well as the university's special collections at the Palace Green Library. It is planned that visiting researchers would also participate in the public engagement programme at Ushaw.<ref name=\"Ushaw Library\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/15067492.Multi_million_pound_plans_for_new_international_residential_research_library_unveiled/|title= Multi-million pound plans for new international residential research library at Ushaw College unveiled|date=3 February 2017|accessdate=3 February 2017|author=Gavin Engelbrecht|work=Northern Echo}}</ref>\n\n===Museums===\n[[File:Durham Kathedrale.jpg|thumb|right|The Old Fulling Mill, original home of the University Museum in 1833, on the bank of the River Wear below Durham Cathedral]]\nThe university manages a number of museums. Built in the 1960s, the [[Durham University Oriental Museum]] grew predominantly from the acquisitions of the university's former School of Oriental Studies.<ref name=\"Oriental Museum:History of the Museum\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/oriental.museum/history/|title=History of the Museum|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=11 January 2009}}</ref> Initially housed across the university and used as a teaching collection, the size of the collection led to the building of the current museum to house the material.<ref name=\"Oriental Museum:History of the Museum\"/> The collection to date contains over 30,000 objects from Asian art to antiquities, covering the [[Orient]] and [[Levant]] to the Far East and the [[Indian Sub-continent]], with over a third of the collection relating to China.<ref name=\"Oriental Museum:History of the Museum\"/><ref name=\"Oriental Museum:Chinese\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/oriental.museum/collections/chinese/|title=Chinese|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=11 January 2009}}</ref> The national importance of the Chinese and Egyptian collections can be seen in the Designated Status from the [[Museums, Libraries and Archives Council]] achieved in 2008.<ref name=\"Oriental Museum:Chinese\"/><ref name=\"Oriental Museum:Egyptian\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/oriental.museum/collections/egypt/|title=Egypt|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=11 January 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"DESIGNATION UPDATE Spring 2008\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mla.gov.uk/what/raising_standards/~/media/Files/pdf/2008/designation_update_spring2008|title=Museums, Libraries and Archives Council DESIGNATION UPDATE Spring 2008|publisher=Museums, Libraries and Archives Council|accessdate=11 January 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090210224051/http://www.mla.gov.uk/what/raising_standards/~/media/Files/pdf/2008/designation_update_spring2008|archivedate=10 February 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Durham University Museum of Archaeology]] moved to Palace Green in 2014, having previously been housed in the Old Fulling Mill on the banks of the Wear. The museum was opened in 1833, being the second university museum in England to allow admittance to the general public.<ref name=\"Museum of Archaeology:History of the Museum\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/archaeology.museum/about/history/|title=History of the Museum|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=5 February 2009}}</ref> The museum focuses on the heritage of North East England and includes national and international collections spanning the [[Prehistoric]], Ancient Greek, [[Roman Britain|Roman]], [[Anglo-Saxon]], [[Medieval]] and [[Post Medieval]] periods.<ref name=\"Museum of Archaeology:Collections of the Museum\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/archaeology.museum/whatshere/|title=What's Here|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=5 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Organisation and administration==\n\n===Academic year===\nThe academic year at Durham is divided into three terms: [[Michaelmas term]], which lasts 10 weeks from October to December; [[Epiphany term]], which lasts nine weeks from January to March; and [[Easter term]], which lasts nine weeks from April to June. All terms start on a Monday. The weeks of term are called \"Teaching Weeks\", numbered from 1 (start of Michaelmas) to 28 (end of Easter), although this period is used for teaching and exams. Additionally, there is an \"Induction Week\" (informally known as \"Freshers' Week\" or Week 0) for first year students prior to the start of Michaelmas term, starting on the first Monday in October.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/dates/|title=Dates of meetings and events|accessdate=3 October 2015|publisher=Durham University}}</ref>\n\nStudents at the university are also expected to \"Keep Term\", whereby students must fulfil their academic requirements at the university. As such Heads of Departments must be satisfied that each student has attended all necessary tutorials, seminars and practical work throughout the term and vacation period.<ref>{{cite web|title=Regulations \u2013 Keeping Terms|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/university.calendar/volumei/current/regs.keeping_terms.pdf|archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20070926121421/http://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/university.calendar/volumei/current/regs.keeping_terms.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=26 September 2007|publisher=Durham University}}</ref>\n\n===Colleges===\n{{main|Colleges of the University of Durham}}\n[[File:Durham Castle Innenhof.jpg|thumb|[[University College, Durham|University College]] is the oldest of the Durham colleges]]\nDurham operates a collegiate structure similar to that of the University of Oxford and the University of Cambridge, in that all the colleges at Durham (and the [[Wesley Study Centre]]) are \"listed bodies\" in part two of the Education (Listed Bodies) (England) Order 2013 made under the [[Education Reform Act 1988]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2013/2993/made|title=The Education (Listed Bodies) (England) Order 2013|date=30 December 2013|accessdate=4 October 2015}}</ref> as bodies that appear to the Secretary of State \"to be a constituent college, school, hall or other institution of a university which is such a recognised body\" (the \"recognised body\" being, in this case, Durham University).<ref>{{cite web|title=Recognised UK Degrees|url=http://www.dfes.gov.uk/recognisedukdegrees/index.cfm?fuseaction=institutes.list&InstituteCategoryID=2|publisher=DFES|accessdate=4 October 2015}}</ref> Though most of the Durham colleges are governed and owned directly by the university itself (the exceptions being St John's and St Chad's), the legal status of the Durham colleges is similar to Oxbridge colleges, setting them apart from those at the universities of Kent, Lancaster, and York.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=U7H_m5ji-IwC&pg=PA72#v=onepage&q&f=false|pages=72\u201373|title=The Collegial Tradition in the Age of Mass Higher Education|author1=Ted Tapper|author2=David Palfreyman|date=20 July 2010|publisher=[[Springer Science+Business Media]]}}</ref> However, unlike at Oxford and Cambridge, there is no formal teaching at Durham colleges (with the exception of [[Cranmer Hall, Durham|Cranmer Hall]] theological college within St John's), although colleges are active in research.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/collegesresearch/|title=Research in Colleges|accessdate=4 October 2015|publisher=Durham University}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://community.dur.ac.uk/cranmer.hall/|title=Welcome to Cranmer Hall|accessdate=4 October 2015|publisher=Cranmer Hall}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk/durham/international|title=Durham University|quote=Colleges are not teaching bodies and are not linked to any particular academic department; all teaching is delivered through the various departments.|publisher=Complete University Guide|accessdate=4 October 2015}}</ref> The colleges dominate the residential, social, sporting, and pastoral functions within the university, and there is heavy student involvement in their operation.\n\n[[Formal (university)|Formal dinner]]s (known as \"formals\") are held at every college; [[Academic dress of Durham University|gowns]] are worn to these events at just over half of the colleges. Gowns are not worn for formals at Collingwood, St Aidan's, St Cuthbert's, Hild Bede, Van Mildert, Stephenson or Ustinov.<ref>{{cite book|url=http://issuu.com/communicationsoffice/docs/ugp2016_singlepages_v4_final|title=Durham University Undergraduate Prospectus 2016|page=26|publisher=Durham University}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/postgraduate/accommodation/features/|title=Which College is right for me?|accessdate=3 October 2015|publisher=Durham University}}</ref> There is a great deal of intercollegiate rivalry, particularly in [[Durham College Rowing|rowing]] and other sporting activities. There is also rivalry between the older \"[[Bailey Colleges|Bailey]]\" colleges and the newer \"Hill\" colleges.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.durhamstudent.co.uk/colleges/|title=The Ultimate Guide to Durham's Colleges|accessdate=3 October 2015|publisher=Durham Student}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.palatinate.org.uk/?p=35020|title=Reviewed and interviewed: Novice Cup 2013|accessdate=3 October 2015|work=[[Palatinate (newspaper)|Palatinate]]}}</ref>\n\nThe colleges are:\n{{Div col|colwidth=20em}}\n{{ordered list|type=none\n | [[File:Durham - Collingwood arms.png|15px]] [[Collingwood College, Durham|Collingwood College]]\n | [[File:Durham - Grey arms.png|15px]] [[Grey College, Durham|Grey College]]\n | [[File:Durham - Hatfield arms.png|15px]] [[Hatfield College]]\n | [[File:Durham - John Snow arms.png|15px]] [[John Snow College]]\n | [[File:Josephine Butler College Crest.png|15px]] [[Josephine Butler College]]\n | [[File:Durham - St Aidan's arms.png|15px]] [[St Aidan's College, Durham|St Aidan's College]]\n | [[File:Durham - St Chads arms.png|15px]] [[St Chad's College]]\n | [[File:Durham - St Cuthberts arms.png|15px]] [[St Cuthbert's Society]]\n | [[File:Durham - St Hild and Bede arms.png|15px]] [[College of St Hild and St Bede]]\n | [[File:Durham - St Johns arms.png|15px]] [[St John's College, Durham|St John's College]]\n | [[File:Durham - St Marys arms.png|15px]] [[St Mary's College, Durham|St Mary's College]]\n | [[South College, Durham|South College]] (due to open in 2020)\n | [[File:Durham - George Stephenson arms.png|15px]] [[Stephenson College, Durham|Stephenson College]]\n | [[File:Durham - Trevelyan arms.png|15px]] [[Trevelyan College]]\n | [[File:Durham - University College arms.png|15px]] [[University College, Durham|University College]]\n | [[File:Durham - Ustinov arms.png|15px]] [[Ustinov College]]\n | [[File:Van Mildert Coll Durham shield.svg|15px]] [[Van Mildert College]]\n}}\n{{Div col end}}\n\n===Governance===\n{{see also|List of Chancellors of the University of Durham|List of Vice-Chancellor & Wardens of the University of Durham}}\n[[File:The Venerable Charles Thorp.jpg|thumb|right|Archdeacon [[Charles Thorp]], founder and first Warden of Durham]]\nThe University is governed by the Statutes put in place by the Universities of Durham and Newcastle upon Tyne Act, 1963, and subsequently amended by the [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Council]]. The Statutes provide that: \"The University shall be governed by a Visitor, Chancellor, Vice-Chancellor, Convocation, Council, Senate, and Boards of Studies.\" (Statute 4).\n<ref name=Statutes>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/university.calendar/volumei/statutes/|title=University Statues|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=1 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Visitor]] for the University of Durham is the [[Bishop of Durham]]. The Visitor is the final arbiter of any dispute within the university, except in those areas where legislation has removed this to the law courts or other [[ombudsman|ombudsmen]], or in matters internal to the two non-maintained colleges (St Chad's College and St John's College), each of which has its own Visitor. Student complaints and appeals were heard by the Visitor until the [[Higher Education Act 2004]] came into force.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.opsi.gov.uk/ACTS/acts2004/40008--c.htm#20 |title=Section 20 of the Higher Education Act 2004 |publisher=Government of the United Kingdom |date=26 October 2011 |accessdate=1 November 2011}}</ref> All student complaints are now heard by the [[Office of the Independent Adjudicator]] for Higher Education.\n\nThe [[Chancellor (education)|Chancellor]] of the university is [[Thomas Allen (baritone)|Sir Thomas Allen]], who succeeded [[Bill Bryson]] in January 2012.<ref name=\"chancellor\"/> The Chancellor is appointed by Convocation for \"a fixed period of not normally less than five years as determined by the Council\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/university.calendar/volumei/statutes/|title=University Statutes|publisher=Durham University|at=Statue 6|accessdate=1 March 2016}}</ref> which can be renewed. The role of the Chancellor is mainly ceremonial; The Vice-Chancellor (formally the ''Vice-Chancellor and Warden'') is the Chief Executive Officer of the University and is appointed by Council.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/vice.chancellor/|title=Vice-Chancellor|accessdate=1 March 2016|publisher=Durham University}}</ref> As Warden the Vice-Chancellor is responsible for the 14 maintained colleges of the University.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/about/governance/|title=How the University is run|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=2 March 2016|quote=\"In his role as Warden, the Vice-Chancellor and Warden also has overall responsibility for fourteen of the University's Colleges \u2013 the Heads of College are directly responsible to the Vice-Chancellor through the Pro-Vice-Chancellor and Deputy Warden of the Colleges. The two recognised Colleges, St John's and St Chad's, are independent foundations with separate Governing Councils.\"}}</ref> Since September 2015 this has been [[Stuart Corbridge]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Tallentire|first1=Mark|title=Durham University names new head|url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/11885190.Durham_University_names_new_head/|accessdate=31 March 2015|work=The Northern Echo|date=27 March 2015}}</ref> succeeding [[Chris Higgins (academic)|Chris Higgins]] who retired in September 2014.<ref name=\"Northern Echo - Durham University vice-chancellor to retire in September\">{{cite news|last=Tallentire|first=Mark|title=Durham University vice-chancellor to retire in September|url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/11054695.Durham_University_vice_chancellor_to_retire_in_September|accessdate=5 March 2014|newspaper=The Northern Echo|date=5 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Durham Graduation.jpg|thumb|left|The university's graduation ceremonies take place in [[Durham Cathedral]] with receptions on [[Palace Green]]]]\n[[Convocation]] is the assembly of the university. Membership of Convocation is open to: the Chancellor, Vice-Chancellor, and Pro-Vice-Chancellors, all graduates, the teaching staff (lecturers, senior lecturers, readers, and professors), and the heads of colleges and licensed halls of residence. It must meet once each year in order to hear the Vice-Chancellor's Address and to debate any business relating to the university. Further meetings can be called if representation is made by a minimum of 50 members. Its powers are limited to appointing the Chancellor (and even then, only on the nomination of Council and Senate) and the making of representations to the university on any business debated (Statute 30).<ref name=Statutes />\n\n[[University council|Council]] is the executive body of the university. In addition to representatives from the university it includes up to 12 lay members (not being teachers or salaried staff in the university or any of its colleges), the [[Dean of Durham]] and the President of Durham Students' Union (Statute 10). Its powers include establishing and maintaining colleges, and recognising non-maintained colleges and licensed halls of residence (Statutes 12 & 13).\n\n[[File:Bill Bryson Chancellor.JPG|thumb|upright|[[Bill Bryson]] (Chancellor 2005\u20132012) in the academic dress of Chancellor of Durham University]]\n[[Academic Senate|Senate]] is the supreme governing body of the university in academic matters. It nominates the Vice-Chancellor and Pro-Vice-Chancellors to Council, and recommends the establishment of Faculties and Boards of Studies. It is Senate that grants degrees, and has the authority to revoke them. It also regulates the use of [[Academic dress of Durham University|academic dress]] of the university (Statutes 19 & 20).<ref name=Statutes />\n\nThe day-to-day running of the University is in the hands of the University Executive Committee (UEC), which is also responsible for the development of the policies and strategies. This is a joint subcommittee of Senate and Council and consists of the Vice-Chancellor and Warden, the Deputy Vice-Chancellor and Provost ([[Chief Academic Officer]]), the two portfolio Pro-Vice-Chancellors (for Education and Research), the three faculty Pro-Vice-Chancellors, the Pro-Vice-Chancellor and Deputy Warden (who has responsibility for the colleges), the Registrar (chief operating officer) and the Treasurer (chief financial officer). All heads of departments and of colleges report directly to one of the members of the UEC.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/committees/uec/ways_working/|title=Ways of Working: Roles and Responsibilities|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=2 March 2016|date=29 January 2016|author=[[Stuart Corbridge]]}}</ref><ref name=\"University Executive Committee\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/committees/uec_standing_orders/|title=University Executive Committee|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=2 March 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"University Executive Committee\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/news/newsitem/?id=29142&itemno=29142|title= Durham appoints Deputy Vice-Chancellor and Provost|date=10 October 2016|publisher=Durham University}}</ref>\n\n===Schools and faculties===\nThe teaching departments of the university are divided into four faculties: Science, Arts and Humanities, Social Sciences and Health, and the Business School. Each faculty is headed by a Pro-Vice-Chancellor and one or more Deputies. These, along with the heads of the departments in the faculty and the Vice-Chancellor, make up the Faculty Board for that faculty. Each department also has a Board of Studies consisting of the Pro-Vice-Chancellor of their faculty, the teaching staff of the department, and student representatives (Statute 29).<ref name=Statutes /> Associated with the first three faculties are three combined honours degrees: Natural Sciences (BSc & MSci), Liberal Arts (BA), and Combined Honours in Social Sciences (BA).<ref>{{cite book|url=https://issuu.com/CommunicationsOffice/docs/ugp2017|pages=54\u201355, 80\u201381, 90\u201391|publisher=Durham University|date=March 2016|title=Undergraduate Prospectus 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe largest degree programmes offered by the university, by number of entrants from the 2013\u201314 admissions cycle, were Business, Accounting and Finance (395), Natural Sciences (221), Modern Languages and Cultures (216), and Geography (216).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/ug.admissions/admindocuments/admincycle1314/2-1-5DepartmentalSummaryFinalAS12Replies.pdf|title=2\u20131\u20135 Departmental Summary \u2013 Final (AS12 Replies) 2013/2014 Admissions Cycle|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=1 October 2015|format=PDF}}</ref>\n\n{{Div col}}\n\n'''Faculty of Social Science & Health'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/socialsciences.health/|title=Faculty of Social Sciences & Health|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=4 March 2016}}</ref>\n* Department of Anthropology\n* Department of Archaeology\n* School of Education\n* Department of Geography\n* School of Government and International Affairs <br /> (''Including the Politics Department and the Institute for Middle East and Islamic Studies'')\n* [[Durham Law Department|Durham Law School]]\n* Department of Sociology\n*Department of Sport and Exercise Sciences\n\n'''Faculty of Arts and Humanities'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/arts.humanities/aboutfaculty/|title=About The Faculty|website=Faculty of Arts and Humanities|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=3 March 2016}}</ref>\n*Department of Classics & Ancient History\n*Department of English Studies\n*Department of History\n*School of Modern Languages and Cultures <br /> (''Includes Arabic, Chinese, Japanese, French, German, Italian, Russian, and Hispanic Studies Departments'')\n* [[Durham University Department of Music|Department of Music]]\n*Department of Philosophy\n*Department of Theology and Religion\n*English Language Centre\n*Centre for Foreign Language Study\n\n'''Faculty of Science'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/science.faculty/|title=Faculty of Science|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=4 March 2016}}</ref>\n*Department of Biosciences\n*Department of Chemistry\n*Department of Computer Science\n*Department of Earth Sciences\n*[[Durham University School of Engineering|Department of Engineering]]\n*Department of Mathematical Science\n*[[Durham University Department of Physics|Department of Physics]]\n*Department of Psychology\n\n'''Faculty of Business ([[Durham University Business School]])'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/university.calendar/volumei/boards_of_studies/|title=University Calendar|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=31 August 2019}}</ref>\n*Department of Accounting\n*Department of Economics and Finance\n*Department of Management and Marketing\n\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==Academic profile==\n\n===Admissions===\n{| class=\"wikitable floatright\" style=\"font-size:85%; text-align:center;\"\n|+ UCAS Admission Statistics\n!\n!2017\n!2016\n!2015\n!2014\n!2013\n|-\n|'''Applications'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ucas.com/file/144241/download?token=nlVZq6el|title=End of Cycle 2017 Data Resources DR4_001_03 Applications by provider|year=2017|website=UCAS|publisher=UCAS|access-date=25 January 2018}}</ref>\n|28,895\n|29,485\n|28,085\n|26,635\n|25,895\n|-\n|'''Offer Rate (%)'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Sex, area background and ethnic group: D86 Durham University|url=https://www.ucas.com/file/145051/download?token=BOfbnBrr|year=2017|website=UCAS|publisher=UCAS|accessdate=25 January 2018}}</ref>\n|74.2\n|70.7\n|69.0\n|68.4\n|58.9\n|-\n|'''Enrols'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ucas.com/file/144196/download?token=JEpp6fiF|title=End of Cycle 2017 Data Resources DR4_001_02 Main scheme acceptances by provider|year=2017|website=UCAS|publisher=UCAS|access-date=25 January 2018}}</ref>\n|4,510\n|4,475\n|4,190\n|4,175\n|4,165\n|-\n|[[Yield (college admissions)|'''Yield (%)''']]\n|21.0\n|21.5\n|21.6\n|22.9\n|27.3\n|-\n|'''Applicant/Enrolled Ratio'''\n|6.41\n|6.59\n|6.70\n|6.38\n|6.22\n|-\n|'''[[UCAS Tariff|Average Entry Tariff]]'''<ref name=\"Complete League Table 2019\">{{cite-web|url=https://www.thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk/league-tables/rankings|title=Top UK University League Table and Rankings|publisher=Complete University Guide}}</ref><ref group=note>New [[UCAS]] points from 2016</ref>\n|n/a\n|197\n|519\n|524\n|521\n|}\n\n[[File:Cosin's Hall, Durham.jpg|right|thumb|Cosin's Hall, home to the [[Institute of Advanced Study (Durham)|Institute of Advanced Study]]]]\nThe average [[UCAS]] point score for new entrants in 2016\u201317 was 197 points, placing Durham University eighth in the country in terms of entrants' points.<ref name=\"CUG UCAS\" /> Durham's student body consists of {{HESA undergraduate population|INSTID=0116}} undergraduates and {{HESA postgraduate population|INSTID=0116}}  postgraduate students ({{HESA year}}).<ref name=\"HESA citation\"/> In 2014/15, Durham had the fourth highest number of students from middle class backgrounds at 85.8 per cent.<ref name=\"Most Middle Class\">{{cite news|url=http://st.hitcreative.com/education/university_guide/active/UniversityGuide/table/year/2016/type/derived/id/106|title=Most Middle Class |work=[[The Times]]/[[Sunday Times]]}}</ref> For the same year, 34.3 per cent of the undergraduate full-time student population came from independent schools and 8.75% from [[grammar schools]],<ref name=\"Total Undergraduate by School Type - Full-Time 2014/2015\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/student.registry/statistics/undergraduate/2.7school/2.7total/142-7b.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160201065236/https://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/student.registry/statistics/undergraduate/2.7school/2.7total/142-7b.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=1 February 2016|title=Total Undergraduate by School Type \u2013 Full-Time 2014/2015|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=4 October 2015}}</ref> 19.35 per cent of full-time students are of ethnic minorities.<ref name=\"Undergraduate Total Students Ethnicity - Full-Time 2014/2016\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/student.registry/statistics/undergraduate/2.10ethnicity/2.10full/142-10a.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160201065237/https://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/student.registry/statistics/undergraduate/2.10ethnicity/2.10full/142-10a.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=1 February 2016|title=Undergraduate Total Students Ethnicity \u2013 Full-Time 2014/2015|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=4 October 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Undergraduate Students by Gender - Full-Time 2007/2008\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/student.registry/statistics/undergraduate/2.4gender/2.4ft/142-4a.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160201065236/https://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/student.registry/statistics/undergraduate/2.4gender/2.4ft/142-4a.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=1 February 2016|title=Undergraduate Students by Gender \u2013 Full-Time 2014/2015|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=4 October 2015}}</ref> In 2014\u201315, 44.8 per cent of full-time undergraduate students lived in University (including St John's and St Chad's colleges) accommodation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/student.registry/statistics/college/4.1accommodation/4.1ft/144-1a.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160201065236/https://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/student.registry/statistics/college/4.1accommodation/4.1ft/144-1a.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=1 February 2016|title=Undergraduate Student Accommodation \u2013 Full Time 2014/2015|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=4 October 2015}}</ref> The university gave offers of admission to 69 per cent of 18-year-old applicants in 2015, the 9th lowest amongst the [[Russell Group]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Which elite universities have the highest offer rates |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/education/2016/10/19/which-elite-universities-have-the-highest-offer-rates/|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=21 October 2016}}</ref> In the 2016\u201317 academic year, the university had a domicile breakdown of 73:6:22 of UK:EU:non-EU students respectively with a female to male ratio of 55:45.<ref>{{cite web|title=Where do HE students study?|url=https://www.hesa.ac.uk/data-and-analysis/students/where-study#provider|website=hesa.ac.uk|publisher=Higher Education Statistics Authority|accessdate=9 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nDurham charges undergraduate fees of \u00a39,250 for home/EU students.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/treasurer/students/tuition_fees/full_time_undergraduates/years/1920/|title=Finance Department|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=26 June 2019}}</ref> Following the Government's announcement in 2016 that fees in England would be allowed to rise by 2.8 per cent (from the then maximum level of\u00a39,000), Durham became one of the first universities in the country to announce it intended to take advantage of this to raise fees to the new maximum of \u00a39,250 for students entering from 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2016/jul/20/english-universities-to-raise-tuition-fees-for-first-time-since-they-trebled|title=English universities to raise tuition fees for first time since they trebled|date=20 July 2016|author=Richard Adams|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref>\n\nFor the undergraduate admissions cycle 2013\u201314, Durham received 26,030 applications (for around 4,200 places),<ref name=\"Total Applications 2013/2014\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/ug.admissions/admindocuments/admincycle1314/1-1TotalApplications.pdf|title=Total Application 2013/2014|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=4 October 2015}}</ref> of which 38.4 per cent were from independent schools<ref name=\"School Types (State/Independent) 2013/2014\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/ug.admissions/admindocuments/admincycle1314/1-4ApplicationsbySchoolTypeState-Independent.pdf|title=Admissions Statistics Documents:School Types (State/Independent) 2013/2014|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=4 October 2015}}</ref> and 13.8 per cent (of UK applications) from ethnic minorities,<ref name=\"Ethnicity and Fee Status Detail: Applications 2013/2014\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/ug.admissions/admindocuments/admincycle1314/1-5-1EthnicityandFeeStatusDetail-Applications.pdf|title=Ethnicity and Fee Status Detail: Applications 2013/2014|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=4 October 2015}}</ref> overall 64.2 per cent of applicants were successful in receiving an offer of admissions.<ref name=\"Total Applications 2013/2014\"/> Durham requires students applying for degrees in law to sit the [[LNAT]] admission test.<ref name=\"LNAT\">{{cite web|url=http://www.lnat.ac.uk/what-is-lnat/do-i-need-to-sit-the-test/|title=Do I need to sit the test??|publisher=LNAT|accessdate=4 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Widening access===\nDurham has been criticised for not accepting as many students from low participation neighbourhoods, and from state schools, as might be expected from its admission standards and course offerings. For admissions in 2015/16, Durham had the third lowest percentage of state school students (among higher education institutions with over 1,000 full-time first-degree entrants) at 60.5 per cent, compared to a [[Higher Education Statistics Agency]] benchmark of 75 per cent. According to pro-vice-chancellor, Alan Hudson, this was a temporary drop from the 63 per cent level the university has reached in recent years, and to which it was expected to return in 2016/17. The university also fell short of its benchmark for admissions from low participation neighbourhoods, accepting 5.1 per cent, compared to a benchmark of 6 per cent.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/data-analysis-latest-hesa-figures-state-school-entrants|work=Times Higher Education|title=Data analysis: latest Hesa figures on state school entrants|date=3 February 2017|author=John Elmes}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/north-east-news/durham-university-one-lowest-admission-12554295|work=Chronicle Live|author=Hannah Graham|date=4 February 2017|title=Durham University has one of the lowest admission rates for pupils from state schools}}</ref> The data for 2016/17 showed that admissions from state schools had recovered to 62.9 per cent, still short of the location-adjusted benchmark of 74.9 per cent, and that admissions from low participation neighbourhoods were 5.2 per cent compared to the location-adjusted benchmark of 6.6 per cent.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hesa.ac.uk/news/01-02-2018/widening-participation-tables|title=Widening participation: UK Performance Indicators 2016/17|publisher=Higher Education Statistics Agency|accessdate=1 September 2018|date=1 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nSince 1992 the university has run a widening access programme, originally called the Centre for Lifelong Learning and now known as the Durham Centre for Academic Development. The centre provides access to Durham degrees for mature students who show academic promise but do not hold the traditional entry requirements. The centre runs a range of [[foundation year]] courses associated with specific degree courses. For the 2013\u201314 admissions cycle, 153 students took up offers of places in the programme.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/foundation.programme/|title=The Foundation Programme|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=1 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/ug.admissions/admindocuments/admissions-2007-08/1-5.pdf|title=Departmental Summary \u2013 Final (AS12) Replies 2013/2014 Admissions Cycle|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=1 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nDurham has partnered with the [[Sutton Trust]] since 2012 to run the Durham University Sutton Trust Summer School for [[Gifted education#United Kingdom|gifted and talented]] school children from underrepresented backgrounds, leading to qualification with 16 to 32 [[UCAS Tariff]] points and a guaranteed conditional offer from Durham if they choose to apply.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://summerschools.suttontrust.com/host-universities/durham-university/|title=Durham University|accessdate=1 October 2015|publisher=[[Sutton Trust]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150721193349/http://summerschools.suttontrust.com/host-universities/durham-university/|archive-date=21 July 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/news/newsitem/?itemno=35514|title=State school students helped to reach university|date=29 August 2018|accessdate=1 September 2018|publisher=Durham University}}</ref> The University also runs the Durham International Summer School<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/international/summerschool/|title=International Summer School|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=1 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151004064836/https://www.dur.ac.uk/international/summerschool/|archive-date=4 October 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> and partners with the Sutton Trust to run the Durham Teacher Summer School.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.suttontrust.com/programmes/teacher-summer-schools/partner-universities/|title=Partner Universities|publisher=Sutton Trust|accessdate=23 February 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160302143703/http://www.suttontrust.com/programmes/teacher-summer-schools/partner-universities/|archive-date=2 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Durham became the first UK university to participate in the [[Inside-Out Prison Exchange Program]].<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2016/feb/22/prison-education-university-kent-jail-swaleside|title=Prison no bar to higher education as university \u2018campus\u2019 opens in Kent jail|date=22 February 2016|author=Eric Allison}}</ref> The scheme, where students study alongside inmates, ran in [[Durham Prison]] and the high-security [[HM Prison Frankland|Frankland Prison]] in 2015 and was expanded to include [[HM Prison Low Newton|Low Newton Prison]] in 2016.<ref>{{cite news|work=BBC News|title=Durham University's Inside-Out scheme sees students study with prisoners|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-tyne-35409927|date=30 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/sociology/crim/insideout/|title=Durham University Inside-Out Prison Exchange Programme|website=Durham University Department of Sociology|accessdate=11 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nDurham gives a bursary, known as the Durham Grant, of \u00a32,000 per year to students from households with an annual income of less than \u00a325,000. The University planned to reduce this to \u00a31,800 per year for students entering from 2016 onwards, after the [[Office for Fair Access]] encouraged moving away from bursaries to other schemes to widen participation. However, this decision was reversed after the government decided to abolish maintenance grants.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.palatinate.org.uk/university-backtracks-on-durham-grant-scheme/|title=University backtracks on Durham Grant Scheme|date=25 February 2016|newspaper=[[Palatinate (newspaper)|Palatinate]]}}</ref> The University also runs the \"Supported Progression\" programme for sixth-form students, aimed at helping talented young people from the North East, Cumbria and Yorkshire to fulfill their potential via a two-year structured programme of events.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cumbriacrack.com/2017/01/26/st-benedicts-sixth-form-students-accepted-onto-durham-university-programme/|title=St Benedict's Sixth Form Students accepted onto Durham University programme|work=Cumbria Crack|author=Carl Fallowfield |date= 26 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Research===\n[[File:View from the 4th floor of the Calman centre.jpg|thumb|right|The Dawson Building houses the departments of Archaeology and Anthropology]]\nThe university is part of the [[Russell Group]], [[Virgo Consortium]] and the [[N8 Group]] of Universities.\nAccording to the latest [[CWTS Leiden Ranking]] 2018 that measures the scientific performance of 500 major universities worldwide, Durham is ranked 89th in the world in terms of the proportion of its academic papers in the top 10 per cent for impact (the \"PP(top 10%)\" measure).<ref name=Leiden2018>{{cite web|url=http://www.leidenranking.com/ranking/2018/list |title=Leiden Ranking 2018 |publisher= Leiden University |accessdate=11 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nResearch institutes at the university include the [[Centre for the Advanced Study of the Arab World]], the [[Durham Energy Institute]], the Institute for Hazard and Risk Research, the [[Institute of Advanced Study (Durham)|Institute of Advanced Study]], the [[International Boundaries Research Unit]] and the [[Institute for Computational Cosmology]].\n\nIn the 2014 [[Research Excellence Framework]], Durham was assessed to have a research profile of 33 per cent world class (4*), 50 per cent internationally important (3*), 15 per cent internationally recognised (2*), and 1 per cent nationally recognised (1*).<ref name=\"THE REF 2014\">{{cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/ref-2014-results-table-of-excellence/2017590.article|title=REF 2014 results: table of excellence|newspaper=[[Times Higher Education]]|date=18 December 2014|author=Paul Jump}}</ref> which was an improvement on the 2008 [[Research Assessment Exercise]].<ref name=\"THE RAE 2008\">{{cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/features/research-assessment-exercise-rae-results-2008/404786.article|title=Research Assessment Exercise (RAE) results, 2008|newspaper=[[Times Higher Education]]|date=18 December 2008}}</ref> However, this was in the context of a rise in the average profile from 2008 to 2015.<ref name=\"THE REF 2014\"/> In the [[Times Higher Education]] ranking by [[grade point average]] (GPA; measuring average quality), Durham fell from joint 14th in 2008 to 20th in 2014 despite a rise in GPA from 2.72 to 3.14.<ref name=\"THE REF 2014\"/> Similarly, Durham fell from 19th to 20th in the Times Higher Education ranking by total research power.<ref name=\"THE REF 2014\"/> However, in Research Fortnight's ranking by total research power (which uses a weighting closer to that used by [[HEFCE]] in making funding allocations, with 2* and 1* research zero-weighted<ref name=\"RSS REF\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rss.org.uk/Images/PDF/about/press-releases/rss-press-release-ref-league-tables-report-11-05-2015.pdf|title=Report from the RSS Working Group on Research Excellence Framework (REF) League Tables|publisher=[[Royal Statistical Society]]|date=11 May 2015}}</ref>) Durham rose from 19th in 2008 to 18th in 2014.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/education/universityeducation/11299261/League-tables-the-top-universities-for-research.html|title=League tables: the top universities|date=18 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Rankings and reputation===\n{{Infobox UK university rankings\n| ARWU_W = 201\u2013300\n| QS_W = =78\n| THE_W = 133\n| LEIDEN_W = 97\n| LINE_1 = 0\n| Complete = 6\n| The_Guardian = 5\n| Times/Sunday_Times = 7\n| LINE_2 = 0\n| TEF = Gold\n}}\n[[File:Durham Law School.jpg|thumb|right|[[Durham Law School]]]]\n\n<!-- note RAE/REF ratings discussed under \"research\" above -->\nDurham University's Strategic Plan 2017\u20132027 defines targets of being in the top 5 nationally on the Times/Sunday Times league table, of having 50 per cent of eligible subjects in the top 50 globally on the QS world rankings, and of being in the top three UK institutions by citations per academic staff member.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/strategy2027/performance/|title=Measuring our Performance|work=University Strategy 2017\u20132027|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=25 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe earlier 2010\u20132020 strategic plan called for it \"to be in the top 5 universities in major UK league tables\" (defined as the Times/Sunday Times Good University Guide and the Complete University Guide) and \"to be in the top 50 universities in the Times Higher Education world rankings by 2020\".<ref name=kpi2015>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/treasurer/financial_statements/Financial_Statements_2015.pdf|title=Financial Statements for the year ended 31 July 2015|publisher=Durham University|page=7}}</ref> The first objective was met in 2012 and 2015, the second remains as yet unmet, with Durham ranking 70th in the world in 2015.<ref name=kpi2015/> The previous 2005\u20132010 strategic plan called for Durham \"to be ranked among the top 30 universities in Europe and the top 100 in the world in the Times Higher Education Supplement international league tables\";<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/treasurer/financial_statements/947FinancialStatementsALL_A4.pdf|title=Financial Statements for the year ended 31 July 2009|publisher=Durham University|page=6}}</ref> Durham ranked 85th in the world (19th in Europe) in 2010 and has since maintained its position in the top 100.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The Guardian|title=The top 100 universities 2010 \u2013 how the Times Higher Education ranks them|url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/datablog/2010/sep/16/top-100-universities-times-higher-education|author=Simon Rogers|date=16 September 2010}}</ref>\n\n;National\nDurham consistently places in the top ten in [[rankings of universities in the United Kingdom]].<ref group=note>It has ranked in the Times top ten since the 2004 tables, the Complete University Guide top ten since it was founded in 2007 (2008 tables) and the Guardian top ten since the 2012 tables.{{cite web|title=Domestic Ranking of British Universities over a 10-Year Period|url=http://theuniversitybuzz.blogspot.co.uk/2017/01/domestic-ranking-of-british.html|publisher=The University Buzz}}</ref> The 2018 ''[[Complete University Guide]]'' ranks Durham 6th overall,<ref name=\"CUG 2018 Durham\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk/durham/performance|title=Durham University|publisher=Complete University Guide|accessdate=25 May 2017}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]] University Guide 2018'' ranks Durham 4th overall<ref name=\"Durham Guardian\"/> and the 2018 ''[[The Times]]/[[Sunday Times]] Good University Guide'' ranks Durham 5th overall.\n\n;Subject\n\nIn the 2020 ''[[Complete University Guide]]'' subject rankings, Durham is top in the UK for English and Music. The university ranks second for French, Geography & Environmental Science, Iberian Languages, Middle Eastern & African Studies, and Theology & Religious Studies. Third for Archaeology, Chemistry, Classics & Ancient History, German, History, Italian, and Russian & East European Languages.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk/durham/performance|title=League Table Performance \u2013 Durham University|website=thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk|access-date=12 May 2019}}</ref> With 30/33 subjects ranked in the top 10, Durham is one of only four universities (along with [[University of Oxford|Oxford]], [[Cambridge]], and [[Imperial College London]]) to have over 90 per cent of their subjects in the top 10 in this ranking.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk/league-tables/who-ranks-top-of-the-tables-by-subject-2020/|title=Who Ranks Top of the Tables by Subject 2020|website=thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk|access-date=12 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn ''[[The Guardian]]'' 2018 subject rankings Durham ranks first in Archaeology, second in Education, and third in Chemistry, Earth Sciences, English, Geography & Environmental Studies, and Religious Studies & Theology.<ref name=\"Durham Guardian\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/news/newsitem/?itemno=31396|title=Durham ranked 4th in The Guardian University Guide|accessdate=25 May 2017|date=16 May 2017|publisher=Durham University}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2018 ''[[The Times]]/[[Sunday Times]] Good University Guide'' subject rankings, Durham is top in music and joint top in English.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/news/newsitem/?itemno=32371|title=Durham ranked 5th in the UK|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=26 November 2017}}</ref> It also ranks second in archaeology and forensic science, East and South Asian studies, geography and environmental science, history, Iberian languages, Italian, and theology and religious studies; joint second in Russian and East European languages: and third in chemistry and education.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://st.hitcreative.com/education/university_guide/active/UniversityGuide/index/goto/league-tables|title=Good University Guide 2017|accessdate=26 November 2017|work=[[The Times]]/[[The Sunday Times]]}}</ref>\n\n;International\nDurham has been placed in the top 100 universities in the world in both the ''[[Times Higher Education]]'' (THE) and [[Quacquarelli Symonds]] (QS) rankings since 2010.<ref group=note>The university monitored both THE and QS rankings as part of its strategic plan until 2017, but did not monitor the Academic Ranking of World Universities (ARWU) or other international rankings.{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/strategic.planning/dataandanalysis/performanceevaluation/leaguetables/|title=Benchmarking League Table Performance|accessdate=24 February 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306103625/https://www.dur.ac.uk/strategic.planning/dataandanalysis/performanceevaluation/leaguetables/|archive-date=6 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Times Higher Education World University Rankings]] for 2017 place Durham 96th in the world (12th in the UK) in 2016, down from 70th in 2015. In the individual subject area rankings for 2016-7, Durham is placed 60th (2015-6: 83rd) in the world (8th in the UK) for physical sciences,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/world-university-rankings/2017/subject-ranking/physical-sciences#!/page/0/length/25/country/2784/sort_by/rank_label/sort_order/asc/cols/rank_only|title= World University Rankings 2016\u20132017 by subject: physical sciences |accessdate=30 September 2016|work=Times Higher Education}}</ref> 60th (2015-6: 36th) in the world (9th in the UK) for social sciences,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/world-university-rankings/2017/subject-ranking/social-sciences#!/page/0/length/25/country/2784/sort_by/rank_label/sort_order/asc/cols/rank_only|title= World University Rankings 2016\u20132017 by subject: social sciences |accessdate=30 September 2016|work=Times Higher Education}}</ref> and 29th (2015-6: 28th)in the world (6th in the UK) for arts and humanities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/world-university-rankings/2017/subject-ranking/arts-and-humanities#!/page/0/length/25/country/2784/sort_by/rank_label/sort_order/asc/cols/rank_only|title= World University Rankings 2016\u20132017 by subject: arts and humanities |accessdate=30 September 2016|work=Times Higher Education}}</ref> Durham is not ranked on the other top-100 subject tables (business and economics; computer science; engineering and technology; life sciences; clinical, pre-clinical and health). Durham re-entered the [[Times Higher Education World Reputation Rankings]] in the 91\u2013100 band in 2017, having not been ranked in the top 100 in 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/world-university-rankings/2017/reputation-ranking#!/page/0/length/25/locations/GB/sort_by/rank/sort_order/asc/cols/stats|title= World Reputation Rankings 2017|work=[[Times Higher Education]]|accessdate=14 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/world-university-rankings/2016/reputation-ranking#!/page/0/length/25/locations/GB/sort_by/rank/sort_order/asc/cols/stats|title=World Reputation Rankings 2016|work=[[Times Higher Education]]|accessdate=14 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe [[QS World University Rankings]] 2018 places Durham 78th in the world (12th in the UK), down from 74th in 2016/2017 and 61st in 2015 \u2013 the fall experienced by many UK universities in the rankings has been attributed to uncertainty over [[Brexit]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/student/into-university/applying/how-brexit-is-affecting-british-universities-funding-issues-higher-education-qs-world-university-a7227911.html|title= Post-Brexit uncertainty and long-term funding issues hit UK higher education, university rankings show|date=6 September 2016|author=Aftab Al|newspaper=[[The Independent]]}}</ref> In the \"faculty\" subject areas for 2017, Durham ranks 45th in the world (9th in the UK) for arts and humanities,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/university-subject-rankings/2017/arts-humanities|title=Arts and Humanities|publisher=QS Quacquarelli Symonds Limited|accessdate=8 July 2017}}</ref> 242nd in the world (26th in the UK) for engineering and technology,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/university-subject-rankings/2017/engineering-technology|title=Engineering and Technology|publisher=QS Quacquarelli Symonds Limited|accessdate=8 July 2017}}</ref> 368th in the world (31st in the UK) for life sciences and medicine,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/university-subject-rankings/2017/life-sciences-medicine|title=Life Sciences and Medicine|publisher=QS Quacquarelli Symonds Limited|accessdate=8 July 2017}}</ref> 72nd in the world (8th in the UK) for natural sciences,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/university-subject-rankings/2017/natural-sciences|title=Natural Sciences|publisher=QS Quacquarelli Symonds Limited|accessdate=8 July 2017}}</ref> and 98th in the world (13th in the UK) for social sciences and management.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/university-subject-rankings/2017/social-sciences-management|title=Social Sciences and Management|publisher=QS Quacquarelli Symonds Limited|accessdate=8 July 2017}}</ref> In the subject rankings for 2017, Durham was ranked 3rd in the world for theology, divinity and religious studies, 4th for archaeology and 7th for geography. Earth and marine sciences (24th), anthropology (35th), English language and literature (35th), history (37th) and law and legal studies (40th) also featured in the top 50 in the world, while Durham also ranked in the top 100 for chemistry, modern languages, physics and astronomy, politics, psychology, and sociology.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/research/news/item/?id=27614&itemno=27614|title=Durham rises in prestigious world rankings|date=22 March 2016|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=23 March 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"QS Durham\">{{cite web|url=http://www.topuniversities.com/universities/durham-university|publisher=QS Quacquarelli Symonds Limited|title=Durham University|accessdate=8 July 2017}}</ref> One of Durham's 2017\u20132027 strategic goals is to have half of its subjects in the top 50 globally on the QS ranking; in 2017 it had 8 in the top 50 out of 27 subjects ranked (30 per cent).<ref name=\"QS Durham\"/> Another 2017\u20132027 strategic goal is for Durham to be in the top three universities in the UK for research citations per faculty; the QS ranking 2018 placed Durham fourth in the UK (82nd globally) for this measure, behind the [[London Business School]], Cambridge and Oxford,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/world-university-rankings/2018|title=QS World University Rankings 2018 \u2013 Rankings indicators \u2013 Citations per faculty|publisher=QS Quacquarelli Symonds Limited|accessdate=10 June 2017}}</ref> slipping from second in the UK (43rd globally) in 2017.<ref name=\"Durham Guardian\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/world-university-rankings/2016|title=QS World University Rankings 2017 \u2013 Rankings indicators \u2013 Citations per faculty|publisher=QS Quacquarelli Symonds Limited|accessdate=25 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Shanghai [[Academic Ranking of World Universities]] placed Durham in the 201\u2013300 bracket. In individual subject areas, Durham is placed in the 51\u201375 bracket for science and the 101\u2013150 bracket for social science, it is not ranked in engineering, life sciences or medical sciences. In individual subjects, the ARWU places Durham 27th in the world (5th in the UK) for physics, and gives no rank for chemistry, mathematics, computer science, or economics/business.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shanghairanking.com/World-University-Rankings/Durham-University.html|title=Durham University|work=Academic Ranking of World Universities|accessdate=25 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe [[CWTS Leiden Ranking]], based on bibliometric indicators of research, placed Durham 89th in the world (16th in the UK) in 2018. In scientific subject areas, Durham ranked 251st in the world (35th in the UK) for biomedical and health science, 104th in the world (26th in the UK) for life and earth sciences, 389th in the world (36th in the UK) for mathematics and computer science, 76th in the world (10th in the UK) for physical sciences and engineering, and 69th in the world (11th in the UK) in social sciences and humanities.<ref name=Leiden2018/>\n\nThe [[Round University Ranking]] placed Durham 94th in the world (12th in the UK) in 2016. In certain subject areas, Durham ranked 30th in the world (8th in the UK) for the humanities, 44th in the world (12th in the UK) for social sciences, 153rd in the world (27th in the UK) for technical sciences, 191st in the world (21st in the UK) for natural sciences, 269th in the world (33rd in the UK) for life sciences and 418th in the world (61st in the UK) for medical sciences.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://roundranking.com/ranking.html|title=Round University Rankings 2016|publisher=RUR Rankings Agency|accessdate=22 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n;Employment\nIn 2017, Durham had the highest graduate employment rate of any UK university, with 97.9 per cent of its graduates in work or further study three and a half years after graduation.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Grove|first1=Jack|title=Russell Group dominates UK's graduate employment charts|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/russell-group-dominates-uk-graduate-employment-charts|accessdate=11 August 2017|work=Times Higher Education}}</ref> In 2015, Durham was placed 47th in the world (8th in the UK) in QS's pilot global employability ranking,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iu.qs.com/qs-graduate-employability-rankings-year-2016-pilot/|title=QS Graduate Employability Rankings \u2013 Year 2016 (Pilot)|publisher=QS Quacquarelli Symonds Limited|accessdate=16 February 2016}}</ref> and 8th in the UK for graduate prospects by the Times and Sunday Times 2016.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=Times Higher Education|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/carousels/top-25-uk-universities-graduate-employment|title=Top 25 UK universities for graduate employment|date=21 September 2015}}</ref> It did not, however, feature in the Times Higher Education Top 150 Global Employability rankings,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/carousels/global-employability-university-ranking-2015-results|title=Global Employability University Ranking 2015 results|date=6 November 2015|newspaper=Times Higher Education|author=Ellie Bothwell}}</ref> but was placed joint 16th in the UK for the employability of its graduates according to recruiters of the UK's major companies.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/student/news/best-uk-universities-chosen-major-employers|title=The best UK universities chosen by major employersdate=12 November 2015|newspaper=Times Higher Education|author=Carly Minsky}}</ref> The ''High Fliers Research'' UK graduate market report for 2016 placed Durham 8th in its table of universities targeted by the largest number of top employees.<ref name=highfliers2016>{{cite web|url=http://www.highfliers.co.uk/download/2016/graduate_market/GMReport16.pdf|page=33|title=The Graduate Market in 2016|publisher=High Fliers Research Limited|date=18 January 2016|accessdate=10 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n;Other indications\nIn 2013, Durham was judged to have the best quality of student life in the country in the inaugural [[Lloyds Bank]] rankings and has never (in 2015) been out of the top three, coming in third in 2014 and second in 2015.<ref>{{cite news|title=Out of 91 UK universities, Durham students have the best quality of life|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/student/news/out-of-91-uk-universities-durham-students-have-the-best-quality-of-life-8844763.html|newspaper=The Independent|date=28 September 2013|location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Durham Students top of the pile in first University Quality of Student Life Survey|url=http://www.lloydsbankinggroup.com/media/pdfs/LTSB/2013/2809_Student_Life.pdf|accessdate=3 October 2013|date=28 September 2015|publisher=Lloyds Bank|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004220307/http://www.lloydsbankinggroup.com/media/pdfs/LTSB/2013/2809_Student_Life.pdf|archivedate=4 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lloydsbankinggroup.com/Media/Press-Releases/2014/lloyds-bank/loughborough-university-races-to-the-top-of-the-lloyds-bank-quality-of-student-life-survey/|title=Loughborough University races to the top of the Lloyds Bank Quality of Student Life Survey|accessdate=4 October 2015|date=3 October 2014|publisher=Lloyd's Bank}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lloydsbankinggroup.com/Media/Press-Releases/2015/lloyds-bank/loughborough-university-retains-top-spot-in-the-2015-lloyds-bank-student-life-survey/|title=Loughborough University retains top spot in the 2015 Lloyds Bank Student Life Survey|date=21 September 2015|accessdate=4 October 2015|publisher=Lloyd's Bank}}</ref>\nThe ''Complete University Guide'' ranked Durham as the 29th safest university in England and Wales for crime in 2016, although with large differences between the two campuses: Durham City had 24.4 incidents per 1000 residents while the Queen's Campus in Stockton had 56.0 incidents per 1000 residents.<ref>{{cite web|title=Crime in University Cities|url=http://www.thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk/crime-in-university-cities/|accessdate=25 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nDurham is listed as part of the [[Sutton Trust 30]] \"most highly selective\" British universities,<ref name=\"Old school 'key to student place'\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/education/7003253.stm|title=Old school 'key to student place'|publisher=BBC |accessdate=31 January 2009 | date=20 September 2007}}</ref> and is one of the few universities to have won [[University Challenge]] more than once (1977 and 2000).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blanchflower.org/uc/winners_teams.html |title=University Challenge \u2013 Series Champions |publisher=Blanchflower.org |date=n.d.|accessdate=1 November 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Student life==\n{{See also|List of social activities at Durham University}}\n\n===Residential life===\n[[File:Great Hall.jpg|thumb|The [[University College, Durham#Great Hall|Great Hall]] at [[University College, Durham|University College]] \u2013 communal dining is traditional at most Durham colleges]]\nDurham students belong to a college for the duration of their time at the university. Most students live in their college for the first year of their undergraduate life, then choose to 'live-out' in their second year, and subsequently have the option of moving back into college for their final year, usually via a ballot system.<ref name=\"DSU: QAA Student Written Submission\">{{cite web|url= http://www.dsu.org.uk/export/sites/Durham/upload_gallery/Appendix_I_-_QAA_Student_Written_Submission.pdf|title=DSU: QAA Student Written Submission|publisher=Durham Students' Union (DSU)|accessdate=5 February 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090326202147/http://www.dsu.org.uk/export/sites/Durham/upload_gallery/Appendix_I_-_QAA_Student_Written_Submission.pdf|archivedate=26 March 2009}}</ref> The Colleges provide a key role in the pastoral care and social centre of students with each running a college tutorial system,<ref name=\"DSU: QAA Student Written Submission\"/><ref name=\"Colleges: Support Structure\">{{cite web|url= http://www.dur.ac.uk/colleges/experience/support/|title=College support structure|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=5 February 2009}}</ref> along with [[Junior Common Room|JCR]]s providing events and societies for undergraduate members, [[Middle Common Room|MCR]]s being a centre for postgraduate students and the [[Senior Common Room|SCR]]s for the college officers, fellows and tutors. These common rooms are run by an executive committee, usually headed by a President. Some colleges use other titles for the head of their JCR: Hatfield retains \"Senior Man\", having rejected a motion to move to \"JCR President\" in May 2014<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thetab.com/uk/durham/2014/05/15/hatfield-crush-senior-man-13235|title=Hatfield JCR crush motion to rename Senior Man|accessdate=3 October 2015|publisher=[[The Tab]]}}</ref> and a motion to allow the incumbent to choose between \"Senior Man\", \"Senior Woman\" or \"Senior Student\" in January 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.palatinate.org.uk/hatfield-college-jcr-rejects-motion-to-change-jcr-president-title-to-\u2018senior-student\u2019/|title=Hatfield College JCR rejects motion to change JCR President title to \u2018Senior Student\u2019|newspaper=[[Palatinate (newspaper)|Palatinate]]|date=24 January 2016|author=Charlie Taylor-Kroll}}</ref> University College voted to allow \"Senior Man\", \"Senior Woman\" or \"Senior Student\" in June 2015,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://community.dur.ac.uk/student.elections/university/index.php?results=186|publisher=University College JCR|title=University College online voting: Results|accessdate=3 October 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160201065236/https://community.dur.ac.uk/student.elections/university/index.php?results=186|archivedate=1 February 2016}}</ref> the incumbent switching to using \"Senior Student\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/university.college/about/staff/|title=Who's Who|publisher=University College|accessdate=3 October 2015}}</ref> and St Chad's uses \"Senior Man\" or \"Senior Woman\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/education-30211616|title='Sexist' job title stays at University College, Durham|date=26 November 2014|accessdate=3 October 2015|publisher=BBC}}</ref>\n\nEach college has a unique identity and a variety of facilities for students ranging from computer rooms and libraries to tennis courts and gyms.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/university.college/undergraduate/facilities/|title=University College : Facilities|publisher=Durham University}}</ref> In 2015, Durham University was voted number 1 in the UK for best university WiFi, on the review platform StudentCrowd.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.studentcrowd.com/article/3-best-universities-for-wifi-2015|title=Best Uni Awards 2015 \u2013 Wifi and Internet|author=Paul Humphreys|date=11 August 2015|work=studentcrowd.com}}</ref> Most colleges have their own sports teams and compete in the collegiate leagues (such as [[Durham College Rowing]]) and have their own theatre company and orchestra which operate parallel to the university level sports teams and organisations.<ref name=\"Colleges: Sports and societies\">{{cite web|url= http://www.dur.ac.uk/colleges/experience/sport/|title=Sports and societies|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=5 February 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Student organisations===\n[[File:Durham Union Palace Green.jpg|thumb|The [[Durham Union Society]] is the university's largest student society]]\nApproximately 200 student clubs and organisations run on Durham's campuses, covering academic, arts, culture and faith, hobbies and games, outdoors, politics, law and music interests.<ref name=\"DSU: societies\">{{cite web|url=http://www.durhamsu.com/main-menu/activities/societies|title=Societies|publisher=DSU|accessdate=15 February 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160125212006/http://www.durhamsu.com/main-menu/activities/societies|archivedate=25 January 2016}}</ref> [[Durham Students' Union]] (DSU) charters and provides most of the funding for these organisations. The DSU runs a Comedy Caf\u00e9, Fresher's Ball, Silent Discos and Vintage fashion fair.<ref name=\"DSU: Events\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dsu.org.uk/pages/events/ |title=Durham Student's Union: Events |publisher=DSU |accessdate=5 February 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090224043511/http://dsu.org.uk/pages/events/ |archivedate=24 February 2009 }}</ref> The largest independent student society in Durham is the [[Durham Union Society]], founded in 1842 as Durham's Student Debating & Union Society.\n\n===Civic engagement===\nDurham's Student Community Action (SCA) oversees 45 volunteer projects in Durham and the surrounding area.<ref name=\"DSU Handbook 2007\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dsu.org.uk/export/sites/Durham/upload_gallery/DSU_Handbook_2007.pdf|title=DAU Handbook 2007|publisher=Durham Students' Union|accessdate=5 February 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090326202139/http://www.dsu.org.uk/export/sites/Durham/upload_gallery/DSU_Handbook_2007.pdf|archivedate=26 March 2009}}</ref> Colleges often organise their own outreach and charitable activities.\n\nDurham University Charity Kommittee (or DUCK) is the university's equivalent of student's [[rag week]].<ref name=\"Community Activities\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/about/community/|title=Durham University: Community Activities|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=5 February 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100413093908/http://www.dur.ac.uk/about/community/|archivedate=13 April 2010 }}</ref> Originally set up as a week event, DUCK has become a permanent feature in raising money for local or national charities with events taking place throughout the year. Activities take place within each college, as well as centrally over the university.<ref name=\"DUCK: Get Involved!\">{{cite web|url=http://duck.dsu.org.uk/?p=involved/index|title=DUCK: Get Involved!|publisher=DUCK|accessdate=5 February 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090212201120/http://duck.dsu.org.uk/?p=involved%2Findex|archivedate=12 February 2009}}</ref> DUCK also organises expeditions to the Himalayas,<ref name=\"DUCK: Expeditions\">{{cite web|url=http://duck.dsu.org.uk/?p=expeditions/index|title=DUCK: BE ON OUR NEXT TREK!|publisher=DUCK|accessdate=5 February 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090212204828/http://duck.dsu.org.uk/?p=expeditions%2Findex|archivedate=12 February 2009}}</ref> Jordan<ref name=\"DUCK: Expeditions\"/> and Mount Kilimanjaro<ref name=\"DUCK: Expeditions\"/> to raise money as well as being involved in the university-run 'Project Sri Lanka'<ref name=\"Project Sri Lanka\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/project.srilanka/|title=Durham University: Project Sri Lanka|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=5 February 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090118163048/http://www.dur.ac.uk/project.srilanka/|archivedate=18 January 2009}}</ref> and 'Project Thailand'.<ref name=\"Project Thailand\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/project.thailand/|title=Durham University: Project Thailand|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=5 February 2009}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Dunelm3.jpg|thumb|Dunelm House, home of the [[Durham Students' Union]]]]\nTeam Durham Community Outreach is a sports community programme aimed at giving support and opportunities through the use of sport.<ref name=\"Community Activities\"/> The programme runs projects such as Summer Camps for children from the Youth Engagement Service and fostered backgrounds along with providing coaching at local schools as well as participating in sports in action.<ref name=\"Sports in Action\">{{cite web|url=http://www.teamdurham.com/community/sportinaction/|title=Team Durham: Sports in Action|publisher=Team Durham|accessdate=5 February 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Town and gown relations===\n\nThe relationship between [[town and gown|the university and the wider city]] has not always been free of tension.<ref>{{cite web |title=Council condemns \u2018insular and selfish\u2019 Durham University students |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/council-condemns-insular-andselfish-durham-university-students-kctv0rszz |website=The Times |accessdate=6 November 2018 }}</ref> University plans for expansion have also faced local opposition.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Banfield |first1=Joe |title=Students may be wrecking Durham. But the university is to blame|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2018/jun/29/students-durham-university-blame-council-selfish |website=The Guardian |accessdate=6 November 2018  |date=29 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Gaspar |first1=Clara |title=Durham University expansion plans prompt anger from local community |url=https://www.palatinate.org.uk/durham-university-expansion-plans-prompt-anger-from-local-community/ |website=Palatinate |accessdate=6 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Student media===\n''[[Palatinate (newspaper)|Palatinate]]'', Durham's independent student run fortnightly newspaper, has been continually published since 1948.<ref name=Echo>{{cite news|title=Future of student paper at risk |work=The Northern Echo |date=7 June 2005 |url=http://archive.thenorthernecho.co.uk/2005/6/7/10844.html |accessdate=28 August 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929110713/http://archive.thenorthernecho.co.uk/2005/6/7/10844.html |archivedate=29 September 2007 }}</ref> Notable former editors include [[George Alagiah]],<ref name=Echo/> [[Hunter Davies]],<ref>{{cite news|first=Jackie |last=McGlone |title=A life in the day of Hunter Davies |work=[[Scotland on Sunday]] |location=Edinburgh |date=20 August 2006 |url=http://living.scotsman.com/people.cfm?id=1212712006 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120721165449/http://living.scotsman.com/people.cfm?id=1212712006 |url-status=dead |archive-date=21 July 2012 |accessdate=28 August 2007 }}</ref> [[Piers Merchant]], [[Timothy Laurence|Sir Timothy Laurence]],<ref>{{cite news|first=Stuart |last=Qualtrough |title=People's Prince Wills may go to Durham University |work=Sunday Mirror |location=London |date=23 May 1999 |url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4161/is_19990523/ai_n14489282 |accessdate=28 August 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090211074040/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4161/is_19990523/ai_n14489282 |archivedate=11 February 2009 }}</ref> [[Jeremy Vine]]<ref name=Echo /> and [[Harold Evans]].<ref name=Echo />\n\n[[Purple Radio]] is Durham's student radio station. It broadcasts live from the [[Durham Students' Union|DSU]] 24 hours a day during term time. The station has existed since the 1980s and is a recognised DSU society. Two daily news bulletins are broadcast every weekday, as well as a Breakfast Show and an Evening Show.<ref name=\"Purple Radio Schedule\">{{cite web|url=http://www.purpleradio.co.uk/schedule|title=Purple Radio Schedule|accessdate=10 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe Bubble, founded in 2010, is an online magazine based at the university covering various subjects, including student and university news.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thebubble.org.uk/site/about|title=The Bubble|accessdate=2 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Sport===\n[[File:Durham regatta Univ College Durham v's Newcastle Uni.jpg|left|thumb|[[University College Boat Club (Durham)|University College Boat Club]] and Newcastle University racing at [[Durham Regatta]]]]\nSport at Durham is a key aspect of student life with some 92 per cent of students regularly taking part.<ref name=\"Sports Uni 2015\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/undergraduate/life/times-sport-uni-2015/|title=Durham University named The Times and Sunday Times Sports University of the Year 2015|work=The Sunday Times|date=21 September 2014|author=Zoe Thomas|accessdate=15 February 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305140224/https://www.dur.ac.uk/undergraduate/life/times-sport-uni-2015/|archive-date=5 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> As of 2018, the university caters for more than 50 different sports, organised under the umbrella name of [[Durham University Athletic Union|Team Durham]], with many being predominantly based at the Graham Sports Centre at Maiden Castle. This facility has 26 courts and pitches for sports ranging from rugby to lacrosse to netball, additional facilities include eleven boat houses and two astroturfs, a fitness studio, and a weights room.<ref>{{cite web |title=University Performance Programmes \u2013 Durham University |url=https://www.teamdurham.com/universitysport/ |website=Team Durham |accessdate=10 October 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Our Facilities \u2013 Durham University |url=https://www.teamdurham.com/facilities/ |website=Team Durham |accessdate=10 October 2018 }}</ref> The university also owns [[The Racecourse]] which has a further eight courts and pitches for cricket, rugby (union and league), squash and football.<ref name=\"Team Durham: Facilities\">{{cite web|url=http://www.teamdurham.com/about/hello/|title=Team Durham: Facilities|publisher=Team Durham|accessdate=5 February 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090302220743/http://www.teamdurham.com/about/hello/|archivedate=2 March 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe university is recognised as a [[Durham MCC University|Centre of Cricketing Excellence]] (one of only six [[MCC Universities|university centres]] to play first-class matches) by the [[England and Wales Cricket Board]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lords.org/mcc/youth-cricket/mcc-universities/ |title= MCC Universities \u2013 investing in a cricketing education |work=lords.org |date=n.d.|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref> The university also has Performance Centres for [[Rowing (sport)|rowing]], [[lacrosse]], [[tennis]] and [[fencing]].<ref name=\"Team Durham: About\">{{cite web|url=http://www.teamdurham.com/about/|title=Team Durham: About|publisher=Team Durham|accessdate=5 February 2009}}</ref>\n\nDurham has been 2nd across all sports in the [[British Universities & Colleges Sport]] (BUCS) table since 2011/12. In 2014/15 it became only the second University (after Loughborough) to pass 4000 BUCS points and the top university in the country for team sports. Both of these were repeated in 2015/16, which also saw Durham beat its own records for total BUCS scores in League and Cup competitions.<ref>{{cite web|date=26 June 2016|url=https://www.teamdurham.com/universitysport/|title=University Sport|accessdate=15 February 2015|publisher=Team Durham}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.teamdurham.com/about/directorsviews/|title=Dean's Update|accessdate=30 August 2016|publisher=Team Durham}}</ref> In rowing, it has a good record at the [[University rowing (UK)|BUCS Regatta]], having won the title for ten consecutive years (2004\u20132013) before coming second in 2014, then regaining the title in 2015<ref name=\"Stage is set for rowing showdown\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/news/newsitem/?itemno=7929|title=Stage is set for rowing showdown|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=7 May 2009}}</ref> before losing it again in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldrowing.com/news/newcastle-triumphant-2016-bucs-regatta|title= Newcastle triumphant at 2016 BUCS regatta|date=5 May 2016|website=World Rowing|accessdate=30 August 2016}}</ref> In 2017 the club finished in 7th place, from 52 ranked teams.<ref>{{cite web |title=BUCS Regatta 2017 \u2013 Overall Victor Ludorum |url=https://www.bucs.org.uk/core/core_picker/download.asp?id=35259 |accessdate=10 October 2018}}</ref> [[Durham University Boat Club]] also competes in [[Durham Regatta]] and [[the Boat Race of the North]] against Newcastle University, which ran 1997 \u2013 2010 and was revived in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thetab.com/uk/newcastle/2015/04/25/boating-hell-newcastle-vs-durham-boat-race-back-11054|title=Aboat time! Newcastle vs Durham boat race is back|publisher=[[The Tab]]|date=25 April 2015|accessdate=3 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Durham University Racecourse.JPG|thumb|[[The Racecourse]] is one of the university's main sites for sporting facilities]]\nDurham University is one of four universities to compete in the unofficial \"Doxbridge\" Tournament in Dublin, a sporting competition between Durham University, the University of Oxford, the University of Cambridge and the University of York.<ref name=\"Doxbridge\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsparty.co.uk/doxbridge/|title=Doxbridge|publisher=Sweet Chariot Ltd|accessdate=15 February 2016}}</ref> Durham colleges also compete officially with colleges from the [[University of York]] in the annual College Varsity tournament held since 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.palatinate.org.uk/?p=46289|title=Durham wins College Varsity|date=3 March 2014|accessdate=3 October 2015|work=[[Palatinate (newspaper)|Palatinate]]}}</ref> Durham won this tournament in 2014 (in York) and 2015 (in Durham) before York recorded their first victory in 2016 (in York).  Durham also competes again long-standing BUCS champions [[Loughborough University]] in the 'BUCS Varsity', a coordinated set of BUCS matches across multiple sports, and in a competition between Durham colleges and Loughborough halls of residence, both of which were organised for the first time in 2015/16. Durham won the BUCS Varsity both home and away in 2015/16 but lost the colleges' competition, held in Durham.<ref>{{cite news|work=[[Palatinate (newspaper)|Palatinate]]|date=6 May 2016|author=Matt Roberts|title= Durham denied Varsity hat-trick over Loughborough|url=http://www.palatinate.org.uk/durham-denied-varsity-hat-trick-over-loughborough/}}</ref>\n\n[[Palatinate (award)|Palatinate]]s are given to athletes who demonstrate a high standard (such as international representation) in their sport. It is similar to a [[blue (university sport)|blue]] awarded at other British universities. The award is named after the colour palatinate associated with the university.\n\n===Music and drama===\n[[File:Durham University Botanic Garden.jpg|thumb|[[Durham University Botanic Garden]]]]\nThe central body for theatre at the university is known as [[Durham Student Theatre]] (DST), with around 700 active student members throughout 27 separate, student-run theatre societies as of 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.durhamstudenttheatre.org/|title=Durham Student Theatre|accessdate=14 October 2018|publisher=Durham Student Theatre}}</ref> The Assembly Rooms is the university-owned theatre, located on [[The Bailey]], which hosts a number of student productions each term. Alongside this, student drama productions are held at Durham City's Gala Theatre (notably Durham University Light Opera Group (DULOG) and Durham Opera Ensemble (DOE), which both perform one show in the Gala every year in Epiphany term), venues around Durham University and within the colleges, [[Durham Castle]], [[Durham Cathedral]], as well as in national and international venues and the [[Edinburgh Fringe Festival]].\n\nSince 1975, the university has played host to the Durham Drama Festival which celebrates new theatrical and dramatic material written by Durham students.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.palatinate.org.uk/?p=54664|title=Durham Drama Festival 2015|work=[[Palatinate (newspaper)|Palatinate]]|accessdate=3 October 2015|date=4 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe Durham Revue is the university's [[sketch comedy]] group. Tracing its roots back to the early 1950s, and known under its current name since 1988, the group consists of six writer-performers (auditioned, interviewed and chosen each Michaelmas Term) and produces a series of shows each year. The group performs annually with [[Cambridge University]]'s [[Footlights]] and [[Oxford University]]'s [[The Oxford Revue]], as well as at the [[Edinburgh Fringe Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/experiencedurham/theatre/companies/durhamrevue/|title=Durham Revue|publisher=Durham Revue|accessdate=3 October 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160201065236/https://www.dur.ac.uk/experiencedurham/theatre/companies/durhamrevue/|archivedate=1 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nMusic is particularly marked by the Durham University Chamber Choir and Orchestral Societies (including the Palatinate Orchestra<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/palatinate.orchestra/ |title=Durham University Palatinate Orchestra |publisher=Durham University |date=n.d.|accessdate=1 November 2011}}</ref>). The Durham Cathedral Choir offers choral scholarships to male students, and several of the colleges (University, Hatfield, Hild Bede, St John's, St Chad's, St Cuthbert's, Grey and St Mary's) also offer organ and/or choral scholarships, as does the Catholic Chaplaincy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.musicdurham.org/scholarships/|accessdate=3 October 2015|publisher=Music Durham |title=Scholarships}}</ref>\n\nDurham is also home to the oldest [[Gamelan]] [[slendro]] set in the UK with an active community group and an artist in residence. The instruments are currently housed in the Grade II listed [[Durham University Observatory]].<ref>{{cite web|title=DGS Observatory|url=http://www.durhamgamelan.org.uk/where.aspx|accessdate=8 June 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130526133033/http://www.durhamgamelan.org.uk/where.aspx|archive-date=26 May 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> Recently a set tuned to peloghas been added meaning that Durham now has a complete Gamelan orchestra. In recent years, the Durham Gamelan Society has performed at several major public events such as the Gong Festivals 2011 & 2012<ref>{{cite web|title=Gong Festival 2012|url=http://gongfestival.co.uk/|accessdate=8 June 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120625122957/http://www.gongfestival.co.uk/|archive-date=25 June 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> and at the Gamelan Lokananta all night [[wayang kulit]] in celebration of York University's Gamelan Sekar Petak 30th anniversary in 2012,<ref>{{cite web|title=Gathering of the Gamelans|url=http://www.york.ac.uk/music/conferences/gathering-of-the-gamelans/ | accessdate=8 June 2012}}</ref> as well as many smaller performances for the International Students' Festival and college events.\n{{clear}}\n\n==Notable alumni==\n{{further|List of Durham University people}}\n\n[[File:General Sir Francis Richard Dannatt, KCB, CBE, MC - York 2007-09-22 (RLH).jpg|upright|thumb|General [[Richard Dannatt, Baron Dannatt|Sir Richard Dannatt]], [[Chief of the General Staff (United Kingdom)|Chief of the General Staff]]]]\n\nDurham alumni are active through organisations and events such as the annual Reunions, Dinners and Balls. There are 67 Durham associations ranging from international to college and sports affiliated groups that cater for the more than 109,000 living alumni.<ref name=\"Durham Diff Alumni\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/DARO/TheDurhamDifference.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629183326/http://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/DARO/TheDurhamDifference.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=29 June 2011 |title=The Durham Difference |publisher=Durham University |accessdate=3 April 2009 }}</ref>\n\nA number of Durham alumni have made significant contributions in the fields of government, law, science, academia, business, arts, journalism, and athletics, among others. These have included [[Justin Welby]], Archbishop of Canterbury (St John's, 1992), [[Milton Margai|Sir Milton Margai]], first prime minister of [[Sierra Leone]] (MD, 1926),<ref name=\"Sierra Leone People's Party\">{{cite web|url=http://www.slpp.ws/browse.asp?page=438|title=Sierra Leone People's Party Official Biography|publisher=Sierra Leone People's Party|accessdate=14 March 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090104142331/http://www.slpp.ws/browse.asp?page=438|archive-date=4 January 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref> the 7th Queensland Premier [[John Douglas (Queensland politician)|John Douglas]] (BA, 1850),<ref name=\"Douglas, John (1828 - 1904)\">{{cite web|url=http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A040087b.htm|title=Douglas, John (1828\u20131904) |publisher=Australian Dictionary of Biography, Volume 4, Melbourne University Press|accessdate=14 March 2009}}</ref> [[Henry Holland, 1st Viscount Knutsford]], [[Secretary of State for the Colonies]] from 1887 to 1892 (Law, 1847), [[Herbert Laming, Baron Laming]], head of the [[Harold Shipman]] inquiry and the investigation of Britain's social services following the [[death of Baby P]], (Applied Social Studies, 1960),<ref name=\"Lord Laming\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/baby-p/4977353/Lord-Laming-Renowned-Social-Worker.html |title=Lord Laming: Renowned Social Worker |work=The Daily Telegraph, 12 March 2009 |accessdate=14 March 2009 |location=London }}</ref> Dame [[Caroline Swift]], the lead counsel to the Shipman inquiry,<ref name=\"Caroline Swift\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pm.gov.uk/output/Page8467.asp |title=DBE Appointment of Caroline Swift QC and Julia Macur QC |publisher=UK Government |accessdate=14 March 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201201151/http://www.pm.gov.uk/output/Page8467.asp |archivedate=1 December 2008  }}</ref> and [[Mo Mowlam]], [[Secretary of State for Northern Ireland]] at the time of the [[Good Friday Peace Agreement]] (Sociology and Anthropology).<ref name=\"Mo Mowlam\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/news/newsitem/?itemno=3971|title=Mo Mowlam: College Principal recalls a student rebel with a love of people|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=14 March 2009}}</ref> Durham graduate [[Libby Lane]] was the first woman to be consecrated bishop in the [[Church of England]].<ref name=\"Libby Lane\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/11672347.Durham_trained_Rev_Libby_Lane_makes_history_as_Church_of_England_appoints_first_female_bishop/|title= Durham trained Rev Libby Lane makes history as Church of England appoints first female bishop |work=[[The Northern Echo]]|accessdate=17 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nDurham graduates also hold noteworthy positions in the law, including Supreme Court Justices [[Anthony Hughes, Lord Hughes of Ombersley|Lord Hughes]] (Law) and [[Jill Black, Lady Black of Derwent|Lady Black]] (Law), the President of the Family Division [[Andrew McFarlane (judge)|Sir Andrew McFarlane]] and the current Lord Chancellor [[Robert Buckland]] (Law) amongst others.\n\nWithin the military graduates include General [[Richard Dannatt, Baron Dannatt]] (Economic History), the [[Chief of the General Staff (United Kingdom)|Chief of the General Staff]], the professional head of the [[British Army]],<ref name=\"Richard Dannatt\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/defence/4269997/Head-of-Army-General-Sir-Richard-Dannatt-given-honorary-degree.html|title=Head of Army General Sir Richard Dannatt given honorary degree|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=14 March 2009 | location=London | date=16 January 2009}}</ref> Vice-Admiral [[Tim Laurence|Sir Tim Laurence]] (Geography), Chief Executive of [[Defence Estates]] and husband to [[Anne, Princess Royal|The Princess Royal]],<ref name=\"Durham Military Alumni\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/durham.first/spring08/armedforces/|title=Alumni in the Armed Forces|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=14 March 2009}}</ref> and Rear-Admiral [[Amjad Hussain]] (Engineering, 1979) highest-ranking officer from an ethnic minority in the [[British Armed Forces]].<ref name=\"Amjad Hussain\">{{cite news|url=http://news.independent.co.uk/uk/this_britain/article357835.ece |title=Admiral becomes highest-ranking officer from an ethnic minority |work=The Independent |location=London |date=15 April 2006 |accessdate=14 March 2008 |first=Arifa |last=Akbar |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071001030538/http://news.independent.co.uk/uk/this_britain/article357835.ece |archivedate=1 October 2007  }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Tim Smit (6509919409).jpg|thumb|upright|left|[[Tim Smit]], founder of the [[Eden Project]]]]\nIn academia, Durham graduates include [[John D. Barrow]] (Mathematics and Physics, 1974), winner of the [[Templeton Prize]],<ref name=\"John D. Barrow\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/physics/news/?itemno=4169&rehref=%2Fphysics%2Fnews%2Farchive%2F&resubj=%20Headlines|title=Durham graduate wins $1M prize|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=14 March 2009}}</ref> [[George Malcolm Brown|Sir George Malcolm Brown]] (Chemistry & Geology, 1950), invited by [[NASA]] to work on the [[moon rock]] samples recovered from the [[Apollo 11]] lunar mission,<ref name=\"George Malcolm Brown\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/obituary-professor-sir-malcolm-brown-1265092.html|title=Obituary: Professor Sir Malcolm Brown |work=The Independent |location=London |date=4 April 1997|accessdate=14 March 2008 | first1=Kingsley | last1=Dunham | first2=Granville | last2=Holland}}</ref> [[George Rochester]] (1926), co-discoverer of the [[kaon]] sub-atomic particle,<ref name=\"George Rochester\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/professor-george-rochester-729830.html|title=Professor George Rochester|work=The Independent |location=London |date=18 March 2002|accessdate=14 March 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080412070220/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/professor-george-rochester-729830.html |archivedate=12 April 2008}}</ref> alongside [[Harold Jeffreys|Sir Harold Jeffreys]] (Mathematics, 1919), winner of the [[Royal Society]]'s [[Copley Medal]],<ref name=\"Harold Jeffreys\">{{cite web|url=http://www-groups.dcs.st-and.ac.uk/~history/Biographies/Jeffreys.html|title=Harold Jeffreys|publisher=School of Mathematics and Statistics University of St Andrews, Scotland|accessdate=14 March 2009}}</ref> [[Kingsley Charles Dunham|Sir Kingsley Charles Dunham]] (Geology 1930) former director of the [[British Geological Survey]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Dunham, Sir Kingsley Charles (1910\u20132001) |url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/10.1093/ref:odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-75702?rskey=J0ve7q&result=1 |website=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography |accessdate=20 September 2018  }}</ref> and [[E. J. Field]], early discoverer of what are now called [[prion]]s and significant contributor to [[Multiple sclerosis|MS]] research. The current Vice-chancellor of the [[University of Wollongong]] ([[Paul Wellings (academic)|Paul Wellings]]),<ref>{{cite web| url=http://media.uow.edu.au/news/UOW116856.html|title=New Vice-Chancellor takes the helm|author=Bernie Goldie|date=3 January 2012|publisher=University of Wollongong|accessdate=5 March 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Paul Wellings\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2009/feb/24/paul-wellings-1994-group-research|title=Paul Wellings appointed as head of 1994 group|work=The Guardian |location=London |accessdate=14 March 2009 | first=Anthea | last=Lipsett | date=24 February 2009}}</ref> former Vice-chancellor of [[Cardiff University]] ([[David Grant (academic)|David Grant]]),<ref name=\"David Grant\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cardiff.ac.uk/about/whoswho/vicechancellor/index.html|title=Vice-Chancellor: Dr David Grant CBE, FREng, FIEE|publisher=Cardiff University|accessdate=14 March 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100919140628/http://cardiff.ac.uk/about/whoswho/vicechancellor/index.html|archive-date=19 September 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> and [[Chris Higgins (academic)|Chris Higgins]], former vice-chancellor of Durham, are also graduates.<ref name=\"Chris Higgins\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/news/newsitem/?itemno=5338|title=Durham welcomes new Vice Chancellor|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=14 March 2009}}</ref>\n\nSeveral alumni hold top positions in the business world. [[Richard Adams (Traidcraft)|Richard Adams]] (Sociology), founder of [[fair trade]] organisation [[Traidcraft]],<ref name=\"Richard John Adams\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/ceremonies/congregation/adams_richard.pdf|archive-url=https://www.webarchive.org.uk/wayback/archive/20160108194743/https://www.dur.ac.uk/resources/ceremonies/congregation/adams_richard.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=8 January 2016|title=Richard John Adams: Doctor of Civil Law, Durham Cathedral, 28&nbsp;June 2007|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=14 March 2009}}</ref> Paul Hawkins (PhD in Artificial Intelligence), inventor of the [[Hawk-Eye]] ball-tracking system,<ref name=\"Paul Hawkins\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/tennis/paul-hawkins-doctors-antidote-to-court-controversies-470422.html|title=Paul Hawkins: Doctor's antidote to court controversies|work=The Independent |location=London |accessdate=14 March 2009 | date=19 March 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121110022957/http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/tennis/paul-hawkins-doctors-antidote-to-court-controversies-470422.html |archivedate=10 November 2012}}</ref> Dame [[Elisabeth Hoodless]] (Sociology), former Executive Director of [[Community Service Volunteers]],<ref name=\"Elisabeth Hoodless\">{{cite web|url=http://www.csv.org.uk/News/Press+Releases/Press+Releases+Honour.htm |title=Dame Elisabeth puts lifetime achievement down to volunteers |publisher=Community Service Volunteers |accessdate=14 March 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081012002226/http://www.csv.org.uk/News/Press%2BReleases/Press%2BReleases%2BHonour.htm |archivedate=12 October 2008 }}</ref> Sir [[Nick Scheele]] (German, 1966), former President and chief operating officer of [[Ford Motor Company]],<ref name=\"Nick Scheele\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/news/newsitem/?itemno=3328|title=Men of Business and Law to receive honorary degrees|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=14 March 2009}}</ref> entrepreneur [[Brenda Lindiwe Mabaso-Chipeio]], [[David Sproxton]] (Geography, 1976), co-founder of [[Aardman Animations]] who produce [[Wallace & Gromit]],<ref name=\"David Sproxton\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dur.ac.uk/news/newsitem/?itemno=6679|title=Wallace and Gromit producer, David Sproxton, receives honorary degree|publisher=Durham University|accessdate=14 March 2009}}</ref> [[Tim Smit]] (Archaeology and Anthropology), co-founder of the [[Eden Project]] and [[David Walton (economist)|David Walton]] (Economics and Mathematics, 1984), member of the [[Bank of England]]'s [[Monetary Policy Committee (United Kingdom)|Monetary Policy Committee]].<ref name=\"David Walton\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/david-walton-405087.html|title=Obituary: David Walton|work=The Independent|location=London|accessdate=14 March 2009|date=23 June 2006|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722142744/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/david-walton-405087.html|archivedate=22 July 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Sir Harold Evans 6 Shankbone 2009 NYC.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Harold Evans|Sir Harold Evans]], Editor at Large, [[Reuters]]]]\n[[File:Jonathan Edwards olympics 2000.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Jonathan Edwards (triple jumper)|Jonathan Edwards]], [[Van Mildert College]], Physics]]\nProminent journalists and media specialists include: [[George Entwistle]], former Director-General of the BBC,<ref>{{cite news|author=John Plunkett |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2012/jul/04/george-entwistle-director-general-profile |title=BBC director general: George Entwistle profile |work=The Guardian |date=4 July 2012 |accessdate=1 June 2017}}</ref> [[Harold Evans|Sir Harold Evans]] (Politics and Economics), editor of ''[[The Sunday Times (UK)|The Sunday Times]]'' from 1967 to 1981 and ''[[The Times]]'' from 1981 to 1982, [[Nigel Farndale]] (Philosophy), ''[[Sunday Telegraph]]'' journalist, [[George Alagiah]] (Politics), presenter of the ''[[BBC News at Six]]'', [[Matthew Amroliwala]] (Law and Politics, 1984), [[BBC News]] channel presenter, [[Biddy Baxter]] (1955), former producer of ''[[Blue Peter]]'', [[Arthur Bostrom]] (BA Hons), [[Officer Crabtree]] in  ''[['Allo 'Allo!]]'', [[Nish Kumar]], stand-up comedian, [[Jamie Campbell (British documentary filmmaker)|Jamie Campbell]] (English Literature), filmmaker, [[Alastair Fothergill]] (Zoology, 1983), series producer of ''[[The Blue Planet]]'', ''[[Planet Earth (2006 TV series)|Planet Earth]]'' and the director of ''[[Earth (2007 film)|Earth]]'', [[Shelagh Fogarty]] (Modern Languages, 1988), host of the [[BBC Radio 5 Live]] breakfast show, [[Lorraine Heggessey]] (English Language & Literature), the first female Controller of [[BBC One]] and [[Chris Terrill]] (Anthropology and Geography), documentary maker, writer and adventurer. Other BBC hosts who have graduated from Durham include [[Chris Hollins]], sports presenter on [[BBC Breakfast]], [[Gabby Logan]] (Law, 1995), [[Kate Silverton]] (Psychology), [[Jeremy Vine]] (English), [[Tim Willcox]] (Spanish) and [[Nina Hossain]] (English Language and Linguistics).\n\nNoted writers include [[Edward Bradley (writer)|Edward Bradley]] author of ''[[The Adventures of Mr. Verdant Green]]'', [[Minette Walters]] (French, 1971), author of ''[[The Sculptress]]'' and ''[[The Scold's Bridle]]'', [[Graham Hancock]] (Sociology, 1973) author of ''[[The Sign and the Seal]]'', [[Tim FitzHigham]], comedian and author, [[James Kirkup]], travel writer, poet and playwright, [[Patrick Tilley]], science fiction author, and [[Lorna Hill]] (born Lorna Leatham, English, 1926), children's writer, author of the Sadlers Wells series.\n\nIn the sports realm, former England rugby captains [[Will Carling]] (Psychology),<ref name=\"Sports Alumni\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/student/into-university/az-uni-colleges/durham-university-of-458918.html|title=Durham, University of|work=The Independent |location=London |accessdate=14 March 2009 }}</ref> [[Phil de Glanville]] (Economics),<ref name=\"Sports Alumni\"/> and vice-captain [[Will Greenwood]] (Economics, 1994),<ref name=\"Sports Alumni\"/> alongside Olympic gold-medal triple jumper [[Jonathan Edwards (triple jumper)|Jonathan Edwards]] (Physics, 1987),<ref name=\"Jonathan Edwards\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/4049800.Jonathan_Edwards_to_receive_honorary_degree/|title=Durham University hands out honorary degrees|work=The Northern Echo|accessdate=14 March 2009}}</ref> Beijing Olympics Bronze-medallist rower [[Stephen Rowbotham]] (Business Economics),<ref name=\"Durham Rowers Beijing\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sportengland.org/iyr_north_east-newpage-94.htm |title=Durham Rowers in Olympics |publisher=Durham University |accessdate=14 March 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081122084043/http://www.sportengland.org/iyr_north_east-newpage-94.htm |archivedate=22 November 2008 }}</ref> London 2012 Gold-medallist rower [[Sophie Hosking]] (Chemistry and Physics),<ref>{{cite web|last=Unwin |first=Bruce |title=Olympic gold medal winner returns to Durham University |url=http://www.durhamtimes.co.uk/news/10020429.Olympic_gold_medal_winner_returns_to_her_former_university/ |work=Durham Times |date=1 November 2012 |accessdate=13 August 2013}}</ref> former England cricket captains [[Nasser Hussain]] (Geochemistry)<ref name=\"Sports Alumni\"/> and [[Andrew Strauss]] (Economics) are among the most famous.<ref name=\"Andrew Strauss\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bucs.org.uk/news.asp?itemid=2530&itemTitle=Durham+alumni+Andrew+Strauss+named+England+Test+and+One+Day+Cricket+captain&section=8&sectionTitle=News+from+BUCS|title=Durham alumni Andrew Strauss named England Test and One Day Cricket captain|publisher=BUCS|accessdate=14 March 2009}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Colleges of Durham University|Historical list of Durham University Colleges]]\n* [[List of modern universities in Europe (1801\u20131945)]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|group=\"note\"}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin|2}}\n* Brickstock, Richard. (2007) ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=eZwyC18W1fkC&printsec=frontcover&client=firefox-a Durham Castle: Fortress, Palace, College.]'' Huddersfield: Jeremy Mills Publishing. \n* Fowler, Joseph Thomas (1904), ''[https://archive.org/download/durhamuniversity00fowluoft/durhamuniversity00fowluoft.pdf Durham University: Earlier Foundations and Present Colleges]'', Kessinger Publishing\n* Heesom, Alan, (1982) ''The founding of the University of Durham'', Durham Cathedral lecture 1982 (Durham, 1982)\n* The [[Surtees Society]], (1853) [https://books.google.com/books/pdf/the_durham_.pdf?id=5d8NAAAAQAAJ&output=pdf&sig=ACfU3U2RvHWnvSDt1cR0FDm9HprARFR_6g The Durham University Calendar with Almanack], Durham: W. E. Duncan and Sons \n* Watson, Nigel (2007), ''Durham Difference: The Story of Durham University'', James & James\n* Whiting, C.E., (1932) ''The University of Durham 1832\u20131932'' (London, 1932)\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links|wikt=no|b=no|v=no|commons=Durham University}}\n* {{Official website}}\n\n{{Durham University|state=expanded}}\n{{Navboxes|list1=\n{{Universities and colleges in North East England}}\n{{Universities in the United Kingdom}}\n{{Coimbra Group}}\n{{Russell Group}}\n{{N8 Group}}\n{{Matariki Network}}\n{{stockton}}<!--Queens Campus-->\n}}\n{{coord|54.773|-1.574|display=title}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Durham University| ]]\n[[Category:Russell Group|Durham University]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1832|Durham University]]\n[[Category:Organisations based in England with royal patronage|Durham University]]\n[[Category:1832 establishments in 